WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:22.800
In the year 1618, the Castilian&nbsp;
Spaniard Garcia de Silva y Figueroa

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:30.160
was traveling through the heartlands of
Persia in what is today Iran. By then,

00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:35.760
Figueroa was about sixty-one years of&nbsp;
age, a venerable statesman who

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:44.400
had set out from Spain four years earlier&nbsp;
as an ambassador from King Philip III.

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:50.320
His mission was to meet with the Shah of&nbsp;
the Safavid Persian Empire, flatter and

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:57.920
befriend him, and encourage him to go to war&nbsp;
with their common rival, the Ottoman Empire.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:07.840
But Figueroa's embassy got off to a bad start.&nbsp;
When he arrived at the Shah's court, the Persian

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:15.440
ruler tried to entertain his guest with a display&nbsp;
of dancing girls, but the aging and pious Spaniard

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:26.160
was unimpressed. Figueroa later wrote about&nbsp;
what happened in his ambassador's report.

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:35.760
The king then told all those present that the&nbsp;
Spanish ambassador, because of his advanced age,

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:40.800
did not like watching dancing girls, and&nbsp;
turning to the ambassador, he said, “It's

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.120
no good trying to deceive us, leading us&nbsp;
to believe that it is due to your virtue,

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:50.240
when we know that the real reason is the&nbsp;
impotence of your advanced age.” At this,

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:59.200
he and the other two ambassadors&nbsp;
burst into laughter.

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:06.080
Now that he was an object of ridicule, Figueroa's&nbsp;
diplomatic aims would also come to nothing,

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:12.400
and he soon left the Shah's court,&nbsp;
despondent, with his mission in ruins.

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:19.920
The old Spaniard set out on the journey home,&nbsp;
but on his way, he consoled himself by taking

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:26.720
in some of the sights of the lands of Persia.&nbsp;
Traveling through the mountainous region of

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:36.880
the Iranian plateau, he and his guides enjoyed the&nbsp;
fruitful lands still watered by ancient aqueducts.

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:43.680
They praise the many palm trees and fruit orchards&nbsp;
that are irrigated with that good water for their

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:49.120
beauty and pleasant appearance, especially the&nbsp;
many orange and lemon trees, which produced sweet

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:55.280
lemons. These can be compared to the other ones&nbsp;
from Valencia, Spain. In fact, they may even be

00:02:55.280 --> 00:03:05.200
better. It was while traveling through&nbsp;
this pleasant region known as the Marv Dasht

00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:12.640
Plateau, along the main road between Isfahan and&nbsp;
Shiraz, that his guides recommended they stop at a

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:21.600
place that was surrounded by folklore, myths, and&nbsp;
mystery. It was a site they called Chehel Minar,

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:28.800
which in Persian means ‘the forty pillars’.&nbsp;
As they approached and Figueroa caught a

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:35.200
glimpse of it in the mouth of a wide valley,&nbsp;
he would have found out why. On the horizon

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:46.960
were the towering shapes of a great number of&nbsp;
massive stone columns reaching up into the sky.

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:55.120
After crossing the river Bramir, we traveled&nbsp;
through a beautiful valley, where the river fed

00:03:55.120 --> 00:04:01.200
many streams and ditches. Many populated villages&nbsp;
and large herds of cattle of all kinds could be

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:07.600
seen. Finally, from a distance, we could see the&nbsp;
highest of the columns or minarets of Chehel

00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:14.720
Minar, only visible through a thick forest&nbsp;
of orchards at the foot of a tall mountain.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.120
As they drew nearer, they caught sight of what

00:04:23.120 --> 00:04:33.840
lay ahead of them; a sprawling mass of impressive&nbsp;
ruins carved from massive blocks of black stone.

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:40.560
After the ambassador had eaten and rested, he&nbsp;
was filled with the desire to see this famous

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:46.160
and great structure that was so worthy of&nbsp;
examination and study, not only because

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:51.600
of its antiquity, but also because of&nbsp;
its stupendous and magnificent size,

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:55.360
especially since no one else had ever&nbsp;
written the kind of accurate and erudite

00:04:55.360 --> 00:05:04.480
description it deserved. For much&nbsp;
of that afternoon, Figueroa explored the

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:16.480
ruins of this once grand city, which must&nbsp;
have been built to a staggering scale.

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:20.480
A very thick wall made of square&nbsp;
stones enclosed a large area at the

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:25.760
foot of the mountain. It was of marvelous&nbsp;
dimensions, standing over two pikes tall,

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:31.040
having been constructed with admirable&nbsp;
symmetry and beautiful proportions. There

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:36.560
were forty-eight standing columns in all. Some of
them were seen to be broken and partially buried

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:44.720
in the ground, and big pieces of others&nbsp;
were spread around all over the plain.

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:54.080
Although much of what remained was a&nbsp;
crumbling mass of shattered stone and brick,

00:05:54.080 --> 00:06:05.520
in other places he was astonished to see how&nbsp;
well the structures had stood the test of time.

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:11.760
We climbed both stairways to find a portico&nbsp;
or entrance supported by two huge horses that

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:16.080
were constructed from white marble, each&nbsp;
of them bigger than a large elephant, with

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:21.440
enormous wings and leonine ferocity.&nbsp;
The stairway as a whole seemed to have

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:26.800
been finished just yesterday. This great&nbsp;
and wonderful structure, for incalculable

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:36.160
centuries, had resisted the ravages of time,&nbsp;
which erodes and consumes all things.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:43.920
In places, the polished stone was still so fine

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:55.840
that it even caused some confusion to one&nbsp;
particular member of their expedition.

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:00.400
The lower sections were set with slabs of black&nbsp;
stone that were so burnished and polished that

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:05.520
anyone who stepped close to it could see his&nbsp;
reflection. It happened that the ambassador's

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:11.040
dog saw its own reflection in the inner surface.&nbsp;
It began snarling and showing his teeth, and

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:16.160
since its shadow and reflection performed the same&nbsp;
actions, it attacked with great impetus and fury,

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:25.680
attempting to bite the slab and rising up on its&nbsp;
hind legs, much to the mirth of those present.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:35.440
Figueroa was a great reader of classical&nbsp;
history, and felt sure that he knew what

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:45.920
this once great city had been. It was&nbsp;
the fabled Persian capital of Persepolis.

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:53.040
After closely observing the location of its&nbsp;
beautiful and fertile countryside and the

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:58.400
proximity of the ancient Araxes River, not only&nbsp;
was there no doubt that this was once the site of

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:05.280
the great and celebrated Persepolis, but anyone who&nbsp;
sees the superb and magnificent monuments of such

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:12.160
ancient majesty can declare it to be such with&nbsp;
certainty. For its antiquity and the grandeur of

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:16.720
its perfection and the imperishability&nbsp;
of the material of which it is built,

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:24.720
Persepolis is incomparable to any of the other&nbsp;
wonders that antiquity has bequeath to us.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:33.840
Figueroa's letter home about his journey would&nbsp;
be the first written account to accurately

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:41.760
identify the ruins of Chehel Minar as the&nbsp;
ancient Persian capital. For centuries,

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:48.080
this city had stood at the heart of what was at&nbsp;
the time the largest empire the world had ever

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:58.000
seen, the empire known today as the Achaemenid,&nbsp;
or simply Persian Empire. It was a power that

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:04.960
had ruled over a vast territory nearly the&nbsp;
size of the United States today, and brought

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:12.160
countless different cultures together within&nbsp;
its borders. But for nearly two millennia, the

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:20.080
ruins of Persepolis had stood alone in the rocky&nbsp;
highlands, now a mystery wreathed with folklore and

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:42.400
legend, the names of its builders forgotten,&nbsp;
and with no one left to tell their story.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:11.120
My name is Paul Cooper, and you're listening&nbsp;
to the Fall of Civilizations podcast.

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:16.960
Each episode I look at a civilization of the&nbsp;
past that rose to glory and then collapsed

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:22.880
into the ashes of history. I want to ask,&nbsp;
what did they have in common? What led to

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:29.040
their fall, and what did it feel like to be&nbsp;
a person alive at the time who witnessed the

00:10:29.040 --> 00:10:37.280
end of their world? In this episode, I want to&nbsp;
tell the story of the Achaemenid Persian Empire.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:44.240
I want to show how this remarkable ancient power&nbsp;
sprung up from the rubble of a ruined world to

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:51.840
become the most powerful human society on earth.&nbsp;
I want to show how they raised their grand palaces

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:59.280
and monuments, and brought an unprecedented
number of people together within their borders. I want

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:06.560
to show how they came into conflict and cooperation&nbsp;
with other ancient peoples, and finally, I want to

00:11:06.560 --> 00:11:26.400
show what happened to bring the palaces of the&nbsp;
Persian kings crashing down in fire and flame.

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:34.240
The story of Persia begins in the ashes of&nbsp;
the old world, the world left behind by the

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:44.000
Assyrian Empire. As we saw in our 13th episode,&nbsp;
for much of the second and first millennia BC,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:49.120
the Assyrian Empire had been one of&nbsp;
the great powers of the ancient world.

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:55.600
They had sprung up in the northern reaches&nbsp;
of the river Tigris in Mesopotamia in what

00:11:55.600 --> 00:12:02.960
is now northern Iraq and Kurdistan, and from&nbsp;
there had expanded their military might to

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:12.240
eclipse all others. Assyria had ruled the region&nbsp;
of Mesopotamia aided by its massive armies, which

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:18.240
were equipped with iron weapons and armor,&nbsp;
and crushed all resistance to their empire.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:28.880
In 729 BC, the Assyrians were powerful enough&nbsp;
to finally conquer their greatest rival,

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:34.320
the largest and most powerful city in&nbsp;
the southern marshlands of Mesopotamia,

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:40.800
the city of Babylon, where our story begins.

00:12:40.800 --> 00:12:47.600
Babylon was at that time the world's greatest&nbsp;
metropolis. Since its founding more than a

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:54.080
thousand years earlier, it had grown to become&nbsp;
the largest city in the world at two points in its

00:12:54.080 --> 00:13:03.680
history, and was probably the first city to have&nbsp;
a population above 200,000 people. The great city

00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:10.480
of Babylon was now absorbed into the Assyrian&nbsp;
Empire, but it would always be a difficult and

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:17.520
rebellious subject. Its people were proud, and&nbsp;
belonged to an ancient lineage of independent

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:26.000
kings. The Babylonians spoke their own dialect,&nbsp;
and their god named Marduk rivaled the Assyrian

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:34.080
deities in prominence. This meant that throughout&nbsp;
the occupation of their city, Babylon's rulers

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:41.120
were always looking for their chance to rise up&nbsp;
and throw off the yoke of their Assyrian masters.

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:49.840
There was a time when the might of Assyria must&nbsp;
have looked completely unbeatable, but when the

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:57.840
fall of Assyria came, it came all at once as&nbsp;
a thunderclap, and it was the city of Babylon

00:13:57.840 --> 00:14:05.440
that proved instrumental in its collapse. After&nbsp;
the death of the last great king of Assyria,

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:12.400
Ashurbanipal, a period of weak kings and&nbsp;
civil wars followed, and during this time,

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:18.640
all of Assyria's enemies took the&nbsp;
opportunity to unite against it. In

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:24.640
the south, the Babylonians finally saw&nbsp;
their moment. They rebelled, and crowned

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:36.320
a man named Nabopolassar as the new king of an&nbsp;
independent Babylon, as one chronicle recalls.

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:40.880
On the 26th day of Arahsamna, Nabopolassar sat

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:48.720
on the throne in Babylon. This was the&nbsp;
beginning of the reign of Nabopolassar.

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:57.440
The Assyrians had dealt with Babylonian rebellions&nbsp;
before, but this time would be different. Now the

00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:05.520
rebelling Babylonians were joined by a number of&nbsp;
powerful allies. Chief among these were a hardy

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:15.840
horse rearing people known as the Medes, who lived in&nbsp;
the mountains and high plains of what is now Iran.

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:23.040
In the year 615 BC, while Assyria was&nbsp;
trying to contain the Babylonian revolt,

00:15:23.040 --> 00:15:28.240
the Medes swept down into the river&nbsp;
plains of the Assyrian Empire,

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:35.200
raiding and ravaging as they went. The&nbsp;
Assyrians were now fighting a war on two

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:44.080
fronts against two very different enemies, and&nbsp;
their mighty edifice began rapidly to crumble.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:51.200
One Babylonian carved stele, dated&nbsp;
around the middle of the 6th century

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:58.160
BC, records this alliance of Babylon and&nbsp;
the Medes, who they refer to with the name

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:06.080
Umman-manda, a name that evokes a&nbsp;
terrifying horde sent by the gods.

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:12.480
The god Marduk provided&nbsp;
Nabopolassar, king of Babylon,

00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:17.920
with help, and gave him a companion for&nbsp;
himself. The king of the Umman-manda,

00:16:17.920 --> 00:16:22.800
who has no rival, he caused to&nbsp;
come to his aid. Above and below,

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:32.160
from right and left, the Umman-manda swept like&nbsp;
a flood storm, avenging Babylon in retaliation.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:43.840
The Medes rode swiftly across the land, and&nbsp;
overwhelmed the Assyrian forces. One by one,

00:16:43.840 --> 00:16:48.800
they besieged and captured each of&nbsp;
the great Assyrian cities that for

00:16:48.800 --> 00:16:53.920
centuries had swelled with&nbsp;
the wealth of their empire.

00:16:56.080 --> 00:17:01.520
Many of Assyria's cities were destroyed&nbsp;
so utterly that they would never return

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:08.000
as centers of population; the bodies of&nbsp;
their hopeless defenders left to rot in

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:16.560
the streets and buried beneath fallen masonry,
their bones left to be covered by the sands.

00:17:18.080 --> 00:17:24.800
This event, the collapse of the Assyrian&nbsp;
Empire, was one of the swiftest and most

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:31.920
dramatic rearrangements of power in world&nbsp;
history. The largest empire on Earth had

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:44.800
been toppled in only about three years, and&nbsp;
in its wake, it left a yawning chasm.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:49.600
In dividing up the territory of&nbsp;
Assyria and the lands beyond,

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:57.040
the Medes and the Babylonians mostly&nbsp;
stuck to what they knew best.

00:17:57.040 --> 00:18:03.520
Like the Assyrians, the Babylonians were a settled&nbsp;
people who lived in villages, towns, and walled

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:10.960
cities, with sophisticated art, technology, and an&nbsp;
advanced understanding of mathematics and writing.

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:18.960
They fielded large infantry armies fed from&nbsp;
fields watered by complex irrigation systems,

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:25.520
where they grew barley, wheat, and fruit&nbsp;
orchards. They were masters of trade, and

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:31.840
their grand cities were resplendent, with goods&nbsp;
brought from all over the Eurasian landmass,

00:18:31.840 --> 00:18:38.240
carried up and down the rivers Tigris&nbsp;
and Euphrates on barges. For this reason,

00:18:38.240 --> 00:18:44.960
they happily swept north and captured many of&nbsp;
the Assyrian cities that still remained after

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:53.040
the destruction that the Medes left behind. These&nbsp;
they absorbed into a new Babylonian Empire that

00:18:53.040 --> 00:19:01.200
in size, geography, and structure looked very&nbsp;
much like the Assyrian Empire it had replaced.

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:09.200
But the rocky mountains to the north&nbsp;
and East, they left to the hardy Medes.

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:12.960
The Medes were in fact only one of countless

00:19:12.960 --> 00:19:24.240
peoples who had lived for millennia in the rocky&nbsp;
highlands of Iran's Zagros Mountains.

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:35.920
Beginning around 100 million years ago,&nbsp;
the Arabian tectonic plate began driving

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:41.440
northwards into the Eurasian Plate, and&nbsp;
over the next tens of millions of years,

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:47.200
the constant pressure bent and buckled&nbsp;
the land of the Eurasian side in what

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:54.640
geologists call a fold and thrust zone.&nbsp;
Today, this landscape is known as the

00:19:54.640 --> 00:20:02.640
Iranian plateau. At its southern edge,&nbsp;
it looks like a piece of rumpled fabric,

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:12.000
a series of alternating mountain ridges and deep&nbsp;
valleys that are known as the Zagros Mountains.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:19.760
The region of the South Zagros would become&nbsp;
known as Pars, and it is from this word that the

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:30.400
name Persia would derive. In the late 4th century&nbsp;
BC, the Greek historian Hieronymus of Cardia wrote

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:38.160
the following description of the landscape&nbsp;
of Persia. High land, blessed with a healthy

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:43.200
climate and full of the fruits appropriate to&nbsp;
the season. There were glens heavily wooded

00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:50.400
and shady cultivated trees of various kinds in&nbsp;
parks, and also naturally converging glades and

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:56.240
hills of trees of every sort, and streams&nbsp;
of water, so that travelers lingered with

00:20:56.240 --> 00:21:05.760
delight in places pleasantly inviting repose. Also,&nbsp;
there was an abundance of cattle of every kind.

00:21:05.760 --> 00:21:12.880
Through these mountains cut an ancient and&nbsp;
well-used highway later known as the Khorasan

00:21:12.880 --> 00:21:22.640
Road. The word Khorasan means ‘sunrise’, since this&nbsp;
highway led to the East and the regions where the

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:32.720
sun rose, and ultimately to the vast deserts&nbsp;
and arid grasslands of the Eurasian Steppe. As

00:21:32.720 --> 00:21:39.840
it would be for much of human history, the steppe&nbsp;
was then home to great numbers of nomadic horse-

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:46.160
-riding peoples who lived by herding cattle and&nbsp;
other animals, and moving from place to place

00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:55.360
to find ever newer pastures. Over the millennia,&nbsp;
countless different peoples had passed along it,

00:21:55.360 --> 00:22:01.200
moving out of the great steppe and into&nbsp;
the shady valleys of Northern Iran.

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:10.160
The first known of these people arrived more than&nbsp;
4,000 years ago, and called themselves the Ariya,

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:19.680
a word that in old Iranian languages likely meant&nbsp;
‘noble’ or ‘lord’. They came from a vast area of

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:31.040
Central Asia known in Sanskrit as Aaryaavarta, or ‘the
home of the Ariyan people’. Today, the word Ariyan still

00:22:31.040 --> 00:22:41.280
forms the etymological root of the modern name&nbsp;
of the nation today, Iran. Alongside these Ariya

00:22:41.280 --> 00:22:50.800
came further waves of migrations from the steppe&nbsp;
into the sheltered hills and valleys of Persia.

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:57.200
While much of the interior of Iran is&nbsp;
characterized by vast sand dune deserts,

00:22:57.200 --> 00:23:03.520
the mountainous regions along the Caspian&nbsp;
Sea are exceedingly green, forested with oak,

00:23:03.520 --> 00:23:11.280
and many of the highland plateaus are&nbsp;
well watered and lined with poplar trees.

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:19.440
Alongside these Ariya came further waves of&nbsp;
migration into these sheltered hills and valleys.

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:25.600
As a group, these people are today referred&nbsp;
to as the Proto-Iranians, and they spoke

00:23:25.600 --> 00:23:32.560
many different related Iranian languages.&nbsp;
Among them, Old Avestan, one of the oldest

00:23:32.560 --> 00:23:39.840
preserved languages in the Indo-European family.&nbsp;
Because this is the same family as English,

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:46.240
we can actually find a lot of linguistic&nbsp;
similarity with our own language. For instance,

00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:58.400
the old Avestan word for daughter is ‘dugedar’. Mother&nbsp;
was ‘maater’, and their word for brother was ‘brater’.

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:06.320
These Proto-Iranians settled all over Central&nbsp;
Asia, from Afghanistan and Pakistan to the hills

00:24:06.320 --> 00:24:13.040
of Iran, and everywhere they went they&nbsp;
developed a wide range of cultures, all

00:24:13.040 --> 00:24:20.880
speaking related languages. Among these&nbsp;
people were the Bahtrees or Bactrians,

00:24:20.880 --> 00:24:26.080
the Sugoda or Sogdians, the&nbsp;
Parthava or Parthians,

00:24:26.080 --> 00:24:37.600
and importantly for our story, in the west of&nbsp;
the Iranian plateau appeared the Maada, or Medes.

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:44.000
While the Babylonians were a centralized and&nbsp;
stratified kingdom, with a king at the top,

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:49.040
officials beneath, and priests and&nbsp;
administrators running the empire,

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:56.480
the Medes were likely more of a loose collection of&nbsp;
tribes bound together in a system of alliances,

00:24:56.480 --> 00:25:03.520
blood oaths, and relationships of marriage.&nbsp;
Assyrian records particularly mention the

00:25:03.520 --> 00:25:11.600
skill of the Medes in horseback riding, and Assyrian&nbsp;
sources always mention with pride the many fine

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:19.040
horses they seized whenever they raided the Median&nbsp;
lands, as this inscription by the Assyrian King

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:29.440
Tiglath-Pileser III shows. In my ninth regal year,&nbsp;
I ordered my armies to march against the Medes.

00:25:29.440 --> 00:25:35.680
I conquered their cities, defeated them,&nbsp;
and took their spoil: 130 horses from

00:25:35.680 --> 00:25:45.120
Bit Ishtar and its districts; 120 horses from&nbsp;
the cities of Gini-zinanu, Sadbat, Sisad; 100

00:25:45.120 --> 00:26:02.320
horses from Upash of Bit Kapsi, 100 horses of Ushru&nbsp;
of Nikisi, 100 horses at Ugsatar and Bardada.

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:09.760
The Assyrians had long put down the Medes with these&nbsp;
kinds of raids, but now with the Assyrian Empire

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:16.960
fallen, the Medes were free to expand. They had&nbsp;
been living and thriving in the mountains for

00:26:16.960 --> 00:26:24.560
centuries, and so, while the Babylonians took the&nbsp;
fertile riverlands of Mesopotamia, the Medes had

00:26:24.560 --> 00:26:31.840
free reign over the hills and mountains in a broad&nbsp;
stretch of what is now Iran, Azerbaijan, Syria,

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:40.400
and Turkey. It's not clear the exact geographic&nbsp;
bounds of their empire or how centralized it ever

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:47.120
was, but of all the peoples of the region, they&nbsp;
were the greatest rival to the power of Babylon.

00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:55.840
So, this is the world as we begin our story.&nbsp;
In the fertile lowlands of Mesopotamia, the

00:26:55.840 --> 00:27:03.040
new Babylonian Empire was just beginning to find&nbsp;
its feet as an imperial power, and in the rocky

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:11.600
mountains to the north and east were the loose&nbsp;
tribal confederation of the horse-rearing Medes.

00:27:11.600 --> 00:27:18.800
This was a world of new and fragile powers;&nbsp;
unstable, uncertain, and now increasingly

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:29.200
paranoid, but for the right man, it could also be&nbsp;
a world for the taking. It was into this landscape,

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:36.960
around the year 600 BC, that a man was born who&nbsp;
would shake up this fragile equilibrium and change

00:27:36.960 --> 00:27:45.680
the course of history. His name in Old Persian&nbsp;
was Kuurush, but he has gone down in history by

00:27:45.680 --> 00:28:07.760
the name given to him by the Greeks, Cyrus, and&nbsp;
he would come to be known as Cyrus the Great.

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:21.040
Cyrus or Kuurush was born into a family that&nbsp;
ruled the province of Anshan in the Zagros

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:29.440
Mountains in southwestern Iran. The province&nbsp;
was centered around the ancient city of Anshan,

00:28:29.440 --> 00:28:37.120
which had once been the original homeland of&nbsp;
the people of Elam, an old and powerful society.

00:28:38.960 --> 00:28:46.160
But Elam had been all but destroyed by the&nbsp;
Assyrian Empire in a cataclysmic war only

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:56.560
fifty years or so earlier, as one tablet written&nbsp;
by the Assyrian king Ashurbanipal describes.

00:28:56.560 --> 00:29:03.840
The great holy city, abode of their gods,&nbsp;
seat of their mysteries, I conquered. I

00:29:03.840 --> 00:29:12.160
entered its palaces. I destroyed the ziggurat. I&nbsp;
smashed its shining copper horns. I reduced the

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:22.400
temples of Elam to naught. Their gods and goddesses&nbsp;
I scattered to the winds. After this destruction,

00:29:22.400 --> 00:29:30.320
what had once been a united Elamite kingdom&nbsp;
fractured. Now the city of Anshan stood in a

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:40.240
state of ruin, its population much reduced from&nbsp;
its former glory. Into this wasted land, sometime

00:29:40.240 --> 00:29:48.640
over the preceding century, a number of nomadic&nbsp;
Iranian peoples had migrated from the north.

00:29:48.640 --> 00:29:54.960
They were cultural and linguistic cousins&nbsp;
to the Medes, and agreed to swear allegiance

00:29:54.960 --> 00:30:01.040
to the Median king, likely offering to&nbsp;
pay him tribute and fight for him in

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:10.240
times of war. Archaeology shows them living&nbsp;
a semi-nomadic lifestyle among the ruins,

00:30:10.240 --> 00:30:17.600
pitching their tents among the fallen columns and&nbsp;
crumbling brick walls of the old Elamite capital.

00:30:20.480 --> 00:30:26.880
Since their arrival, these Iranian peoples&nbsp;
intermarried and merged with what remained

00:30:26.880 --> 00:30:33.760
of the local Elamites, adopting some of&nbsp;
their ancient dress and customs, and there

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:40.800
they formed a new hybrid culture, one that&nbsp;
was half nomadic and half belonging to the

00:30:40.800 --> 00:30:47.760
ancient devastated civilization of Elam.&nbsp;
The three major tribes that made up these

00:30:47.760 --> 00:30:56.560
people were the Maspiya, the Marafiyah, and the&nbsp;
Parsagad. These were the people that today we

00:30:56.560 --> 00:31:11.440
call the Persians, and it was into this&nbsp;
society that the baby boy Cyrus was born.

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:25.200
It's worth pausing here and mentioning that we&nbsp;
know very little for sure about the early life

00:31:25.200 --> 00:31:32.960
of Cyrus. His is a childhood that&nbsp;
is wreathed in myth and mystery.

00:31:34.080 --> 00:31:39.520
That's because for much of the more than two&nbsp;
millennia since the Persian Empire flourished,

00:31:39.520 --> 00:31:45.040
their story has been told largely by&nbsp;
another people, a people who at times

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:52.320
admired and emulated them, and at others hated&nbsp;
and feared them, and against whom they fought

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:58.800
many bitter wars. These were the people who&nbsp;
lived in the rocky islands and mountainous

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:06.000
mainlands where the Mediterranean meets&nbsp;
the Black Sea, the Greeks, and one Greek in

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:16.960
particular who has been given the name the&nbsp;
Father of History. His name was Herodotus.

00:32:16.960 --> 00:32:24.880
Herodotus was born in the city of Halicarnassus, now&nbsp;
the Turkish port town of Bodrum, around the year

00:32:24.880 --> 00:32:34.960
485 BC, more than a hundred years after the birth of&nbsp;
Cyrus the Great. He was a Greek, but this wasn't

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:42.640
at all a simple identity. Greece was at that&nbsp;
time divided between clusters of about a thousand

00:32:42.640 --> 00:32:50.400
independent city-states, speaking dialects&nbsp;
including Ionian, Dorian, Attic and Aeolian,

00:32:50.400 --> 00:32:58.880
and all constantly warring amongst themselves.&nbsp;
The writer Plato famously describes the Greek

00:32:58.880 --> 00:33:07.600
cities like so. The earth is very large, and we&nbsp;
who dwell between the pillars of Hercules and

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:17.040
the river Phasis live in a small part of it around&nbsp;
the sea, like ants or frogs about a pond. But these

00:33:17.040 --> 00:33:24.880
cities were united by a shared culture, language,&nbsp;
and reverence for a shared pantheon of gods.

00:33:26.160 --> 00:33:36.160
When he reached the age of about thirty, Herodotus&nbsp;
felt a calling to travel. Around the year 454 BC,

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:42.800
he set out from his home of Halicarnassus and&nbsp;
traveled to Egypt and Libya, then through

00:33:42.800 --> 00:33:50.640
Palestine to the Phoenician city of Tyre, and after&nbsp;
that, down the river Euphrates, possibly as far as

00:33:50.640 --> 00:33:58.480
Babylon. Everywhere he went, he asked people&nbsp;
what they knew of the past of their region,

00:33:58.480 --> 00:34:05.920
and he wrote down everything he saw and heard&nbsp;
as he went. These accounts he compiled into

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:15.120
nine books he called Historiai, which in ancient&nbsp;
Greek meant ‘researches’ or ‘inquiries’, but is the

00:34:15.120 --> 00:34:27.520
origin of our word ‘history’. In the introduction to&nbsp;
his work, Herodotus explains what motivated him.

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:34.320
Herodotus of Halicarnassus hereby publishes&nbsp;
the results of his inquiries,

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:39.280
hoping to do two things; to preserve&nbsp;
the memory of the past by putting on

00:34:39.280 --> 00:34:44.480
record the astonishing achievements&nbsp;
both of the Greek and the non-Greek

00:34:44.480 --> 00:34:53.120
peoples, and more particularly to show&nbsp;
how the two races came into conflict.

00:34:53.120 --> 00:34:59.440
There was no publishing industry in ancient&nbsp;
Greece, no printing press or mass production

00:34:59.440 --> 00:35:06.880
of books, and so, Herodotus wrote his work to&nbsp;
be read aloud to audiences of citizens, often

00:35:06.880 --> 00:35:14.320
at popular festivals. One account by the&nbsp;
writer Lucian claims that Herodotus first

00:35:14.320 --> 00:35:23.280
debuted his histories by reading them aloud&nbsp;
at the Olympic games to a rapt audience.

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:27.840
The great Olympian games were at&nbsp;
hand, and Herodotus thought this

00:35:27.840 --> 00:35:33.840
the opportunity he had been hoping for. He&nbsp;
waited for a packed audience to assemble,

00:35:33.840 --> 00:35:39.920
one containing the most eminent men from all&nbsp;
Greece. He appeared in the temple chamber,

00:35:39.920 --> 00:35:46.160
presenting himself as a competitor for an&nbsp;
Olympic honor. Then he recited his histories,

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:51.920
and so bewitched his audience that his books were&nbsp;
called after the muses, for they, too, were nine in

00:35:51.920 --> 00:35:58.480
number. By this time, he was much better known&nbsp;
than the Olympic victors themselves. He had

00:35:58.480 --> 00:36:08.480
only to appear, and he was pointed out; “That is that&nbsp;
Herodotus who wrote the tale of the Persian Wars.”

00:36:08.480 --> 00:36:15.040
Perhaps due to this need to captivate a crowd,&nbsp;
Herodotus was a writer who brought his stories

00:36:15.040 --> 00:36:22.160
to life in vivid color, full of dramatic&nbsp;
characters, strange lands, gory murders,

00:36:22.160 --> 00:36:27.040
dream visions and prophecies, and&nbsp;
sometimes fantastical creatures.

00:36:27.920 --> 00:36:35.920
Even for some ancient Greeks, Herodotus' wild&nbsp;
tales went too far. Plutarch would later write

00:36:35.920 --> 00:36:43.520
a blistering essay entitled On the Malice of&nbsp;
Herodotus, tearing apart much of his histories,

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:49.520
and the writer Ctesias, himself also a source&nbsp;
on the Persian Empire, supposedly rubbished

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:58.240
many of Herodotus' claims, too, as related by the&nbsp;
chronicler Photius. He differs almost entirely

00:36:58.240 --> 00:37:07.440
from Herodotus, whom he accuses of falsehood in&nbsp;
many passages, and calls an inventor of fables.

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:15.920
But historians generally consider Ctesias even&nbsp;
less reliable than Herodotus. Even worse still

00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:23.840
is Xenophon's biography of Cyrus the Great, titled&nbsp;
Cyropaedia, which is best described as a piece

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:30.720
of fanfiction, in which the Greek soldier and&nbsp;
writer uses Cyrus as a blank slate onto which

00:37:30.720 --> 00:37:38.080
he can project a fictional version of an&nbsp;
idealized king. But for better or worse,

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:43.840
for many of the events that follow, Herodotus&nbsp;
is the only source we have available.

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:52.640
That's because in the light of history, the&nbsp;
Persians themselves are all but silent. The

00:37:52.640 --> 00:38:00.240
Persians never wrote down the kind of narrative&nbsp;
histories that made Herodotus famous. For learning

00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:06.480
about their past, they relied on a cast&nbsp;
of oral storytellers or singers who would

00:38:06.480 --> 00:38:13.440
regale their people with stories of the old&nbsp;
times, as the Greek writer Strabo records.

00:38:15.600 --> 00:38:22.160
As teachers of learning, they use the wisest&nbsp;
men who weave in legends in order to make it

00:38:22.160 --> 00:38:33.200
useful. Both with and without song, they recite&nbsp;
the deeds of the gods and the noblest men.

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:40.000
Just like Herodotus, these tales were designed&nbsp;
to be read out loud to an audience, but instead

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:45.680
of writing them down, their storytellers&nbsp;
simply remembered them using astonishing

00:38:45.680 --> 00:38:52.880
feats of memory. These tales they would have&nbsp;
passed on to one another by word of mouth, so

00:38:52.880 --> 00:38:59.840
long as the tradition of storytellers continued,
but for this reason, the Persians are not able to

00:38:59.840 --> 00:39:08.000
tell their own story in the light of history.&nbsp;
The historian Lloyd Llewellyn-Jones puts the

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:16.000
dilemma for historians bluntly. We cannot believe&nbsp;
much of what Herodotus says, and yet we cannot

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:22.160
do without him. Some historical truths about&nbsp;
the Persians may well lie hidden in Herodotus,

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:30.000
but one needs to dig deep through the&nbsp;
layers of fantasy and fiction to find them.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:35.680
In the end, trying to glean the truth&nbsp;
about this very ancient past can feel

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:40.880
like exploring the depths of the deep&nbsp;
ocean, where a single beam of light might

00:39:40.880 --> 00:39:46.160
illuminate a whole ecosystem or an&nbsp;
undiscovered species living down

00:39:46.160 --> 00:39:55.840
in the depths, but elsewhere in all&nbsp;
directions, there is only darkness.

00:40:04.880 --> 00:40:12.160
Like many momentous figures of this time, such&nbsp;
fantasy and fiction completely shrouds the early

00:40:12.160 --> 00:40:20.320
life of Cyrus the Great. What we know for sure&nbsp;
is that Cyrus was born into a royal family.

00:40:20.960 --> 00:40:28.160
He was the son of a Persian ruler named&nbsp;
King Cambyses I of Anshan and possibly

00:40:28.160 --> 00:40:36.640
his wife Mandane, who was reportedly a Mede.&nbsp;
As such, Cyrus may have grown up speaking

00:40:36.640 --> 00:40:45.600
both Old Persian and his mother's tongue of&nbsp;
Median. His mother Mandane was also royalty.

00:40:46.160 --> 00:40:53.600
She was the daughter of the ruling king of the&nbsp;
Medes, a man named Astyages, who all the tribes of

00:40:53.600 --> 00:41:02.320
the Persians swore loyalty to. As such, Cyrus was&nbsp;
likely born the immediate heir to the province of

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:10.240
Anshan, and, through his mother, a distant heir&nbsp;
to the throne of the entire Median Empire, a

00:41:10.240 --> 00:41:16.480
unique situation that his mother would no doubt&nbsp;
have reminded him of many times throughout his

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:27.680
childhood. One legendary account of Cyrus'&nbsp;
birth and upbringing is given by Herodotus.

00:41:27.680 --> 00:41:35.520
The first year after the marriage of his daughter,&nbsp;
Astyages saw a vision. A vine appeared to spring

00:41:35.520 --> 00:41:44.160
from his daughter, which overspread all Asia. On&nbsp;
this occasion, also he consulted his interpreters.

00:41:44.160 --> 00:41:51.840
The result was that he sent for his daughter from&nbsp;
Persia. When the time of her delivery approached,

00:41:51.840 --> 00:41:59.040
the Magi had declared the vision to intimate that&nbsp;
the child of his daughter should supplant him

00:41:59.040 --> 00:42:08.160
on the throne. On her arrival, he kept a strict&nbsp;
watch over her, intending to destroy her child.

00:42:11.680 --> 00:42:17.760
Unable to kill the small baby himself,&nbsp;
Astyages enlists the help of a general

00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:24.400
named Harpagus, and tells him to take the&nbsp;
baby Cyrus out into the wilds, and there

00:42:24.400 --> 00:42:33.600
leave him in the open to die. But Harpagus&nbsp;
takes pity on the child and lets him live.

00:42:34.800 --> 00:42:42.880
He instantly sent for a herdsman who, as he knew,&nbsp;
pursued his occupation in a place among mountains,

00:42:42.880 --> 00:42:50.400
frequented by savage beasts. When the herdsman&nbsp;
had received his orders, he took the child and

00:42:50.400 --> 00:43:00.640
returned to his cottage. From here, this fairy&nbsp;
tale unfolds with a colorful brutality. When

00:43:00.640 --> 00:43:06.880
the boy's identity is finally discovered,&nbsp;
the king Astyages is enraged, and realizes

00:43:06.880 --> 00:43:14.720
that the general Harpagus has betrayed him. As&nbsp;
punishment, he orders that Harpagus' son is to

00:43:14.720 --> 00:43:25.360
be secretly killed, then he invites the general to&nbsp;
a banquet at which he puts on a lurid spectacle.

00:43:25.360 --> 00:43:33.360
Before the rest, as well as before Astyages
himself, dishes of mutton were placed.

00:43:33.360 --> 00:43:40.800
But to Harpagus, all the body of his son was&nbsp;
served, except the head and the extremities,

00:43:40.800 --> 00:43:49.520
which were kept apart in a covered basket. After&nbsp;
he seemed well satisfied, Astyages asked him how he

00:43:49.520 --> 00:43:56.480
liked his fare. Harpagus expressed himself greatly&nbsp;
delighted. The attendants then brought him the

00:43:56.480 --> 00:44:03.440
basket which contained the head and extremities of&nbsp;
his child, and desired him to help himself to what

00:44:03.440 --> 00:44:11.120
he thought proper. Harpagus uncovered the vessel&nbsp;
and beheld the remains of his son. He continued,

00:44:11.120 --> 00:44:20.080
however, master of himself and betrayed no unusual&nbsp;
emotions. When Astyages inquired if he knew of

00:44:20.080 --> 00:44:26.160
what flesh he had eaten, he acknowledged&nbsp;
that he did, and that the king's will was

00:44:26.160 --> 00:44:33.200
always pleasing to him. Saying this, he took the&nbsp;
remains of the body and returned to his house,

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:44.640
meaning, as I suppose, to bury them together.&nbsp;
Astyages thus revenged himself upon Harpagus.

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:48.080
Despite taking this brutal revenge on his general,

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:56.080
Astyages’ court priests or Magi convinced&nbsp;
the Median king not to kill Cyrus and to let

00:44:56.080 --> 00:45:14.400
him go, but the general Harpagus would&nbsp;
never forget what the king had done.

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:20.000
This story would no doubt have thrilled&nbsp;
Herodotus’ audience as he read it out to them,

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:27.120
but we can be relatively sure that it is a piece&nbsp;
of mythology. The trope of the abandoned child

00:45:27.120 --> 00:45:34.080
is one that reoccurs throughout folklore and&nbsp;
myth, from the Greek story of Oedipus to the

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:42.480
Akkadian King Sargon to Moses and the fairy&nbsp;
tale Snow White. The story of the king's vision

00:45:42.480 --> 00:45:49.600
is another theme that often occurs in the early&nbsp;
lives of great men, and perhaps most famously in

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:57.200
the Gospel of Matthew, when King Herod orders all&nbsp;
the baby boys in Jerusalem to be killed when told

00:45:57.200 --> 00:46:04.640
of the birth of Jesus, and the most colorful&nbsp;
and bloodthirsty part, the revenge taken by

00:46:04.640 --> 00:46:10.640
tricking someone into eating the flesh of their&nbsp;
loved ones also occurs throughout mythology

00:46:10.640 --> 00:46:17.120
and folklore, featuring, for instance, in&nbsp;
the sixth book of Ovid's Metamorphosis,

00:46:17.120 --> 00:46:25.200
which then inspired Shakespeare's bloodthirsty&nbsp;
play, Titus Andronicus. For all these reasons,

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:31.440
it's safe to assume that this story of Cyrus'&nbsp;
early life is a work of literature rather than

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:38.640
fact, but I include it to give a sense of the&nbsp;
kinds of stories that constantly swirled around

00:46:38.640 --> 00:46:45.200
the life of this enigmatic character, as an&nbsp;
example of why the accounts of Herodotus need

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:52.960
to be treated carefully as we go forward, and of&nbsp;
course, because no one can resist a good story.

00:47:05.600 --> 00:47:13.600
The rest of what we know about Cyrus' life&nbsp;
can be gleaned in fragments. The Greek writer

00:47:13.600 --> 00:47:21.920
Xenophon records what Persians some centuries later&nbsp;
still remembered about the character of Cyrus.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:31.440
Even to this day, the barbarians tell in story and&nbsp;
in song that Cyrus was most handsome in person,

00:47:31.440 --> 00:47:37.360
most generous of heart, most devoted&nbsp;
to learning, and most ambitious,

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:44.800
so that he endured all sorts of labor and faced&nbsp;
all sorts of danger for the sake of praise.

00:47:44.800 --> 00:47:49.600
As a boy, the young Cyrus would have&nbsp;
been raised with all the skills needed

00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:55.600
by a man of the Persian royal line.&nbsp;
The first five years of a boy's life

00:47:55.600 --> 00:48:04.480
he would spend with his mother and the other&nbsp;
women of the tribe, as Herodotus describes.

00:48:04.480 --> 00:48:11.920
Until his fifth year, his father does not lay eyes&nbsp;
on the boy, who spends his time with the woman.

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:20.720
This is done so that if he dies during his&nbsp;
upbringing, he will not distress his father.

00:48:20.720 --> 00:48:26.640
During this time, his mother would have cared for&nbsp;
her son, taught him the language and the songs of

00:48:26.640 --> 00:48:33.600
her people, and all the while must have looked at&nbsp;
her little son growing, and wondered whether one

00:48:33.600 --> 00:48:42.080
day he might be destined for great things. But&nbsp;
after that, the boy was handed over to his father

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:51.120
and taught the ways of men. Although our typical&nbsp;
impression of Persian royalty, derived largely from

00:48:51.120 --> 00:48:57.680
Greek sources, is one of luxury and decadence,&nbsp;
in fact the early life of Cyrus would have

00:48:57.680 --> 00:49:05.920
been quite different. The Persians were a hardy&nbsp;
pastoral people who survived by herding cattle,

00:49:05.920 --> 00:49:12.320
hunting on horseback with a bow and arrow and&nbsp;
with trained hawks, and these are all the skills

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:20.800
that the young Cyrus would have learned, as the&nbsp;
Greek writer Strabo recounts. From age five to twenty-five,

00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:25.040
they are trained to shoot with the bow,&nbsp;
handle the spear, ride on horseback,

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:30.560
and speak the truth. They gather the boys in one&nbsp;
place, after rousing them before dawn with the

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:35.920
noise of a bronze instrument, and order them to&nbsp;
follow in a race after marking out a distance of thirty

00:49:35.920 --> 00:49:45.920
to forty stadia. Strabo records the broad education&nbsp;
that a Persian prince was required to absorb.

00:49:46.880 --> 00:49:53.440
They train them in speaking loudly, how to breathe&nbsp;
and use their lungs, and to endure heat and cold

00:49:53.440 --> 00:50:00.240
and rain, and to cross torrents, and also to herd&nbsp;
flocks and live outdoors, surviving on wild fruit,

00:50:00.240 --> 00:50:08.000
terebinth, acorns, wild pears. Their daily diet,&nbsp;
after exercising, consists of bread, barley,

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:15.040
cardamom, grains of salt, and baked or boiled&nbsp;
meat, and water to drink. They hunt by hurling

00:50:15.040 --> 00:50:21.520
spears from horseback, and with bows and lassos.&nbsp;
Towards evening they learn to cultivate plants,

00:50:21.520 --> 00:50:26.960
how to cut and collect roots, how to make&nbsp;
weapons, and the technique of making linen cloth

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:35.760
and hunter's nets. But while the Persians still&nbsp;
lived a relatively humble and hardy existence,

00:50:35.760 --> 00:50:42.320
the later Greek writer Xenophon records that&nbsp;
by this time the Medes were quite different.

00:50:44.480 --> 00:50:51.840
Cyrus noticed that his grandfather Astyages was&nbsp;
wearing makeup, with eyes outlined, color rubbed on

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:59.520
his face, and false hair, as was the Median fashion.&nbsp;
All this is Median, as are the purple tunics and

00:50:59.520 --> 00:51:05.120
sleeved coats, the necklaces worn around the&nbsp;
neck and the bracelets on their wrists, while

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:11.600
the Persians, even now in their homes, have&nbsp;
simpler clothes and a more humble lifestyle.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:20.160
When Cyrus was grown, he succeeded his father&nbsp;
as the ruler of the Persian tribe of the

00:51:20.160 --> 00:51:26.160
Pasargad, and it's then that he found himself&nbsp;
coming into conflict with his grandfather,

00:51:26.160 --> 00:51:35.120
the king of the Medes, Astyages. The exact details&nbsp;
of this conflict we can never know, but it's

00:51:35.120 --> 00:51:44.080
clear that Cyrus saw his moment. He gathered the&nbsp;
tribes of the Persians around him. The Pasargadae,

00:51:44.080 --> 00:51:51.760
Maraphiya, the Masapiya, the Derusiad, Germaniya,&nbsp;
Dai, Mardi, and Sagartiya, all of them united by

00:51:51.760 --> 00:52:00.480
their language and shared culture. Herodotus&nbsp;
imagines Cyrus giving a rousing speech.

00:52:01.920 --> 00:52:06.400
Cyrus collected and slaughtered&nbsp;
all his father's goats, sheep,

00:52:06.400 --> 00:52:13.040
and oxen in preparation for entertaining the&nbsp;
whole Persian army at a banquet, together with

00:52:13.040 --> 00:52:18.480
the best wine and bread he could procure.&nbsp;
The next day the guests assembled, and

00:52:18.480 --> 00:52:26.080
were told to sit down on the grass and enjoy&nbsp;
themselves. "Men of Persia," he exclaimed,

00:52:26.080 --> 00:52:34.000
"you are the arbiters of your own fortune. My&nbsp;
voice is the voice of freedom. I am the instrument

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:44.240
of your prosperity. Decline all future obedience&nbsp;
to Astyages.” The Persians, who had long spurned at

00:52:44.240 --> 00:52:53.280
the yoke imposed on them, were glad of such a&nbsp;
leader, and ardently obeyed the call of liberty.

00:52:55.040 --> 00:53:05.520
All the tribes of the Persian peoples now united&nbsp;
around Cyrus. Astyages was naturally enraged. He

00:53:05.520 --> 00:53:10.320
ordered that all his court soothsayers,&nbsp;
who had long ago convinced him to spare

00:53:10.320 --> 00:53:17.680
and release Cyrus, should be crucified. Then,&nbsp;
with their screams still echoing in his ears,

00:53:17.680 --> 00:53:25.440
he gathered his armies and marched out to meet&nbsp;
the Persian upstart. As he marched, he sent out

00:53:25.440 --> 00:53:36.400
messengers, demanding in furious terms that Cyrus&nbsp;
come and bow at his feet, as Herodotus recounts.

00:53:36.400 --> 00:53:42.800
Cyrus sent the messenger back with the threat&nbsp;
that he would be there a good deal sooner than

00:53:42.800 --> 00:53:52.720
Astyages liked. Astyages thereupon armed the Medes
to a man, and so far lost his wits as to appoint

00:53:52.720 --> 00:53:59.440
Harpagus to command them, having apparently&nbsp;
forgotten how he had treated him. The result

00:53:59.440 --> 00:54:06.320
was that when he took the field and engaged the&nbsp;
Persian army, some of Harpagus' men deserted to

00:54:06.320 --> 00:54:13.600
the Persians, and the greater number deliberately&nbsp;
shirked fighting and took to their heels.

00:54:17.360 --> 00:54:23.440
With the betrayal of this general, Astyages&nbsp;
was forced to gather a militia made up of

00:54:23.440 --> 00:54:29.600
what citizens he could find, and made&nbsp;
a last ditch attempt to stop the army

00:54:29.600 --> 00:54:37.920
of Cyrus. When Astyages learned of the&nbsp;
disgraceful collapse of the Median army,

00:54:37.920 --> 00:54:44.480
he armed all Medes, both under and over military&nbsp;
age who had been left in the city,

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:53.280
led them out to battle, and was defeated. His&nbsp;
men were killed, and he himself was taken alive.

00:54:54.720 --> 00:55:02.720
Harpagus was a real person, attested in a number&nbsp;
of sources, and one inscription found on a clay

00:55:02.720 --> 00:55:09.440
tablet in the ruins of Babylon, known as the&nbsp;
Nabonidus Chronicle, also hints at a betrayal

00:55:09.440 --> 00:55:17.600
by one of Astyages' generals, although the&nbsp;
general isn't named. In the sixth year,

00:55:17.600 --> 00:55:24.720
King Astyages called up his troops and marched&nbsp;
against Cyrus, king of Anshan, in order to

00:55:24.720 --> 00:55:32.000
meet him in battle. The army of Astyages revolted&nbsp;
against him, and in fetters they delivered him

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:40.080
to Cyrus. Cyrus marched against the country of&nbsp;
Ecbatana; the royal residents he seized; silver,

00:55:40.080 --> 00:55:48.720
gold, other valuables of the country Ecbatana&nbsp;
he took as loot and brought to Anshan.

00:55:48.720 --> 00:55:54.960
Whether because Astyages really was the&nbsp;
sadistic tyrant that Herodotus claims,

00:55:54.960 --> 00:56:03.840
we don't know, but after this, Harpagus would go&nbsp;
on to become one of Cyrus' most loyal generals.

00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:13.840
And Herodotus claims that after the battle,&nbsp;
Harpagus came to jeer at the captured Astyages.

00:56:13.840 --> 00:56:19.360
After the capture of Astyages,&nbsp;
Harpagus came and jeered at him,

00:56:19.360 --> 00:56:26.320
asking what it felt like to be a slave&nbsp;
instead of a king. Then said Astyages,

00:56:26.320 --> 00:56:33.280
"You are not only the wickedest, but&nbsp;
the most stupid of men. As things are,

00:56:33.280 --> 00:56:46.320
the innocent Medes have become slaves instead of&nbsp;
masters, and the Persians masters of the Medes.”

00:56:46.320 --> 00:56:51.280
Cyrus was now the lord of the&nbsp;
mountainous regions of the Near East,

00:56:51.280 --> 00:56:57.280
stretching from Persia right up to&nbsp;
perhaps their most powerful rival.

00:56:57.280 --> 00:57:12.320
This was a kingdom in the region of Asia Minor, in&nbsp;
what is now Western Turkey, the kingdom of Lydia.

00:57:12.320 --> 00:57:17.680
The Lydians were an ancient people. They&nbsp;
were even mentioned in Homer's epic,

00:57:17.680 --> 00:57:22.960
the Iliad, where they are listed&nbsp;
among the allies of the Trojans.

00:57:22.960 --> 00:57:30.240
They spoke their own Lydian language, which was in&nbsp;
the same Indo-European family as Persian and Greek.

00:57:30.240 --> 00:57:36.560
And according to the account of Herodotus,&nbsp;
throughout the war between Cyrus and Astyages,

00:57:36.560 --> 00:57:43.200
the king of Lydia had been watching.&nbsp;
He believed he had sensed an opening to

00:57:43.200 --> 00:57:51.680
take advantage of the chaos and expand his&nbsp;
borders even further. His name was Croesus.

00:58:07.920 --> 00:58:12.560
Croesus' kingdom of Lydia was astonishingly rich.

00:58:13.200 --> 00:58:18.320
In fact, the legendary King Midas, who&nbsp;
had the power to turn anything to gold

00:58:18.320 --> 00:58:25.280
with his touch, was supposed to have&nbsp;
once ruled over one of its regions.

00:58:25.280 --> 00:58:33.040
Lydia stood above a rich seam of electrum, a&nbsp;
naturally occurring alloy of gold and silver,

00:58:33.040 --> 00:58:38.640
that its people had eagerly mined for&nbsp;
centuries, and in the preceding decades,

00:58:38.640 --> 00:58:45.680
they had learned how to remove the silver from&nbsp;
this alloy to create coins of pure gold on an

00:58:45.680 --> 00:58:52.080
industrial scale. As the first people in&nbsp;
the world to produce gold in this manner,

00:58:52.080 --> 00:58:59.440
the Lydians were soon at the heart of&nbsp;
the world's most lucrative industry.

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:05.600
As a result, King Croesus soon&nbsp;
gained a reputation as a new Midas,

00:59:05.600 --> 00:59:13.760
the richest man in the world. Plutarch, in&nbsp;
his Life of Solon, gives one description

00:59:13.760 --> 00:59:19.680
of his legendary appearance at&nbsp;
the Lydian capital of Sardis.

00:59:21.040 --> 00:59:26.320
He was decked out with everything in the&nbsp;
way of precious stones, dyed raiment,

00:59:26.320 --> 00:59:32.480
and wrought gold that men deem remarkable&nbsp;
or extravagant or enviable, in order that he

00:59:32.480 --> 00:59:39.440
might present a most august and gorgeous spectacle.

00:59:39.440 --> 00:59:46.800
With these vast riches, King Croesus of&nbsp;
Lydia had also spent lavishly on his army,

00:59:46.800 --> 00:59:56.640
the pride of which was a wing of well-trained&nbsp;
armored cavalry, as Herodotus recounts.

00:59:56.640 --> 01:00:02.800
Now, at this time, there was no nation&nbsp;
in Asia more valiant or warlike than the

01:00:02.800 --> 01:00:09.040
Lydian. It was their custom to fight&nbsp;
on horseback, carrying long spears,

01:00:09.040 --> 01:00:15.360
and they were skilled in the management of horses.

01:00:15.360 --> 01:00:21.680
With this force, and bankrolled by his almost&nbsp;
limitless wealth, Croesus had gone to war

01:00:21.680 --> 01:00:29.120
from the moment he became king. He ruthlessly&nbsp;
conquered the various Greek city-state colonies

01:00:29.120 --> 01:00:36.880
that had been founded on the western coast of Asia&nbsp;
Minor, the regions of Ionia, Aeolia, and Doria,

01:00:36.880 --> 01:00:44.640
until he ruled virtually all of the western&nbsp;
segment of what is now Turkey. But still he

01:00:44.640 --> 01:00:53.440
dreamed of more, and he had watched the civil war&nbsp;
unfolding in far-off Persia with some interest.

01:00:54.320 --> 01:00:59.760
Croesus was actually the brother-in-law of&nbsp;
the Median king Astyages, having married

01:00:59.760 --> 01:01:05.680
his sister as part of a peace treaty, one in&nbsp;
which he had promised to keep his border at

01:01:05.680 --> 01:01:13.200
a river known to the Greeks as the Halys, and&nbsp;
which is known today as the Kizilirmak. But

01:01:13.200 --> 01:01:20.880
with Astyages now toppled, Croesus believed&nbsp;
the former treaty was no longer in effect.

01:01:20.880 --> 01:01:26.640
He now saw his chance to advance beyond&nbsp;
this border and become not just the

01:01:26.640 --> 01:01:33.680
richest but also the most powerful&nbsp;
man in the eastern Mediterranean.

01:01:33.680 --> 01:01:39.440
But Croesus was not an impulsive&nbsp;
man. Before any course of action,

01:01:39.440 --> 01:01:48.560
he did what any sensible man of this&nbsp;
time would do; he asked the gods.

01:01:48.560 --> 01:01:53.600
For this purpose, he sent out&nbsp;
messages to all the oracles of Greece,

01:01:53.600 --> 01:02:00.400
asking them whether he should attack&nbsp;
the Persians. Of all these oracles,

01:02:00.400 --> 01:02:16.880
the most famous and widely&nbsp;
respected was the oracle at Delphi.

01:02:20.160 --> 01:02:28.720
The oracle at Delphi was a woman who bore&nbsp;
the title of Pythia. For at least 200 years,

01:02:28.720 --> 01:02:34.800
people had flocked from all over the Greek world&nbsp;
and beyond to ask the oracle what the future

01:02:34.800 --> 01:02:42.880
held. Once someone came to consult the oracle,&nbsp;
they would be asked to make their offerings,

01:02:42.880 --> 01:02:51.040
often a laurel wreath and a black ram, and then&nbsp;
they would be allowed to ask their question. The

01:02:51.040 --> 01:02:59.360
Pythia would then descend into a stone chamber&nbsp;
called the adyton. Ancient sources describe this

01:02:59.360 --> 01:03:07.280
room filling with vapors, and from these vapors she&nbsp;
would enter into a state of spiritual possession,

01:03:07.280 --> 01:03:14.000
in which the god Apollo would actually&nbsp;
speak through her, often in cryptic riddles.

01:03:15.120 --> 01:03:22.960
The Greek writer Strabo describes the effects&nbsp;
of these gases. They say that the seat of the

01:03:22.960 --> 01:03:30.080
oracle is a cave that is hollowed out deep&nbsp;
down in the earth, with a rather narrow mouth

01:03:30.080 --> 01:03:38.560
from which arises breath that inspires a divine&nbsp;
frenzy, and that over that mouth is placed a high

01:03:38.560 --> 01:03:47.280
tripod, mounting which the Pythian priestess&nbsp;
receives the breath and then utters oracles.

01:03:47.280 --> 01:03:51.040
The writer Plutarch, who served&nbsp;
as a priest of the temple at

01:03:51.040 --> 01:04:00.320
Delphi for many years some centuries later,&nbsp;
described the strange smell of these fumes.

01:04:00.320 --> 01:04:04.640
Occasionally and fortuitously, the&nbsp;
room in which they seat the god's

01:04:04.640 --> 01:04:08.400
consultants is filled with a fragrance and breeze,

01:04:08.400 --> 01:04:17.360
as if the adyton were sending forth the essences&nbsp;
of the sweetest and most expensive perfumes.

01:04:17.360 --> 01:04:23.040
The description of this chamber is so specific&nbsp;
and intriguing that archaeologists have long

01:04:23.040 --> 01:04:29.120
searched for a scientific explanation&nbsp;
for these fits of ecstatic possession.

01:04:29.840 --> 01:04:36.080
It's been suggested that the area beneath the&nbsp;
adyton was filled with smoldering branches of

01:04:36.080 --> 01:04:43.520
oleander, a common but extremely poisonous plant&nbsp;
with bright pink flowers that grows around Greece

01:04:43.520 --> 01:04:51.360
and Asia Minor. Eating just one leaf of oleander&nbsp;
is enough to kill a person, and inhaling its smoke

01:04:51.360 --> 01:04:59.200
can have powerful psychoactive effects, including&nbsp;
hallucinations. Another suggestion is that the

01:04:59.200 --> 01:05:07.840
priestesses were inhaling fumes that actually&nbsp;
emanated from the depths of the earth itself.

01:05:10.480 --> 01:05:17.680
Delphi sits at a lively geological zone, at a&nbsp;
confluence of two major tectonic fault lines,

01:05:17.680 --> 01:05:23.200
and the limestone beneath it is high in&nbsp;
content of hydrocarbon gases, and among

01:05:23.200 --> 01:05:31.440
them the psychoactive gas ethylene. Ethylene&nbsp;
has been used historically as an anesthetic,

01:05:31.440 --> 01:05:38.160
but inhaled in small amounts, it can bring about&nbsp;
a conscious but trance-like state which is said to

01:05:38.160 --> 01:05:47.120
include euphoria, out of body experiences,&nbsp;
and in some cases, fits and convulsions.

01:05:47.120 --> 01:05:52.480
The gas also has a sweet smell, which&nbsp;
might explain Plutarch's description of

01:05:52.480 --> 01:05:58.880
the chamber's aroma. Modern analysis has&nbsp;
shown that spring water near the site of

01:05:58.880 --> 01:06:05.200
the oracle does contain traces of ethylene,&nbsp;
and that at certain fissures in the rock,

01:06:05.200 --> 01:06:10.800
the gas may have been released in sufficient&nbsp;
concentrations to account for the Pythia's

01:06:10.800 --> 01:06:17.680
visions. If this is the case, then it's&nbsp;
no surprise that the shrine at Delphi had

01:06:17.680 --> 01:06:24.560
been revered for so many years as a place where&nbsp;
humans could commune with the voices of the gods,

01:06:24.560 --> 01:06:31.600
which seemed to breathe out of&nbsp;
the rocks of the earth itself.

01:06:31.600 --> 01:06:37.040
What is certain is that the Delphic&nbsp;
Oracle was revered around all of Greece,

01:06:37.040 --> 01:06:42.320
and her word could make or break the&nbsp;
fortunes of even the most powerful kings.

01:06:43.840 --> 01:06:50.480
It was to this priestess that King Croesus&nbsp;
of Lydia sent his messengers, as he considered

01:06:50.480 --> 01:06:58.320
making war on Cyrus and the young power&nbsp;
of Persia. These messengers came laden

01:06:58.320 --> 01:07:08.640
with gifts that spoke to the enormous wealth of&nbsp;
the kingdom of Lydia, as Herodotus describes.

01:07:08.640 --> 01:07:16.560
He melted down a vast store of gold&nbsp;
and made of it ingots. These were 117 in

01:07:16.560 --> 01:07:25.200
number. He bade also to be made a figure of&nbsp;
a lion of refined gold, weighing ten talents.

01:07:25.200 --> 01:07:32.240
When these offerings were fully made, Croesus&nbsp;
sent them to Delphi, and other gifts besides,

01:07:32.240 --> 01:07:40.560
namely two very great bowls,
one of gold and one of silver.

01:07:40.560 --> 01:07:47.680
With their lavish gifts handed over, Herodotus&nbsp;
recounts the message that the oracle gave to King

01:07:47.680 --> 01:07:56.720
Croesus. The Lydians, who were to bring these gifts&nbsp;
to the temples, were charged by Croesus to inquire

01:07:56.720 --> 01:08:04.240
of the oracles. Shall Croesus send an army against&nbsp;
the Persians? The judgment given to Croesus by the

01:08:04.240 --> 01:08:16.160
oracle was that if he should send an army against&nbsp;
the Persians, he would destroy a great empire.

01:08:16.160 --> 01:08:29.040
Buoyed up by this seemingly enthusiastic advice,&nbsp;
Croesus immediately readied himself for war.

01:08:29.040 --> 01:08:37.520
In 547 BC, King Cyrus of Persia got news that&nbsp;
Croesus had marched out of his capital of Sardis

01:08:37.520 --> 01:08:45.840
and crossed the old border of the Halys River.&nbsp;
From there, the Lydian forces had swept into the

01:08:45.840 --> 01:08:52.480
region of Cappadocia, a landscape of strange&nbsp;
rock formations and white limestone gullies,

01:08:52.480 --> 01:09:02.080
and rounded on the regional capital of Pteria,&nbsp;
as Herodotus recounts. Croesus, then passing over

01:09:02.080 --> 01:09:10.720
his army, came to the part of Cappadocia called Pteria,&nbsp;
where he encamped, and laid waste the farms of the

01:09:10.720 --> 01:09:18.960
Syrians; and he took and enslaved the city of the&nbsp;
Pterians, and took also all the places about it,

01:09:18.960 --> 01:09:24.880
and drove the Syrians from their homes,&nbsp;
though they had done him no harm.

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:35.440
When Cyrus heard the news of this Lydian invasion,&nbsp;
it must have troubled him. He was a new ruler in

01:09:35.440 --> 01:09:42.800
a warrior culture that revered strength above&nbsp;
all else. If he failed to meet this challenge,

01:09:42.800 --> 01:09:49.520
he could lose the respect of all his subjects, and&nbsp;
his young empire would fall apart as quickly as

01:09:49.520 --> 01:09:57.760
it had begun. He quickly gathered his forces&nbsp;
of combined Persian and Median warriors, and

01:09:57.760 --> 01:10:07.040
marched out to meet King Croesus in the shadow&nbsp;
of the now ruined city of Pteria. Cyrus,

01:10:07.040 --> 01:10:12.880
mustering his army and gathering to&nbsp;
him all those who dwelt upon his way,

01:10:12.880 --> 01:10:19.680
went to meet Croesus. When Cyrus had come&nbsp;
and encamped face to face with Croesus,

01:10:19.680 --> 01:10:26.800
the armies made trial of each other's strength&nbsp;
with might. The battle was stubborn. Many on

01:10:26.800 --> 01:10:35.920
both sides fell, and when they were parted&nbsp;
at nightfall, neither had the advantage.

01:10:35.920 --> 01:10:43.680
Croesus was clearly surprised by the strength&nbsp;
of Cyrus' response. Despite the famous Lydian

01:10:43.680 --> 01:10:52.240
cavalry, the clash had ended in a stalemate,&nbsp;
and now his invasion had lost all momentum.

01:10:52.240 --> 01:10:59.920
To make matters worse, winter was drawing in.&nbsp;
The mountainous geography of Asia Minor means

01:10:59.920 --> 01:11:06.080
its winters can be extremely punishing, with&nbsp;
temperatures below freezing, and even dropping

01:11:06.080 --> 01:11:15.040
to -20° in extreme conditions. In that season,&nbsp;
snow could sit on the ground for weeks at a time,

01:11:15.040 --> 01:11:22.720
and military campaigns became impossible.&nbsp;
As a result, Croesus decided to retreat back

01:11:22.720 --> 01:11:30.080
over the Halys River, and return through the&nbsp;
mountains to his capital of Sardis. There, he

01:11:30.080 --> 01:11:36.960
would send out requests for reinforcements from&nbsp;
his allies in Egypt and Babylon, even planning

01:11:36.960 --> 01:11:45.040
to request help from the warlike Greek city&nbsp;
of Sparta. It was in his mind to muster all

01:11:45.040 --> 01:11:51.760
these forces and assemble his own army, then to&nbsp;
wait ‘til the winter was over and march against

01:11:51.760 --> 01:11:58.640
the Persians at the beginning of spring. With&nbsp;
such intent, as soon as he returned to Sardis,

01:11:58.640 --> 01:12:08.720
he sent heralds to all his allies, summoning&nbsp;
them to assemble at Sardis in five months time.

01:12:08.720 --> 01:12:16.320
But none of this would come to pass. That's&nbsp;
because Croesus had drastically underestimated

01:12:16.320 --> 01:12:24.080
the Persian king Cyrus. Rather than waiting&nbsp;
out the winter, as Croesus had expected,

01:12:24.080 --> 01:12:32.560
Cyrus took a remarkable decision. When&nbsp;
Croesus marched away after the battle,

01:12:32.560 --> 01:12:37.520
Cyrus took counsel and perceived thereby&nbsp;
that it was his business to march with

01:12:37.520 --> 01:12:44.480
all speed against Sardis before the power&nbsp;
of the Lydians could again be assembled.

01:12:45.200 --> 01:12:58.400
He marched his army into Lydia, and so himself&nbsp;
came to bring the news of it to Croesus.

01:12:58.400 --> 01:13:06.560
The march would have been a difficult one. Ahead&nbsp;
of the Persian army lay nearly a thousand kilometers

01:13:06.560 --> 01:13:13.520
of rocky, mountainous territory, with unfamiliar&nbsp;
routes and narrow passes through the mountains.

01:13:14.400 --> 01:13:21.920
Winter was coming, perhaps snow falling. As&nbsp;
such, we can only imagine the astonishment

01:13:21.920 --> 01:13:29.120
of King Croesus of Lydia as he looked out over&nbsp;
the walls of his capital of Sardis and saw the

01:13:29.120 --> 01:13:38.400
amassed forces of the Persian army arriving&nbsp;
on the horizon. Herodotus recalls his shock.

01:13:39.440 --> 01:13:46.640
All had turned out contrary to Croesus'&nbsp;
expectation, and he was in a great quandary.

01:13:46.640 --> 01:13:56.720
Nevertheless, he led out the Lydians&nbsp;
to battle in the plain, wide and bare.

01:13:56.720 --> 01:14:02.000
As the Persians rode to battle, they would&nbsp;
have been struck by the landscape they saw

01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:08.960
ahead of them, dominated by a remarkable&nbsp;
series of monuments, the burial mounds of

01:14:08.960 --> 01:14:17.680
Lydia's ancient kings. For centuries, Lydians&nbsp;
had buried their rulers in vast tombs, with

01:14:17.680 --> 01:14:25.200
bases built of stepped limestone and marble,&nbsp;
and great heaps of earth towering above them.

01:14:26.240 --> 01:14:32.320
The largest of these, the mound thought to&nbsp;
have been built for Croesus' father, Alyattes,

01:14:32.320 --> 01:14:41.360
has the same footprint as the Pyramid of Giza,&nbsp;
and stands to nearly half its height at 63 meters.

01:14:41.360 --> 01:14:47.920
Littered around the high plain to the north&nbsp;
of Sardis stood around 150 of these burial

01:14:47.920 --> 01:14:54.320
mounds, and they would have made an imposing&nbsp;
statement about the power and prestige of the

01:14:54.320 --> 01:15:05.200
ancient kingdom of Lydia, and up ahead&nbsp;
stood the impregnable citadel of Sardis.

01:15:05.200 --> 01:15:11.120
While the main city was defended by a strong&nbsp;
wall, it was the citadel that made the city

01:15:11.120 --> 01:15:18.880
virtually impossible to capture. It was perched on&nbsp;
a knife edge of limestone jutting out of the plain

01:15:18.880 --> 01:15:27.200
known as Mount Tmolus, its sides so steep that&nbsp;
the fortress barely needed walls in some places.

01:15:28.400 --> 01:15:34.320
Although the Persian army was large, Cyrus&nbsp;
would need every one of his soldiers to take

01:15:34.320 --> 01:15:41.440
that fortress, and he had already seen the damage&nbsp;
that the powerful Lydian cavalry could inflict

01:15:41.440 --> 01:15:53.280
on his army. But he brought a secret weapon&nbsp;
to the battlefield, as Herodotus describes.

01:15:53.280 --> 01:15:59.040
Assembling all the camels that followed&nbsp;
his army bearing food and baggage, he took

01:15:59.040 --> 01:16:04.240
off their burdens and set men upon&nbsp;
them equipped like cavalry men. He

01:16:04.240 --> 01:16:11.520
ordered them to advance ahead of his army&nbsp;
against Croesus' horses. Horses fear camels,

01:16:11.520 --> 01:16:18.240
and can endure neither the sight nor the&nbsp;
smell of them. So, when battle was joined,

01:16:18.240 --> 01:16:28.480
as soon as the horses smelt and saw the camels,&nbsp;
they turned to flight, and all Croesus’ hope was lost.

01:16:28.480 --> 01:16:34.080
With their cavalry scattered, the Lydians&nbsp;
retreated to their lofty citadel, and the

01:16:34.080 --> 01:16:42.560
Persians besieged the steep-sided fortress. The&nbsp;siege
went on for fourteen days, during which they must

01:16:42.560 --> 01:16:52.400
have wondered how they would ever capture it, but&nbsp;
they were about to get a stroke of luck. Herodotus

01:16:52.400 --> 01:16:59.040
recalls that one side of the city's citadel&nbsp;
looked out over a cliff so sheer that it was

01:16:59.040 --> 01:17:06.880
comparatively lightly defended, since no one could&nbsp;
ever hope to climb it. On the eve of the fourteenth

01:17:06.880 --> 01:17:13.280
day of the siege, a soldier in the Persian army&nbsp;
spotted a Lydian warrior climbing down a hidden

01:17:13.280 --> 01:17:21.200
route on this side of the fortress. As he watched,&nbsp;
he saw the man climb down to an outcrop, where he

01:17:21.200 --> 01:17:28.960
reached down and picked up his helmet, which had&nbsp;
fallen from the rampart. No doubt worried that

01:17:28.960 --> 01:17:34.560
he would be disciplined by his superiors for&nbsp;
losing his helmet, this Lydian had dared the

01:17:34.560 --> 01:17:46.240
death-defying climb down to retrieve it, but he had&nbsp;
also inadvertently shown the Persians the way up.

01:17:46.240 --> 01:17:52.240
This Mardian had seen one of the Lydians&nbsp;
descend by this part of the citadel after

01:17:52.240 --> 01:18:00.000
a helmet that had fallen down, and fetch it; he&nbsp;
took note of this and considered it, and now he

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:11.680
himself climbed up, and other Persians after&nbsp;
him. Many ascended, and thus was Sardis taken.

01:18:11.680 --> 01:18:18.320
King Croesus of Lydia was captured. With&nbsp;
the fall of Sardis, the entirety of his

01:18:18.320 --> 01:18:25.040
powerful kingdom, and its vast stores of&nbsp;
gold, passed into the hands of the Persians.

01:18:26.080 --> 01:18:33.200
Herodotus ends his story&nbsp;
with a final ironic twist.

01:18:33.200 --> 01:18:41.280
So, the Persians took Sardis and made Croesus himself&nbsp;
prisoner, he having reigned fourteen years and been

01:18:41.280 --> 01:18:54.320
besieged fourteen days, and, as the oracle foretold,&nbsp;
the empire he brought to an end was his own.

01:18:54.320 --> 01:19:02.320
Herodotus recounts that Cyrus actually spared&nbsp;
Croesus’ life, and took him on as an adviser.

01:19:02.320 --> 01:19:08.400
While we have no further evidence of this, it is&nbsp;
plausible, since we do have documentary evidence

01:19:08.400 --> 01:19:15.760
that Cyrus spared the lives of many of the men he&nbsp;
conquered. With the kingdom of Lydia and its vast

01:19:15.760 --> 01:19:24.000
wealth now absorbed into his growing empire, Cyrus&nbsp;
turned his sights on the lowlands of Mesopotamia,

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:50.800
where the empire of Babylon now stretched.

01:19:50.800 --> 01:19:56.960
In the years since the fall of the Assyrian&nbsp;
Empire, the Babylonians had become one of

01:19:56.960 --> 01:20:02.560
the most powerful empires in the world,&nbsp;
conquering Syria and all the way down the

01:20:02.560 --> 01:20:10.160
coast of Palestine to the borders of Egypt, but&nbsp;
they had experienced some considerable unrest

01:20:10.160 --> 01:20:17.280
among their conquered territories. Just&nbsp;
one example was the incessant rebellions

01:20:17.280 --> 01:20:31.120
of the Jewish kingdom of Judah, centered&nbsp;
around its ancient capital of Jerusalem.

01:20:31.120 --> 01:20:38.000
The people of Judah had despised the Assyrian&nbsp;
Empire in its day, and now hated the Babylonian

01:20:38.000 --> 01:20:45.760
Empire that replaced it just as much.&nbsp;
At the beginning of the 6th century BC,

01:20:45.760 --> 01:20:53.200
a number of the Judean cities in the Levant&nbsp;
rebelled against Babylonian rule. As a result,

01:20:53.200 --> 01:21:00.800
in 597 BC, King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon&nbsp;
marched west and besieged the city of

01:21:00.800 --> 01:21:10.640
Jerusalem. After a grueling thirty-month siege, the&nbsp;
city fell, and King Nebuchadnezzar sacked it, and

01:21:10.640 --> 01:21:21.040
burned down the temple that stood on the temple&nbsp;
mount, as the Hebrew Book of Kings recounts.

01:21:21.040 --> 01:21:26.400
And it came to pass in the ninth year of his&nbsp;
reign that Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon,

01:21:26.400 --> 01:21:34.640
came, he and all his army, against Jerusalem,&nbsp;
and encamped against it; and they built forts

01:21:34.640 --> 01:21:39.280
against it round about, and he burned&nbsp;
the house of the Lord, and the king's

01:21:39.280 --> 01:21:49.600
house, and all the houses of Jerusalem. Even&nbsp;
every great man's house burnt he with fire.

01:21:49.600 --> 01:21:56.000
The kingdom of Judah was now officially&nbsp;
dissolved. Large numbers of its people

01:21:56.000 --> 01:22:02.880
captured in the sack of Jerusalem were rounded&nbsp;
up and deported to Babylon to be resettled,

01:22:02.880 --> 01:22:10.720
a typical tactic of Mesopotamian empires&nbsp;
when dealing with troublesome populations.

01:22:10.720 --> 01:22:16.640
But despite these troubles in some of its more&nbsp;
restive provinces, the rule of Nebuchadnezzar II

01:22:16.640 --> 01:22:24.000
was prosperous, and it's during his reign&nbsp;
that Babylon built its most famous landmark,

01:22:24.000 --> 01:22:31.200
the Ishtar Gate, a towering edifice faced all&nbsp;
over with brilliant blue glazed bricks, which

01:22:31.200 --> 01:22:39.280
opened up onto a grand processional street.&nbsp;
Nebuchadnezzar ruled for nearly sixty years,

01:22:39.280 --> 01:22:48.080
but after his death, the young empire fell into a&nbsp;
period of turmoil. His son and chosen successor,

01:22:48.080 --> 01:22:55.600
Amel-Marduk, was apparently incompetent, and ruled&nbsp;
for only two years before being overthrown by his

01:22:55.600 --> 01:23:02.240
brother-in-law. This man ruled for only four&nbsp;
years before dying and passing the throne to

01:23:02.240 --> 01:23:09.360
his son, who ruled for only two or three months&nbsp;
before himself being killed and deposed.

01:23:10.240 --> 01:23:21.120
This period of turmoil came to an end with the&nbsp;
reign of a king in Babylon named Nabonidus.

01:23:21.120 --> 01:23:27.280
He stands out in history as a truly&nbsp;
enigmatic figure. He had no relation

01:23:27.280 --> 01:23:31.600
to any previous king, and the fact&nbsp;
he even became king at all seems

01:23:31.600 --> 01:23:39.120
to have come as something of a surprise&nbsp;
to him, as he writes in one inscription.

01:23:39.120 --> 01:23:50.320
I am Nabonidus, the only son who has nobody. In&nbsp;
my mind, there was no thought of kingship. One

01:23:50.320 --> 01:23:57.440
strange aspect of Nabonidus is that he appears&nbsp;
to have had somewhat unusual religious beliefs.

01:23:58.160 --> 01:24:04.480
The principal god of Babylon had always been&nbsp;
Marduk, the king of the gods and lord of the

01:24:04.480 --> 01:24:12.640
universe, but Nabonidus was devoted instead to&nbsp;
the moon god Sin, after apparently seeing him in

01:24:12.640 --> 01:24:20.560
a vision. In fact, carvings of Nabonidus often&nbsp;
show him offering his reverence to the carved

01:24:20.560 --> 01:24:28.400
figure of the moon. This seems to have caused&nbsp;
some friction in the country, as one Babylonian

01:24:28.400 --> 01:24:35.680
clay tablet complains. He made the image of&nbsp;
a deity which nobody had ever seen in this

01:24:35.680 --> 01:24:41.440
country. He introduced it into the temple and&nbsp;
placed it upon a pedestal. He called it by the

01:24:41.440 --> 01:24:51.760
name of Sin. It is adorned with a crown of lapis&nbsp;
lazuli, its appearance that of the eclipsed moon.

01:24:51.760 --> 01:24:58.080
At one point, he seems to have taken a&nbsp;
self-imposed exile from Babylon lasting ten years,

01:24:58.080 --> 01:25:04.720
in which he devoted himself to quiet meditation&nbsp;
in the faraway temple of Tayma in what is today

01:25:04.720 --> 01:25:13.920
Saudi Arabia. This distanced him from his subjects&nbsp;
and disrupted the ceremonial calendar of the city.

01:25:14.640 --> 01:25:20.800
He even failed to show his face at the annual&nbsp;
Babylonian New Year festival, celebrated at the

01:25:20.800 --> 01:25:27.920
spring equinox. Usually, the king would climb to&nbsp;
the highest chamber of the city's temple, where

01:25:27.920 --> 01:25:34.800
the high priest of Marduk would ceremonially slap&nbsp;
him on the face, reminding him to be humble to the

01:25:34.800 --> 01:25:44.480
gods. But Nabonidus, busy worshiping the moon&nbsp;
god far away in Arabia, didn't attend, as one

01:25:44.480 --> 01:25:53.040
Babylonian inscription recounts. The king was&nbsp;
in Tayma, while the crown prince, his officers,

01:25:53.040 --> 01:25:59.680
and his army were in Akkad. The king did&nbsp;
not come to Babylon in the month Nisanu.

01:25:59.680 --> 01:26:09.440
The god Nabu did not come to Babylon. The&nbsp;
New Year's festival did not take place.

01:26:09.440 --> 01:26:17.680
We don't know how the war with the Persians began,&nbsp;
but it had clearly begun to seem inevitable.

01:26:17.680 --> 01:26:24.880
Around 540 BC, Nabonidus ordered that the statues&nbsp;
of the gods of each city in his empire should

01:26:24.880 --> 01:26:32.480
be transported to Babylon for safekeeping. One&nbsp;
Babylonian letter from an official in the city

01:26:32.480 --> 01:26:40.080
of Uruk describes the preparations to transport&nbsp;
the goddess Eanna down the river to Babylon on a

01:26:40.080 --> 01:26:50.800
raft buoyed up by inflated goat skins. Letter of&nbsp;
Rimut to Nabu-mukin-zeri. May Nabu and Marduk bless

01:26:50.800 --> 01:26:57.760
my brothers! Send me one leather mat and five&nbsp;
inflated goat skins for the boat so that the

01:26:57.760 --> 01:27:05.920
Lady Eanna may go to Babylon on the Euphrates.&nbsp;
Other tablets describe the priests continuing

01:27:05.920 --> 01:27:14.000
to give offerings of food to the holy statues as&nbsp;
they sailed down the river on the way to Babylon.

01:27:15.760 --> 01:27:22.800
Soon war was declared, and Cyrus marched&nbsp;
down into the lowlands of Mesopotamia,

01:27:22.800 --> 01:27:28.480
arriving in the year 539 BC.

01:27:28.480 --> 01:27:35.760
King Nabonidus gathered his armies and set out&nbsp;
to meet the invaders at a place called Opis.

01:27:36.640 --> 01:27:45.840
The text known as the Nabonidus Chronicle recounts&nbsp;
in sparse terms what happened next. In the month

01:27:45.840 --> 01:27:52.400
Tashritu, when Cyrus did battle at Opis on the&nbsp;
bank of the Tigris against the army of Babylon,

01:27:52.400 --> 01:27:57.360
the people of Babylon retreated.&nbsp;
He carried off the plunder and

01:27:57.360 --> 01:28:04.080
slaughtered the people. On the 14th day,&nbsp;
Sippar was captured without a battle.

01:28:04.080 --> 01:28:16.320
Nabonidus fled. On the sixteenth day, the army&nbsp;
of Cyrus entered Babylon without a battle.

01:28:16.320 --> 01:28:23.200
One Babylonian text written afterwards on the&nbsp;
order of Cyrus is called the Cyrus Cylinder.

01:28:23.760 --> 01:28:30.800
In this piece of official propaganda, he explains&nbsp;
that the Babylonian god Marduk had called on

01:28:30.800 --> 01:28:39.280
him, since King Nabonidus had so heretically&nbsp;
turned his back on the city's patron deity.

01:28:39.280 --> 01:28:47.360
In Nabonidus' mind, reverential fear of Marduk,&nbsp;
king of the gods, had come to an end. He did yet

01:28:47.360 --> 01:28:55.920
more evil to his city every day. He brought ruin&nbsp;
on his people. Marduk inspected and checked all

01:28:55.920 --> 01:29:01.840
the countries, seeking for the upright king&nbsp;
of his choice. He took the hand of Cyrus,

01:29:01.840 --> 01:29:08.640
king of the city of Anshan, and called him by his&nbsp;
name, proclaiming him aloud for the kingship over

01:29:08.640 --> 01:29:16.400
all of everything. Marduk joyfully looked at&nbsp;
Cyrus' good deeds and at his righteous heart.

01:29:16.400 --> 01:29:23.520
He made him take the road to Babylon, and marched&nbsp;
at his side like a friend and companion. Without

01:29:23.520 --> 01:29:34.880
combat or battle, he caused him to enter Babylon,&nbsp;
his city. He saved Babylon from oppression.

01:29:34.880 --> 01:29:41.520
The people of Babylon must have feared the&nbsp;
worst when Cyrus' army swept into the city,

01:29:41.520 --> 01:29:49.440
but they were pleasantly surprised. The Nabonidus&nbsp;
Chronicle even describes how Cyrus ordered Persian

01:29:49.440 --> 01:29:55.840
soldiers to stand guard outside the great&nbsp;
temple to Marduk, called the Esagil, to ensure

01:29:55.840 --> 01:30:03.200
its protection. Until the end of the month, the&nbsp;
shield-bearers of Persia surrounded the gates of

01:30:03.200 --> 01:30:10.240
the Esagil. There was no interruption of whatever&nbsp;
rites in the Esagil and the other temples, and

01:30:10.240 --> 01:30:17.840
no ritual date was missed. There was peace in the&nbsp;
city when Cyrus spoke greetings to all of Babylon.

01:30:17.840 --> 01:30:27.280
The gods of Akkad that Nabonidus had brought to&nbsp;
Babylon returned safely to their cult places.

01:30:27.280 --> 01:30:31.200
All of this signaled that Cyrus&nbsp;
wanted to promote an image of

01:30:31.200 --> 01:30:41.520
himself as a very different kind of&nbsp;
ruler to those who had come before.

01:30:41.520 --> 01:30:48.000
When he arrived, Cyrus found Babylon full of&nbsp;
captured peoples who had been seized from their

01:30:48.000 --> 01:30:56.400
lands in far-flung provinces and forced&nbsp;
to relocate to the city, and remarkably,

01:30:56.400 --> 01:31:02.160
one of his first decrees as the ruler of&nbsp;
Babylon was to allow all of these peoples,

01:31:02.160 --> 01:31:09.840
if they wished, to return home. These&nbsp;
people came from all over the empire.

01:31:09.840 --> 01:31:17.920
Elamites and Medes from the Zagros, Aramaeans from&nbsp;
Syria, Phoenicians from cities like Tyre and Sidon,

01:31:17.920 --> 01:31:27.040
even Egyptians and Arabs. But most famously,&nbsp;
they also came from the Hebrew kingdom of Judah.

01:31:27.040 --> 01:31:36.480
The Hebrew Bible recalls this event. Now in the&nbsp;
first year of Cyrus, king of Persia, he made a

01:31:36.480 --> 01:31:43.440
proclamation throughout all his kingdom, and put&nbsp;
it also in writing, saying, "Thus saith Cyrus,

01:31:43.440 --> 01:31:49.600
king of Persia, the Lord God of heaven hath&nbsp;
given me all the kingdoms of the earth. Who

01:31:49.600 --> 01:31:59.200
is there among you of all his people? His God&nbsp;
be with him, and let him go up to Jerusalem."

01:31:59.200 --> 01:32:05.440
Like the people of Babylon with Marduk, the&nbsp;
Judeans interpreted Cyrus as having been

01:32:05.440 --> 01:32:12.480
chosen by their god Yahweh to set them free.&nbsp;
Cyrus might have calculated that sending back

01:32:12.480 --> 01:32:18.800
these few thousand deportees would improve&nbsp;
his reputation around his new empire, but

01:32:18.800 --> 01:32:24.080
he couldn't have predicted quite how long&nbsp;
or how far this act of kindness would be

01:32:24.080 --> 01:32:30.880
remembered. Since the Hebrew Bible would form&nbsp;
the basis for the future Christian religion,

01:32:30.880 --> 01:32:38.480
his good deed would be immortalized in the holy&nbsp;
text of one of the world's major religions. The

01:32:38.480 --> 01:32:46.160
Hebrew poet prophet we know as Second Isaiah&nbsp;
would even go so far as to name Cyrus with a

01:32:46.160 --> 01:32:54.320
title that in Hebrew was pronounced ‘mashiach’,&nbsp;
which meant ‘the anointed one of God’, a title

01:32:54.320 --> 01:33:02.880
which gives us the English word ‘messiah’. This&nbsp;
is what the Lord says to Cyrus, his Messiah,

01:33:02.880 --> 01:33:09.200
whose right hand he will empower. Before&nbsp;
him, mighty kings will be paralyzed with

01:33:09.200 --> 01:33:18.880
fear. Their fortress gates will be opened, never&nbsp;
to shut again. Cyrus would be the first and only

01:33:18.880 --> 01:33:28.000
non-Jewish person to ever be awarded that title,&nbsp;
a testament to his skill at winning people over.

01:33:28.000 --> 01:33:35.200
Meanwhile, the name Babylon would pass into&nbsp;
memory as a byword for oppression, slavery, and

01:33:35.200 --> 01:33:44.640
corruption, a reminder that our actions in history&nbsp;
can resonate far longer than we might ever expect.

01:34:09.440 --> 01:34:16.320
The empire that Cyrus forged the&nbsp;
Persians would refer to as Kh-sha-thra,

01:34:16.320 --> 01:34:24.960
meaning simply ‘the kingdom’, and it would always&nbsp;
be a cultural melting pot. The Persians themselves

01:34:24.960 --> 01:34:32.000
had begun as a successful marriage of Iranian&nbsp;
and Elamite cultures, but over the decades

01:34:32.000 --> 01:34:38.560
and centuries that followed, they would add&nbsp;
elements of Mesopotamian dress, religion, art,

01:34:38.560 --> 01:34:46.080
and iconography. They also introduced ideas&nbsp;
in architecture, medicine, and engineering

01:34:46.080 --> 01:34:52.880
from conquered regions like Lydia, the Greek&nbsp;
cities of Asia Minor, Egypt, and Phoenicia.

01:34:53.840 --> 01:35:03.120
Herodotus describes this Persian ability to&nbsp;
synthesize the ways of others. No race is so

01:35:03.120 --> 01:35:10.000
ready to adopt foreign ways as the Persian.&nbsp;
For instance, they wear the Median costume,

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:17.440
as they think it handsomer than their own,&nbsp;
and their soldiers wear the Egyptian armor.

01:35:19.120 --> 01:35:24.960
Persia was an empire that combined&nbsp;
and reproduced the best ideas from

01:35:24.960 --> 01:35:35.360
each culture it absorbed, and in that&nbsp;
way it was remarkably successful.

01:35:35.360 --> 01:35:41.040
For the Greek writers who encountered Persians&nbsp;
and described them, one of the most remarkable

01:35:41.040 --> 01:35:50.000
aspects of their appearance was their clothing,
as Herodotus describes. Around their heads they

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:57.680
wore something called a tiara of soft felt,&nbsp;
while on their body they wore a multicolored

01:35:57.680 --> 01:36:05.760
sleeved garment and a piece of armor in appearance&nbsp;
like fish scales made of iron. Around their legs

01:36:05.760 --> 01:36:15.360
they wore trousers. Trousers were an innovation&nbsp;
developed on the Eurasian Steppe, designed to

01:36:15.360 --> 01:36:22.400
protect the legs while riding a horse night and&nbsp;
day. In the years after the conquest of Babylon,

01:36:22.400 --> 01:36:30.960
the Persians would combine these with fine fabrics&nbsp;
and expensive dyes to create new, stylish garments.

01:36:30.960 --> 01:36:38.880
The Greek writer Xenophon describes the&nbsp;
appearance of the Persian prince. Upon a chariot

01:36:38.880 --> 01:36:45.440
he appeared in the gates, wearing his tiara&nbsp;
upright, a purple tunic shot with white,

01:36:45.440 --> 01:36:52.240
trousers of scarlet dye about his&nbsp;
legs, and a mantle all of purple.

01:36:54.000 --> 01:36:59.840
Greeks had for centuries worn simple&nbsp;
tunics and cloaks, and always left their

01:36:59.840 --> 01:37:06.320
legs bare. They found the appearance of&nbsp;
Persian trousers ridiculous, and mocked

01:37:06.320 --> 01:37:14.480
their baggy appearance using the slang word&nbsp;
‘thulakoi’, a word which means ‘sacks’. In fact,

01:37:14.480 --> 01:37:20.240
if an ancient Greek were somehow transported into&nbsp;
the modern day, perhaps the first thing they would

01:37:20.240 --> 01:37:28.640
be struck by was how everyone around them was&nbsp;
dressed like a Persian. Apart from their clothes,

01:37:28.640 --> 01:37:35.280
Persians also looked physically different to&nbsp;
the Greek writers who documented them. When they

01:37:35.280 --> 01:37:42.160
captured Persian prisoners of war, ancient writers&nbsp;
expressed surprise at how white their skins were

01:37:42.160 --> 01:37:52.720
compared to the sunburned Greeks, and considered&nbsp;
this a sign of their softness and effeminacy.

01:37:52.720 --> 01:37:57.760
When the Greeks depicted Persians in their&nbsp;
art, their beards are always shown to be

01:37:57.760 --> 01:38:03.680
big and bushy, with long mustaches, and&nbsp;
we also see the importance of beards

01:38:03.680 --> 01:38:11.360
in Persian culture reflected in the carved&nbsp;
palace reliefs at Persepolis. In these images,

01:38:11.360 --> 01:38:20.640
the men with the highest status are always&nbsp;
shown to have the most formidable beards.

01:38:24.320 --> 01:38:29.840
Religion in the empire was complex and&nbsp;
diverse, and it's not actually known for

01:38:29.840 --> 01:38:36.800
sure what religious beliefs early rulers like&nbsp;
Cyrus would have held, but they were likely

01:38:36.800 --> 01:38:44.640
followers of an early form of Iranian religion&nbsp;
and what would later become Zoroastrianism.

01:38:45.760 --> 01:38:50.800
The Zoroastrian faith was founded&nbsp;
by a prophet named Zarathustra,

01:38:50.800 --> 01:38:55.280
who likely lived somewhere in the&nbsp;
eastern regions of the Iranian world,

01:38:55.280 --> 01:39:03.920
perhaps in modern Afghanistan or Tajikistan.&nbsp;
He was born sometime around the year 1,000 BC,

01:39:03.920 --> 01:39:11.600
likely into a nomadic or semi-nomadic people.&nbsp;
At the age of thirty, while attending his people's

01:39:11.600 --> 01:39:17.520
annual spring festival, Zarathustra saw a&nbsp;
vision in which a shining being appeared

01:39:17.520 --> 01:39:27.200
to him and taught him about the god called Ahura&nbsp;
Mazda, or ‘wise lord’. This shining being also told

01:39:27.200 --> 01:39:36.720
him about an evil entity known as Angra Mainyu,&nbsp;
or ‘the destructive spirit’. For all of time,

01:39:36.720 --> 01:39:44.000
Ahura Mazda and Angra Mainyu had been locked in&nbsp;
an eternal battle in which the forces of ‘asha’,

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:54.320
or ‘order’, were pitted against the evil forces of&nbsp;
‘druj’, or ‘deception’. After this vision, Zarathustra

01:39:54.320 --> 01:40:01.120
decided to devote his life to promoting the good&nbsp;
force of asha and spreading the word of the wise

01:40:01.120 --> 01:40:10.480
god Ahuram Mazda. His life teachings would be&nbsp;
collected in a series of texts known as the Gathas,

01:40:10.480 --> 01:40:19.440
the divine songs, which forms part of the&nbsp;
Zoroastrian religious text, the Avesta.

01:40:19.440 --> 01:40:27.040
Fundamentally, Zarathustra taught that a person's&nbsp;
thoughts, words, and actions formed an unbroken

01:40:27.040 --> 01:40:33.840
chain. If you strived to think only good&nbsp;
thoughts, then you would speak only good

01:40:33.840 --> 01:40:55.520
words, and then commit only good actions, as the&nbsp;
following Zoroastrian prayer song describes.

01:40:56.720 --> 01:40:59.760
With outspread hands in petition for that help,

01:40:59.760 --> 01:41:05.840
O Mazda, I will pray for the works of&nbsp;
the holy spirit, O thou the right,

01:41:05.840 --> 01:41:13.040
whereby I may please the will of good thought;&nbsp;
the wise whom thou knowest as worthy, for

01:41:13.040 --> 01:41:22.400
their good deeds and their good thought,&nbsp;
for them do thou fulfill their longing.

01:41:29.520 --> 01:41:35.840
Part of the attainment of good thought and&nbsp;
good words was an uncompromising adherence

01:41:35.840 --> 01:41:43.840
to speaking the truth, something that Persians&nbsp;
took extremely seriously. Herodotus describes

01:41:43.840 --> 01:41:52.080
witnessing this firsthand. They consider&nbsp;
telling lies more disgraceful than anything

01:41:52.080 --> 01:41:59.840
else, and, next to that, owing money. There are&nbsp;
many reasons for their horror of debt, but

01:41:59.840 --> 01:42:08.240
the chief of their conviction is that a man&nbsp;
who owes money is bound also to tell lies.

01:42:09.840 --> 01:42:13.280
Zoroastrians particularly held earth, fire,

01:42:13.280 --> 01:42:22.080
and water to be sacred and agents of purifying.&nbsp;
Zoroastrian temples had at their heart an

01:42:22.080 --> 01:42:28.560
eternal flame that was supposed to never be put&nbsp;
out. The priests of the temple would wear face

01:42:28.560 --> 01:42:35.280
masks over their mouths so that their unclean&nbsp;
breath would not pollute the sacred fire.

01:42:35.840 --> 01:42:45.360
Persians also held rivers and other bodies&nbsp;
of water to be sacred, as Herodotus describes.

01:42:45.360 --> 01:42:52.320
The following are certain Persian customs which&nbsp;
I can describe from personal knowledge. The

01:42:52.320 --> 01:42:58.080
erection of statues and altars is not an&nbsp;
acceptable practice amongst them, and anyone

01:42:58.080 --> 01:43:04.880
who does such a thing is considered a fool.&nbsp;
God in their system is the whole circle of

01:43:04.880 --> 01:43:12.160
the heavens, and they sacrifice to him from the&nbsp;
tops of mountains. They also worship the sun,

01:43:12.160 --> 01:43:19.920
moon and earth, fire, water, and winds, which&nbsp;
are their only original deities. They have

01:43:19.920 --> 01:43:25.200
a profound reverence for rivers.&nbsp;
They will never pollute a river with

01:43:25.200 --> 01:43:31.040
urine or spittle, or even wash their hands&nbsp;
in one, or allow anyone else to do so.

01:43:35.040 --> 01:43:42.080
The inscriptions of the Persians continually&nbsp;
reference the god Aruha Mazda, but the Persian

01:43:42.080 --> 01:43:49.600
court also held reverence for other gods like&nbsp;
the warrior goddess Anahita, an Elamite god

01:43:49.600 --> 01:44:00.240
named Human, and Mithra, god of the sun, guardian&nbsp;
of cattle, the harvest, and the waters. Perhaps

01:44:00.240 --> 01:44:07.920
partly as a result of their religious conviction,&nbsp;
the Persians were also prolific gardeners. While

01:44:07.920 --> 01:44:15.440
we can't reconstruct the true shape of Achaemenid&nbsp;
religion, later Zoroastrians held that the dry

01:44:15.440 --> 01:44:23.600
and desert parts of the world were made barren&nbsp;by
the destructive and deceptive spirit Angra Mainyu.

01:44:23.600 --> 01:44:30.480
Meanwhile, the spirit of the good Ahura Mazda&nbsp;
gave them the task of turning the deserts of the

01:44:30.480 --> 01:44:37.760
world green. What we know for sure is that&nbsp;
wherever they went, the Persians cultivated

01:44:37.760 --> 01:44:46.480
ornamental gardens. These gardens they gave a&nbsp;
name that suggested exclusivity and security, from

01:44:46.480 --> 01:44:56.720
the Persian words ‘pairi’ and ‘daiza’, meaning ‘walled’ or&nbsp;
‘bricked around’; ‘pairidaiza’. The name for these gardens

01:44:56.720 --> 01:45:06.400
passed into Greek as ‘paradeisos’, which gives us the&nbsp;
English word ‘paradise’. These places particularly

01:45:06.400 --> 01:45:13.120
impressed Greek travelers to Persia, since the&nbsp;
Greeks at that time had no culture of ornamental

01:45:13.120 --> 01:45:20.640
gardens. In his rhetorical work Oeconomicus,&nbsp;
the Greek writer Xenophon describes with awe

01:45:20.640 --> 01:45:27.360
the flourishing paradaizas that the Persians&nbsp;
built in the Lydian capital of Sardis, which

01:45:27.360 --> 01:45:36.320
he witnessed with his own eyes. He was astonished&nbsp;
at the beauty of the trees within, all planted at

01:45:36.320 --> 01:45:43.760
equal intervals, the long straight rows of waving&nbsp;
branches, the perfect regularity, the rectangular

01:45:43.760 --> 01:45:51.120
symmetry of the whole, and the many sweet scents&nbsp;
which hung about them as they paced the park.

01:45:52.880 --> 01:45:58.640
These gardens also impressed Hebrew&nbsp;
writers, who adopted the word ‘pardes’

01:45:58.640 --> 01:46:04.880
into Hebrew to describe an orchard,
and they may have used these gardens

01:46:04.880 --> 01:46:10.000
as a model for the walled garden of&nbsp;
Eden in the Book of Genesis, which

01:46:10.000 --> 01:46:17.680
is thought to have been written down in&nbsp;
its final form during the Persian period.

01:46:26.480 --> 01:46:31.840
Since earth and water were both considered&nbsp;
sacred elements in Iranian religion,

01:46:31.840 --> 01:46:38.080
it was considered blasphemy to pollute them with&nbsp;
the remains of the dead. Instead, the bodies of

01:46:38.080 --> 01:46:44.560
those deceased were taken into high structures&nbsp;
built on the tops of hills or mountains.

01:46:45.120 --> 01:46:53.200
Today, these have become known as the Towers of&nbsp;
Silence, presided over by Zoroastrian priests known

01:46:53.200 --> 01:47:02.320
as Magi. Here the bodies were laid out and left&nbsp;
for the birds to pick apart, and then the bones

01:47:02.320 --> 01:47:11.440
were bleached by the sun and wind. Herodotus&nbsp;
describes this practice with some distaste.

01:47:13.120 --> 01:47:18.160
So much I can say of them from my own&nbsp;
certain knowledge, but there are other

01:47:18.160 --> 01:47:24.480
matters concerning the dead which are&nbsp;
secretly and obscurely told; how the dead

01:47:24.480 --> 01:47:30.320
bodies of Persians are not buried before&nbsp;
they have been mangled by birds or dogs,

01:47:30.320 --> 01:47:38.480
but this is the way of the Magi. I know for&nbsp;
certain, for they do not conceal the practice.

01:47:39.920 --> 01:47:46.320
It's not known exactly how widespread this&nbsp;
practice was during the Persian period, and

01:47:46.320 --> 01:47:54.000
it was never used for rulers. Later Achaemenid&nbsp;
kings were buried in rock-cut tombs usually

01:47:54.000 --> 01:48:02.960
in the sides of a cliff at a place called&nbsp;Naqsh-i
Rustam, a few kilometers northwest of Persepolis.

01:48:02.960 --> 01:48:07.520
There, the stone walls and floors of&nbsp;
their chambers kept the bodies from

01:48:07.520 --> 01:48:14.240
making contact with the sacred earth beneath&nbsp;
them, and as an added benefit, were visible in

01:48:14.240 --> 01:48:26.480
the distance from the great city, a potent&nbsp;
reminder of the kings that had come before.

01:48:26.480 --> 01:48:32.240
Greeks like Herodotus were also bemused&nbsp;
by the Persians’ custom of each year

01:48:32.240 --> 01:48:38.480
celebrating the day of someone's&nbsp;
birth. Of all days in the year,

01:48:38.480 --> 01:48:44.400
a Persian most distinguishes his birthday,&nbsp;
and celebrates it with a dinner of special

01:48:44.400 --> 01:48:51.120
magnificence. A rich Persian on his birthday&nbsp;
will have an ox or a horse or a camel or a

01:48:51.120 --> 01:49:01.920
donkey baked whole in the oven and served up&nbsp;
at the table, and the poor some smaller beast.

01:49:01.920 --> 01:49:09.280
At these celebrations, it's likely that a great&nbsp;
amount of wine would have flowed. The nomadic

01:49:09.280 --> 01:49:15.840
ancestors of the Persians had likely drunk&nbsp;
out of cups made of hollowed-out cow horns,

01:49:15.840 --> 01:49:22.880
but the Persians had long since replaced&nbsp;
bone for silver and gold. Now they drank

01:49:22.880 --> 01:49:29.280
out of vessels called rhytons that were still&nbsp;
shaped like animal horns but could be wrought

01:49:29.280 --> 01:49:37.680
in ornate patterns in precious metals. Wine&nbsp;
was produced in the upland regions of Persia

01:49:37.680 --> 01:49:44.560
in the area of modern Shiraz, and imported&nbsp;
from vineyards in Syria and elsewhere.

01:49:45.360 --> 01:49:50.160
Persians not only enjoyed wine for its&nbsp;
pleasurable effects, but believed it could

01:49:50.160 --> 01:49:59.280
actually help them consider the world from&nbsp;
a different angle, as Herodotus describes.

01:49:59.280 --> 01:50:04.400
They are very fond of wine. If an&nbsp;
important decision is to be made,

01:50:04.400 --> 01:50:08.720
they discuss the question when they&nbsp;
are drunk, and the following day,

01:50:08.720 --> 01:50:15.360
the master of the house where the discussion was&nbsp;
held submits their decision for reconsideration

01:50:15.360 --> 01:50:24.080
when they are sober. If they still approve it, it&nbsp;
is adopted. If not, it is abandoned. Conversely,

01:50:24.080 --> 01:50:31.440
any decision they make when they are sober is&nbsp;
reconsidered afterwards, when they are drunk.

01:50:32.800 --> 01:50:36.880
However, despite their love&nbsp;
of the good things in life,

01:50:36.880 --> 01:50:46.800
Persians were still governed by strict rules&nbsp;
about behavior in public, as Xenophon recounts.

01:50:46.800 --> 01:50:53.360
There remains even unto this day evidence of their&nbsp;
moderate fare; for even to the present time,

01:50:53.360 --> 01:50:58.960
it is a breach of decorum for a Persian to&nbsp;
spit or to blow his nose. It is a breach of

01:50:58.960 --> 01:51:04.960
decorum also to be seen going apart either to&nbsp;
make water or for anything else of that kind;

01:51:04.960 --> 01:51:18.000
and this would not be possible for them&nbsp;
if they did not lead an abstemious life.

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:24.640
With his vast empire conquered and his rule&nbsp;
steadily solidifying across his domain,

01:51:24.640 --> 01:51:33.040
Cyrus settled down and began to build a grand&nbsp;
palace complex which he would name his capital.

01:51:33.040 --> 01:51:39.280
He elected to build this at the location of&nbsp;
his decisive final battle against the Medes at

01:51:39.280 --> 01:51:48.240
a place called Pasargadae. Archaeology has shown&nbsp;
that the palace that Cyrus built would be of a

01:51:48.240 --> 01:51:56.320
strange and unprecedented design, a garden city&nbsp;
dotted with pavilions and palace structures made

01:51:56.320 --> 01:52:04.080
of stone and decorated in marble. In this&nbsp;
way, it actually mirrored the structure of

01:52:04.080 --> 01:52:11.760
a nomadic camp stretched out over the plain,&nbsp;
but with stone structures instead of tents.

01:52:13.360 --> 01:52:20.400
It was a clear architectural nod to the nomadic&nbsp;
roots of the Persian people, and perhaps the kind

01:52:20.400 --> 01:52:29.360
of habitation in which Cyrus himself felt&nbsp;
the most comfortable; surrounded by nature.

01:52:29.360 --> 01:52:37.440
The defining feature of this palace would be&nbsp;
its garden, a masterpiece of a Persian pairidaiza.

01:52:38.400 --> 01:52:44.480
Modern pollen analysis has shown that&nbsp;
trees like cypress and hazelnut, oak,

01:52:44.480 --> 01:52:52.000
elm, and pistachio were cultivated here. Fed&nbsp;
by water channels cut from dressed stone,

01:52:52.000 --> 01:52:59.840
this paradise would have blossomed even on&nbsp;
this high arid plateau in the middle of Persia.

01:53:00.800 --> 01:53:07.200
The garden was divided into four parts, and&nbsp;
it's thought that this was designed to evoke

01:53:07.200 --> 01:53:13.600
the same phrase that Cyrus would use again&nbsp;
and again whenever he described himself in

01:53:13.600 --> 01:53:27.440
his inscriptions. I am Cyrus, king of the&nbsp;
four quarters of the world. This quartered

01:53:27.440 --> 01:53:33.840
design would become integral to the design of&nbsp;
Persian gardens around the world, which followed

01:53:33.840 --> 01:53:43.200
the style known as ‘chaharbagh’, or ‘four-part gardens’.&nbsp;
In later centuries, these would be found across a

01:53:43.200 --> 01:53:49.600
vast stretch of the Earth, from the gardens of&nbsp;
Seville in southern Spain to those of Northern

01:53:49.600 --> 01:54:00.240
India and the Taj Mahal, but it's a design that&nbsp;
began here in the gardens of Cyrus the Great.

01:54:00.240 --> 01:54:07.360
Construction on the palace of Pasargadae&nbsp;
began in 546 BC, and would continue for

01:54:07.360 --> 01:54:14.720
the next sixteen years. But it would be brought&nbsp;
to a sudden end by an event that must have

01:54:14.720 --> 01:54:21.760
sent shockwaves around the Persian Empire&nbsp;
and beyond. That was the death in the year

01:54:21.760 --> 01:54:41.840
530 of the King of Kings, King of the Four&nbsp;
Quarters of the World, Cyrus the Great.

01:54:41.840 --> 01:54:49.360
Just as with his birth, there are many stories&nbsp;
told of how Cyrus the Great met his end,

01:54:49.360 --> 01:54:57.360
and many of them have the hallmarks of mythology.&nbsp;
What we know with some certainty is that Cyrus

01:54:57.360 --> 01:55:03.280
had decided to expand his empire into the&nbsp;
northeast in the great plain that stretches

01:55:03.280 --> 01:55:12.480
out between the Caspian and Aral seas. Much of the&nbsp;
eastern half of the Persian Empire was unknown to

01:55:12.480 --> 01:55:20.000
the Greeks, and so, our history of it is largely&nbsp;
blank. From the perspective of written history,

01:55:20.000 --> 01:55:27.920
the eastern side of the empire is like the dark&nbsp;
side of the moon, a place always in shadow. But

01:55:27.920 --> 01:55:35.600
according to Herodotus, this region was home&nbsp;
to a warlike people known as the Massagetai.

01:55:36.800 --> 01:55:44.240
The people Herodotus called the Massagetai likely&nbsp;
called themselves something like the Masyaka-ta,

01:55:44.240 --> 01:55:51.360
meaning ‘the fish eating people’, since they made&nbsp;
their livelihood fishing in the Caspian Sea.

01:55:51.360 --> 01:56:00.560
Herodotus describes their simple way of life.&nbsp;
These are said to be a great people and mighty,

01:56:00.560 --> 01:56:08.000
dwelling towards the East and the sunrise, where&nbsp;
men are said to live whose food is raw fish, and

01:56:08.000 --> 01:56:17.920
their customary dress seal skins. The Massagetai&nbsp;
also seemed to have used some kind of drug,

01:56:17.920 --> 01:56:25.440
possibly cannabis, during their ceremonies&nbsp;
and celebrations, as Herodotus recounts.

01:56:27.280 --> 01:56:32.640
Assembling in companies and kindling&nbsp;
a fire, the people sit around it and

01:56:32.640 --> 01:56:38.640
throw a plant into the flames. Then the&nbsp;
smell of it as it burns makes them drunk

01:56:38.640 --> 01:56:44.800
as the Greeks are with wine, and more and&nbsp;
more drunk as more is thrown on the fire,

01:56:44.800 --> 01:56:54.720
‘til at last they rise up and dance, and even&nbsp;
sing. Such is said to be their way of life.

01:56:54.720 --> 01:57:00.880
Perhaps realizing the dangerous nature of the&nbsp;
campaign he was embarking on, Cyrus made sure to

01:57:00.880 --> 01:57:08.880
settle the matter of his succession before he set&nbsp;
out. He named his son Cambyses as his successor,

01:57:08.880 --> 01:57:16.640
and also made him regent of the empire in his&nbsp;
absence. He also had a younger son, Bardiya, and to

01:57:16.640 --> 01:57:24.480
this man he gave a large and wealthy area in the&nbsp;
East, which he also exempted from taxes. It was a

01:57:24.480 --> 01:57:34.560
clear sign that he hoped his sons would manage&nbsp;
to live in peace once he was no longer around.

01:57:34.560 --> 01:57:43.040
According to Herodotus, the ruler of&nbsp;
the Massagetai was a queen named Tomyris.

01:57:43.040 --> 01:57:50.960
Now, at this time, the Massagetai were ruled by&nbsp;
a queen called Tomyris, whose husband was dead.

01:57:50.960 --> 01:57:57.760
Cyrus sent a message with a pretense of wooing&nbsp;
her for his wife, but Tomyris would have none of

01:57:57.760 --> 01:58:07.280
his advance, well understanding that he wooed&nbsp;
not her, but her kingdom. After this peaceful

01:58:07.280 --> 01:58:14.480
approach failed, Herodotus claims that Cyrus lay&nbsp;
an ambush at a feast, in which he served strong

01:58:14.480 --> 01:58:24.560
wine to a group of Massagetai noblemen, among them&nbsp;
the son of the queen Tomyris. These nomadic men,

01:58:24.560 --> 01:58:30.480
unused to strong wine, were soon roaring&nbsp;
drunk, and in this helpless state,

01:58:30.480 --> 01:58:38.240
Cyrus' men fell on them and killed them all.&nbsp;
After this deceitful act, the heartbroken Tomyris

01:58:38.240 --> 01:58:46.560
rallied her forces and rode out to crush&nbsp;
Cyrus with the rage of a grieving mother.

01:58:46.560 --> 01:58:53.360
There perished the greater part of the Persian&nbsp;
army, and there fell Cyrus himself. Tomyris

01:58:53.360 --> 01:59:00.000
filled a skin with human blood and sought&nbsp;
for Cyrus' body among the Persian dead.

01:59:00.000 --> 01:59:05.680
When she found it, she put his head into&nbsp;
the skin and spoke these words of insult

01:59:05.680 --> 01:59:17.680
to the dead man; “Even as I threatened, so&nbsp;
will I do, and give thee thy fill of blood.”

01:59:17.680 --> 01:59:25.600
Exciting and poetic as it is, this stirring tale&nbsp;
of treachery and revenge is likely a folk tale.

01:59:25.600 --> 01:59:28.880
Herodotus himself points&nbsp;
out that even at the time,

01:59:28.880 --> 01:59:35.280
multiple versions of the great man's&nbsp;
death were already circulating.

01:59:35.280 --> 01:59:46.240
Many stories are related to Cyrus' death; this&nbsp;
that I have told is the worthiest of credence.

01:59:49.360 --> 01:59:58.640
In contrast, the Greek writer Xenophon has Cyrus&nbsp;
die peacefully in bed, surrounded by his sons.

01:59:58.640 --> 02:00:04.960
The Greek Ctesias, who lived in Persia, describes&nbsp;
him being wounded in battle against the Scythians,

02:00:04.960 --> 02:00:11.680
but coming home to his palace at Pasargadae,&nbsp;
where he later died of his wounds. Ultimately,

02:00:11.680 --> 02:00:18.720
we can never know the truth, which must lie&nbsp;
somewhere between these accounts. What we

02:00:18.720 --> 02:00:26.560
know is that in the year 530 BC, Cyrus the&nbsp;
Great died, likely on campaign in the East.

02:00:27.360 --> 02:00:33.600
He would be buried in a modest tomb at his&nbsp;
palace of Pasargadae, a monument that combines

02:00:33.600 --> 02:00:40.000
some elements of the mound tombs of Lydia that he&nbsp;
had seen on his march to Sardis all those years

02:00:40.000 --> 02:00:48.000
before, and others based on the stepped design of&nbsp;
a Mesopotamian or Elamite ziggurat, the stone base

02:00:48.000 --> 02:00:56.480
raising him above the sacred earth in accordance&nbsp;
with Iranian tradition. The Greek traveler Arrian

02:00:56.480 --> 02:01:02.560
passed through the region some centuries later,&nbsp;
and wrote one description of the tomb's remaining

02:01:02.560 --> 02:01:10.800
finery. The tomb of the famous Cyrus was in the&nbsp;
royal park at Pasargadae, and around it a grove of

02:01:10.800 --> 02:01:18.160
all kinds of trees had been planted. The park was&nbsp;
also watered by a stream, and high grass grew in

02:01:18.160 --> 02:01:25.360
the meadow. In the building lay a golden coffin&nbsp;
in which the body of Cyrus had been buried. A

02:01:25.360 --> 02:01:31.920
carpet of Babylonian tapestry with purple rugs&nbsp;
formed the bedding. Upon it were also a Median

02:01:31.920 --> 02:01:40.800
coat with sleeves and other tunics. Perhaps since&nbsp;
Iranians before that point typically didn't use

02:01:40.800 --> 02:01:47.600
gravestones or monuments for their burials, there&nbsp;
is a distinctly defensive tone to the inscription

02:01:47.600 --> 02:01:56.000
reportedly carved over the tomb. Upon the tomb,&nbsp;
an inscription in Persian letters had been placed,

02:01:56.000 --> 02:02:04.800
which bore the following meaning in the Persian&nbsp;
language. O man, I am Cyrus, son of Cambyses, who

02:02:04.800 --> 02:02:16.320
founded the empire of the Persians, and was king&nbsp;
of Asia. Do not therefore grudge me this monument.

02:02:16.320 --> 02:02:24.640
With the death of Cyrus, his son Cambyses&nbsp;
ascended to the throne. Cambyses' name in

02:02:24.640 --> 02:02:31.920
Old Persian was Kamboojiya. He was the son and&nbsp;
heir of a king who had started with virtually

02:02:31.920 --> 02:02:39.040
nothing, the ruler of a small tribe, and with&nbsp;
cunning tactical genius and political acumen

02:02:39.040 --> 02:02:44.960
had carved out the world's largest empire&nbsp;
in only three decades, and brought countless

02:02:44.960 --> 02:02:53.360
people under his banner. The expectation&nbsp;
on this prince must have been immense,

02:02:53.360 --> 02:03:13.440
but unfortunately, he would not live&nbsp;
up to the promise of his father.

02:03:13.440 --> 02:03:20.400
There seems to have been some question over&nbsp;
the abilities of Cambyses from the very start.

02:03:20.400 --> 02:03:27.280
In 538 BC, his father had named him governor&nbsp;
of Babylon and its surrounding areas, but he

02:03:27.280 --> 02:03:34.000
was removed from that position after only&nbsp;
nine months. The reason for this is unclear,

02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:39.520
but we might take it as a warning sign that&nbsp;
all would not be well when this young prince

02:03:39.520 --> 02:03:46.800
took the throne. According to the account&nbsp;
of Herodotus, one of his first acts was

02:03:46.800 --> 02:03:53.040
to have his brother Bardiya secretly killed,&nbsp;
ensuring that no rival to his rule remained

02:03:53.040 --> 02:04:03.760
alive. To do this job, he enlisted the&nbsp;
help of a priest or Magi named Gaumata.

02:04:03.760 --> 02:04:10.560
Cambyses, as the Egyptians say,&nbsp;
became absolutely mad, and the

02:04:10.560 --> 02:04:15.920
first of his evil deeds was that he&nbsp;
put to death his brother, Bardiya,

02:04:15.920 --> 02:04:21.760
who was of the same father and the same&nbsp;
mother as himself. Some say that he took

02:04:21.760 --> 02:04:32.320
him out to hunt and there slew him; others that he&nbsp;
brought him to the Erythraian Sea and drowned him.

02:04:32.320 --> 02:04:38.240
When this Magi Gaumata sent him word that&nbsp;
his brother was dead and his reign secure,

02:04:38.240 --> 02:04:45.120
Cambyses set his sights on further territorial&nbsp;
expansion and the one great prize that would

02:04:45.120 --> 02:04:57.120
outdo the conquests of his esteemed father,&nbsp;
the ancient and wealthy kingdom of Egypt.

02:05:02.480 --> 02:05:10.800
Egypt at this time was undergoing something of&nbsp;a
renaissance. Under the long forty-four-year rule of its

02:05:10.800 --> 02:05:17.200
pharaoh Ahmose II, the lands of the Nile&nbsp;
Valley had prospered and regained some of

02:05:17.200 --> 02:05:23.840
the glory that had characterized its golden&nbsp;
ages of the Old, Middle, and New Kingdoms.

02:05:24.560 --> 02:05:32.320
But in 526 BC, this great pharaoh died, and&nbsp;
the rule of Egypt passed on to his son,

02:05:32.320 --> 02:05:41.120
a man named Psamtik III. Cambyses, perhaps knowing&nbsp;
all too well the pressure of trying to live up

02:05:41.120 --> 02:05:48.560
to a high-achieving father, immediately&nbsp;
prepared to invade the lands of Egypt.

02:05:48.560 --> 02:05:57.280
The very next year, in the spring of 525&nbsp;
BC, Cambyses set out. To help him on his

02:05:57.280 --> 02:06:05.120
campaign, he recruited an enormous force&nbsp;
drawn from all corners of the empire.

02:06:05.120 --> 02:06:11.040
A Persian army of this time was made up of a&nbsp;
patchwork of different units, who each fought

02:06:11.040 --> 02:06:17.920
in the traditional manner of their homeland.&nbsp;
There were long-speared cavalry from Lydia,

02:06:17.920 --> 02:06:23.920
shielded spearmen from Babylonia,&nbsp;
archers from the Medes, and Elamites.

02:06:23.920 --> 02:06:29.520
He also recruited skilled sailors from the&nbsp;
Phoenician cities on the Palestinian coast,

02:06:29.520 --> 02:06:37.280
along with their swift ships, and heavily-armored&nbsp;
Greek hoplites from the Ionian cities of Asia.

02:06:38.080 --> 02:06:43.600
These Greek warriors would become known&nbsp;
as the bronze men from the sea, since

02:06:43.600 --> 02:06:51.520
they had trained to fight with heavy&nbsp;
armor covering most of their bodies.

02:06:51.520 --> 02:06:58.160
With this force of perhaps 50,000 soldiers,&nbsp;
Cambyses set out to Egypt, sending half

02:06:58.160 --> 02:07:04.880
by land and half by sea on the Phoenician&nbsp;
ships, and met at the port town of Pelusium,

02:07:04.880 --> 02:07:13.520
the gateway to the Nile Delta. At Pelusium,&nbsp;
sources indicate that the pharaoh of Egypt

02:07:13.520 --> 02:07:20.560
had sent a man named Wedjahorresnet to command&nbsp;
much of the Egyptian fleet, with orders to repel

02:07:20.560 --> 02:07:29.760
the advancing army of the Persians. But this&nbsp;
man, for unknown reasons, decided to defect.

02:07:29.760 --> 02:07:35.840
Whether bribed or threatened, when Cambyses&nbsp;
arrived, Wedjahorresnet turned his ships

02:07:35.840 --> 02:07:44.160
over to the Persian army and swore allegiance to&nbsp;
Cambyses. Now without a navy and cut off on the

02:07:44.160 --> 02:07:56.400
waterways of the Nile Delta, the Egyptian&nbsp;
army was swiftly surrounded and defeated.

02:07:56.400 --> 02:08:02.960
Wedjahorresnet was suitably rewarded&nbsp;
for his part in the battle. One inscribed

02:08:02.960 --> 02:08:07.360
statue now kept in the Vatican&nbsp;
describes the strange trajectory

02:08:07.360 --> 02:08:15.840
of his life, and perhaps gives some sense&nbsp;
of why he refused to fight the Persians.

02:08:15.840 --> 02:08:22.320
The great king of all foreign lands, Cambyses,&nbsp;
came to Egypt, bringing the foreigners of every

02:08:22.320 --> 02:08:27.280
foreign country with him. When he had&nbsp;
taken possession of the entire country

02:08:27.280 --> 02:08:33.360
and he was made great sovereign of Egypt, his&nbsp;
majesty appointed me his chief physician.

02:08:33.360 --> 02:08:38.160
I protected the inhabitants from the very large&nbsp;
troubles which had come from all over the

02:08:38.160 --> 02:08:47.760
whole country, and I defended the meek against&nbsp;
the powerful. I saved those who were afraid.

02:08:49.680 --> 02:08:57.680
Cambyses was crowned as the pharaoh of Egypt in&nbsp;
August 525 BC, only a few months after setting out

02:08:57.680 --> 02:09:07.200
on campaign in the city of Sais in the western Nile&nbsp;
Delta. There he was awarded the pschent, the double

02:09:07.200 --> 02:09:14.080
crown that combined the white bulbous crown of&nbsp;
Upper Egypt with the red crown of Lower Egypt,

02:09:14.080 --> 02:09:21.360
a symbol that had been worn by Egyptian pharaohs&nbsp;
for more than two and a half thousand years.

02:09:21.360 --> 02:09:29.440
But if Herodotus is to be believed, Cambyses&nbsp;
didn't share his father's diplomatic streak.

02:09:29.440 --> 02:09:41.680
When he captured the pharaoh Psamtik, he seems to have&nbsp;
enjoyed humiliating him with a cruel spectacle.

02:09:41.680 --> 02:09:49.840
On the tenth day after the surrender of the walled&nbsp;
city of Memphis, Cambyses took Psamtik, king of

02:09:49.840 --> 02:09:56.560
Egypt, who had reigned for six months, and confined&nbsp;
him in the outer part of the city with other

02:09:56.560 --> 02:10:04.720
Egyptians to insult him. He dressed the daughter&nbsp;
of the king as a slave and sent her out with a

02:10:04.720 --> 02:10:11.520
pitcher to fetch water, together with other girls&nbsp;
from the families of the leading men. So, when the

02:10:11.520 --> 02:10:18.640
girls went out before their fathers’ eyes, crying&nbsp;
and lamenting, all the rest answered with cries

02:10:18.640 --> 02:10:27.200
and weeping, seeing their children abused,&nbsp;
but Psamtik only bowed himself to the ground.

02:10:29.600 --> 02:10:37.680
Next, the king's son was paraded before him in&nbsp;
chains, to be led to his death. But once again,

02:10:37.680 --> 02:10:42.400
the king did not cry. It was only when he saw an

02:10:42.400 --> 02:10:48.560
old servant of his walking among&nbsp;
the crowd that his mask cracked.

02:10:50.080 --> 02:10:55.920
After these two had gone, it happened&nbsp;
that there was one of his companions,

02:10:55.920 --> 02:11:01.680
a man passed his prime who had lost&nbsp;
all his possessions, and begged of the

02:11:01.680 --> 02:11:10.000
army. This man now went out before Pharaoh&nbsp;
Psamtik and the Egyptians. When Psamtik saw him,

02:11:10.000 --> 02:11:16.960
he broke into loud weeping, striking his&nbsp;
head and calling on his companion by name.

02:11:19.120 --> 02:11:26.320
In Herodotus, Cambyses comes across as a&nbsp;
sadist and a tyrant. He describes him brutally

02:11:26.320 --> 02:11:33.040
suppressing the religion of Egypt, destroying&nbsp;
temples as a punishment for rebellions, flogging

02:11:33.040 --> 02:11:40.640
priests, and even killing the sacred Apis bull,&nbsp;
a beloved and holy animal in the city of Memphis,

02:11:40.640 --> 02:11:48.480
believed to be the living offspring of the god&nbsp;
Hathor. But actual Egyptian sources undermine

02:11:48.480 --> 02:11:56.880
this view. They show that Cambyses worked hard to&nbsp;
ingratiate himself with his Egyptian subjects. Far

02:11:56.880 --> 02:12:03.520
from murdering an Apis bull, he actually attended&nbsp;
the funeral services when one of these bulls died,

02:12:03.520 --> 02:12:12.000
and no Egyptian sources mention its murder.&nbsp;
But the very existence of these stories, still

02:12:12.000 --> 02:12:18.160
circulating in Egypt about eighty years later&nbsp;
when Herodotus passed through, shows us that

02:12:18.160 --> 02:12:25.120
Cambyses was unpopular. He appears to have&nbsp;
attempted to reform the Egyptian tax system

02:12:25.120 --> 02:12:30.720
so that citizens no longer paid their taxes to&nbsp;
the temples, something that would have enraged

02:12:30.720 --> 02:12:38.400
the ancient and powerful priestly class. While&nbsp;
Cyrus had skillfully absorbed people into the

02:12:38.400 --> 02:12:44.720
empire by listening to what they wanted and&nbsp;
ensuring he gave it to them, his son Cambyses

02:12:44.720 --> 02:12:53.520
tried to meddle in local affairs, and alienated&nbsp;
his people. Whether Egypt would have eventually

02:12:53.520 --> 02:13:02.240
erupted in rebellion against Cambyses, we&nbsp;
will never know. That's because in 522 BC,

02:13:02.240 --> 02:13:13.200
only four years into his rule as pharaoh, Cambyses&nbsp;
got some remarkable and extremely disturbing news.

02:13:13.200 --> 02:13:18.320
Back in Babylon, a man had shown up&nbsp;
claiming to be his younger brother,

02:13:18.320 --> 02:13:27.760
Bardiya, and this man had&nbsp;
declared himself king of Persia.

02:13:38.400 --> 02:13:41.840
In the version of this story&nbsp;
that Herodotus gives us,

02:13:41.840 --> 02:13:48.000
Cambyses had already secretly killed his&nbsp;
younger brother, Bardiya. For this reason,

02:13:48.000 --> 02:13:53.680
he immediately realized that this Bardiya&nbsp;
must be an impostor, and the only person

02:13:53.680 --> 02:14:03.840
it could be is the only other person who knew&nbsp;
that Bardiya was dead, the Magi named Gaumata.

02:14:03.840 --> 02:14:09.760
Realizing that he might be about to lose his&nbsp;
kingdom, Cambyses leapt onto his horse and set

02:14:09.760 --> 02:14:20.560
out to fight this impostor, but he would never&nbsp;
reach the battlefield, as Herodotus describes.

02:14:20.560 --> 02:14:28.160
Having wept his fill in great grief for all&nbsp;
his mishap, he leapt upon his horse with

02:14:28.160 --> 02:14:36.000
intent to march forthwith to Susa against&nbsp;
the Magi. As he mounted, the scabbard knob

02:14:36.000 --> 02:14:43.680
of his sword slipped off, and the naked blade&nbsp;
struck his thigh, wounding him. After this,

02:14:43.680 --> 02:14:51.200
the bone became gangrened and the thigh&nbsp;
rotted, which took off Cambyses, son of Cyrus,

02:14:51.200 --> 02:15:03.600
who had reigned in all seven years and five&nbsp;
months, and left no sons or daughters at all.

02:15:03.600 --> 02:15:12.160
This was an unbelievable situation. With Cambyses&nbsp;
dead, the impostor Bardiya now ruled the empire.

02:15:13.520 --> 02:15:20.160
This man, by a grand coincidence, happened to be&nbsp;
the spitting image of the disappeared prince, a

02:15:20.160 --> 02:15:26.240
likeness so perfect that all but one of Bardiya's&nbsp;
wives failed to notice the difference between

02:15:26.240 --> 02:15:34.640
them. This wife, a woman named Phaedyme, alerted&nbsp;
some members of the court. Aghast that an

02:15:34.640 --> 02:15:41.360
impostor was sitting on the throne, these six&nbsp;
men began a plot to overthrow the false king.

02:15:42.880 --> 02:15:47.040
To help them in their plan, they&nbsp;
recruited the help of a faithful

02:15:47.040 --> 02:15:52.720
general of the dead king Cambyses and a&nbsp;
distant member of the royal family,

02:15:52.720 --> 02:16:03.920
a man who in Old Persian was named Daari-vaush.&nbsp;
His name would be rendered into Greek as Darius.

02:16:03.920 --> 02:16:08.400
Now came to Susa Darius, son of Hystaspes,

02:16:08.400 --> 02:16:15.200
from Persia, and on his coming, the six&nbsp;
Persians resolved to make Darius, too, their

02:16:15.200 --> 02:16:24.640
comrade. The seven then met and gave&nbsp;
each other pledges and spoke together.

02:16:24.640 --> 02:16:32.160
Darius and his co-conspirators chose their&nbsp;
moment, then struck. They drew their daggers

02:16:32.160 --> 02:16:38.880
and burst into the false king's apartment while&nbsp;
he slept, managing to overpower his bodyguards.

02:16:39.840 --> 02:16:44.720
Finally, the conspirators found themselves&nbsp;
in a bitter hand-to-hand struggle,

02:16:44.720 --> 02:16:50.560
which Herodotus renders in thrilling fashion.

02:16:50.560 --> 02:16:57.840
Two of the seven, Darius and Gobryas, hurled&nbsp;
themselves into the chamber with him. Gobryas and

02:16:57.840 --> 02:17:04.560
the Magi grappled together, while Darius stood&nbsp;
perplexed in the darkness, fearing to strike.

02:17:04.560 --> 02:17:13.040
Gobryas, seeing Darius stand idle, cried to know&nbsp;
why he did not strike. “For fear of stabbing you,”

02:17:13.040 --> 02:17:20.080
quote Darius. “Nay,” said Gobryas, “thrust with&nbsp;
your sword, though it be through both of

02:17:20.080 --> 02:17:31.200
us.” So, Darius thrust with his dagger, and by&nbsp;
good luck it was the Magi that he stabbed.

02:17:31.200 --> 02:17:36.960
The impostor king lay dead, and in the&nbsp;
aftermath of this assassination, the

02:17:36.960 --> 02:17:44.960
plotters swept in to consolidate their power.&nbsp;
Finally, as the dust of the coup settled,

02:17:44.960 --> 02:17:51.520
Darius was made king, and the line&nbsp;
of Cyrus the Great was saved.

02:17:53.040 --> 02:17:59.040
This official version of events would&nbsp;
be immortalized not only by Herodotus,

02:17:59.040 --> 02:18:05.280
but also chiseled into the limestone&nbsp;
face of a cliff on Mount Bisitun, a hundred

02:18:05.280 --> 02:18:12.399
meters above the ground, and visible for all to&nbsp;
see on the road from Ecbatana to Babylon.

02:18:12.399 --> 02:18:17.920
In this Bisitun inscription, Darius&nbsp;
recounts the exact story that Herodotus

02:18:17.920 --> 02:18:34.240
does of Cambyses killing his brother in secret&nbsp;
and the impostor Bardiya taking the throne.

02:18:38.240 --> 02:18:46.399
A son of Cyrus, named Cambyses, one of our&nbsp;
dynasty, was king here before me. That

02:18:46.399 --> 02:18:56.879
Cambyses had a brother, Bardiya by name, and Cambyses&nbsp;
slew this Bardiya. There was a certain man, a Magi,

02:18:56.880 --> 02:19:04.800
Gaumata by name, who raised a rebellion,&nbsp;
saying, "I am Bardiya, the son of Cyrus,

02:19:04.800 --> 02:19:11.760
the brother of Cambyses.” He seized the&nbsp;
kingdom. The people feared him exceedingly,

02:19:11.760 --> 02:19:20.960
for he slew many who had known the real&nbsp;
Bardiya so that no one would recognize him.

02:19:35.600 --> 02:19:39.680
The inscription is accompanied&nbsp;
by a carving showing Darius with

02:19:39.680 --> 02:19:46.720
one foot placed on the fallen body of&nbsp;
the Magi Gaumata, beside which Darius

02:19:46.720 --> 02:19:57.040
recounts in his own words the plot to&nbsp;
overthrow and murder the impostor king.

02:20:00.720 --> 02:20:10.479
There was none who dared to act against Gaumata,&nbsp;
the Magi, until I came. Then I prayed to Ahura Mazda.

02:20:10.479 --> 02:20:19.280
Ahura Mazda brought me help. On the tenth day of&nbsp;
the month, with a few men, I slew that Gaumata,

02:20:19.280 --> 02:20:39.599
the Magi. I dispossessed him of the kingdom. By&nbsp;
the grace of the Ahura Mazda, I became king.

02:20:42.720 --> 02:20:49.120
This remarkable story is so outlandish that&nbsp;
many modern historians actually don't believe

02:20:49.120 --> 02:20:56.880
it at all. They propose an alternate version of&nbsp;
events, but this other version is in some ways

02:20:56.880 --> 02:21:03.120
just as incredible. It's now thought that&nbsp;
the man who rose up in rebellion against

02:21:03.120 --> 02:21:08.880
Cambyses was actually his younger brother,&nbsp;
Bardiya, and that everything that makes up

02:21:08.880 --> 02:21:15.520
the core of Herodotus' account and the&nbsp;
Bisitun inscription was an audacious ruse

02:21:15.520 --> 02:21:22.480
by the man who had ultimately seized&nbsp;
the throne, the usurper king Darius.

02:21:23.920 --> 02:21:30.240
We can never know whether all the conspirators&nbsp;
were in on the lie or whether Darius had actually

02:21:30.240 --> 02:21:37.439
convinced them that Bardiya was an impostor.&nbsp;
Either way, the official propaganda of Darius'

02:21:37.439 --> 02:21:45.519
new regime clearly won the day, now inscribed&nbsp;
in stone at Mount Bisitun and clearly circulating

02:21:45.520 --> 02:21:51.439
among the people to such an extent that they&nbsp;
would recount it to Herodotus generations later.

02:21:51.439 --> 02:21:59.359
The story of the impostor Bardiya had now, for&nbsp;
all intents and purposes, become the truth.

02:21:59.359 --> 02:22:11.200
Darius was now the new King of Kings,&nbsp;
King of the Four Quarters of the World.

02:22:16.800 --> 02:22:23.120
It's clear from the Bisitun inscription that&nbsp;
from the moment Darius seized power, he faced

02:22:23.120 --> 02:22:31.359
an understandable crisis of legitimacy. He was&nbsp;
not the direct descendant of Cyrus the Great,

02:22:31.359 --> 02:22:39.040
but claimed to be a distant cousin of the&nbsp;
great empire builder. In a culture completely

02:22:39.040 --> 02:22:44.960
dominated by the idea of telling the truth, the&nbsp;
creeping suspicion that the new king might have

02:22:44.960 --> 02:22:53.680
lied his way to the throne must have eroded many&nbsp;
people's faith in his rule. Perhaps as a result,

02:22:53.680 --> 02:23:04.560
more impostors were now popping up all over&nbsp;
the land, as the Bisitun inscription recounts.

02:23:10.160 --> 02:23:21.280
After I had slain Gaumata, the Magi, a certain man named&nbsp;
Ashina raised a rebellion in Elam, and he spoke thus

02:23:21.280 --> 02:23:30.240
unto the people of Elam; “I am king in Elam.”&nbsp;
Thereupon, the people of Elam became rebellious,

02:23:30.240 --> 02:23:38.080
and a certain Babylonian named Nidintu-Bel&nbsp;
raised a rebellion in Babylon. He lied to

02:23:38.080 --> 02:23:54.399
the people, saying, "I am Nebuchadnezzar,&nbsp;
the son of Nabonidus.”

02:23:54.399 --> 02:23:59.759
Whether these people were actually lying&nbsp;
about their identities or whether Darius

02:23:59.760 --> 02:24:06.399
was now calling all of his enemies impostors,&nbsp;
we can never know, but while he set out to

02:24:06.399 --> 02:24:18.160
crush these rebellions, more broke out&nbsp;
in virtually every corner of the empire.

02:24:18.160 --> 02:24:28.080
While I was in Babylon, these provinces revolted&nbsp;
from me; Persia, Elam, Media, Assyria, Egypt,

02:24:28.080 --> 02:24:42.160
Parthia, Margiana, Sattagydia, and Scythia.
At least one of these rebel leaders also claimed

02:24:42.160 --> 02:24:49.920
to be the missing brother, Bardiya, something that&nbsp;
must have thrown up even more confusion. It was a

02:24:49.920 --> 02:24:57.120
time when people's shared reality was becoming&nbsp;
completely untethered, and now no one knew who

02:24:57.120 --> 02:25:05.680
the rightful king was. For a time, it must have&nbsp;
looked like the vast empire was about to collapse

02:25:05.680 --> 02:25:14.800
entirely, but this was not to be the case. That's&nbsp;
because Darius seems to have been an exceptionally

02:25:14.800 --> 02:25:22.560
talented general, and gathered a number of capable&nbsp;
allies among the Medes, Persians, and Armenians.

02:25:23.359 --> 02:25:30.000
These loyal generals swept around the empire,&nbsp;
putting down one rebellion after another, and

02:25:30.000 --> 02:25:37.040
crucifying each of their leaders in&nbsp;
cruel public displays of brutality.

02:25:37.040 --> 02:25:49.120
In just his first year of rule, Darius claimed&nbsp;to
have put down no fewer than nineteen rebellions.

02:25:56.800 --> 02:26:05.840
This is what I have done. By the grace of Ahura
Mazda, have I always acted. After I became king,

02:26:05.840 --> 02:26:12.479
I fought nineteen battles in a single year,&nbsp;
and by the grace of a Ahura Mazda,

02:26:12.479 --> 02:26:22.639
I overthrew nine kings, and I made them captive. As&nbsp;
to these provinces which revolted, lies made them

02:26:22.640 --> 02:26:32.240
revolt so that they deceived the people. King&nbsp;
Darius says, "You who shall be king hereafter,

02:26:32.240 --> 02:26:44.559
protect yourself vigorously from lies and punish&nbsp;
the liars well. Then may your country be secure.”

02:26:52.880 --> 02:26:59.520
To address his crisis of legitimacy, Darius&nbsp;
set about marrying every available woman he

02:26:59.520 --> 02:27:06.960
could find descended from the family of Cyrus&nbsp;
the Great, including two of Cyrus' daughters.

02:27:06.960 --> 02:27:13.359
In this way, he interjected himself and&nbsp;
his sons into the line of succession, and

02:27:13.359 --> 02:27:23.040
silenced his critics. Darius even went so far&nbsp;
as to create a legendary common ancestor, who

02:27:23.040 --> 02:27:30.479
he gave the name Ha-khaa-manish. This figure&nbsp;
would be called Achaemenes by the Greeks, and

02:27:30.479 --> 02:27:35.919
it's by this name that the bloodline&nbsp;
of Cyrus is often called today the

02:27:35.920 --> 02:27:45.040
Achaemenids, even though Cyrus himself never&nbsp;
mentioned the name in his inscriptions.

02:27:45.040 --> 02:27:53.040
To make this deception complete, Darius even&nbsp;
sent stonemasons to Cyrus' palace at Pasargadae

02:27:53.040 --> 02:27:59.280
in a shameless attempt to rewrite history&nbsp;
and link the great king with his own line.

02:28:00.319 --> 02:28:18.399
These men carved a simple message into the&nbsp;
stone pillars in the voice of the previous king.

02:28:19.200 --> 02:28:24.559
I am Cyrus the king, an Achaemenid.
The only thing that gives the game away to&nbsp;
modern archaeologists is that this message

02:28:24.560 --> 02:28:30.240
was carved in a type of cuneiform alphabet&nbsp;
that would not be in use until the reign

02:28:30.240 --> 02:28:38.000
of Darius, since in other inscriptions Darius&nbsp;
boasts about introducing it. For this reason,

02:28:38.000 --> 02:28:44.880
most historians believe that&nbsp;
it was not written by Cyrus.

02:28:53.680 --> 02:28:59.840
Eventually, after three years of near ceaseless&nbsp;
fighting, the rebellions burned themselves

02:28:59.840 --> 02:29:08.000
out like wildfires running out of dry brush, and&nbsp;
Darius was able to settle down into a relatively

02:29:08.000 --> 02:29:16.560
stable rule. From that rocky start,&nbsp;
Darius underwent a campaign of expansion,

02:29:16.560 --> 02:29:25.040
especially in the East. Conquest of parts&nbsp;
of India had begun under Cyrus the Great,

02:29:25.040 --> 02:29:31.600
but Darius pushed the empire's boundaries right&nbsp;
up to the area of the Punjab in Northern India,

02:29:31.600 --> 02:29:38.479
conquering virtually all of what is today&nbsp;
Pakistan. Although sources on this side of

02:29:38.479 --> 02:29:43.919
the empire are scant, it's worth remembering&nbsp;
that the Persian Empire was a territory that

02:29:43.920 --> 02:29:50.319
straddled worlds, from the humid riverlands&nbsp;
of India to the Eurasian Steppe in the north,

02:29:50.319 --> 02:29:57.679
the Indian Ocean to the south, and Europe,&nbsp;
North Africa, and the Mediterranean in the west.

02:29:59.120 --> 02:30:07.120
Darius now ruled over a land area of 5.5&nbsp;
million square kilometers, larger than the Roman

02:30:07.120 --> 02:30:14.160
Empire at its height, and with an estimated&nbsp;
population of as many as 20 million people.

02:30:14.160 --> 02:30:20.160
With a world population at the time of little&nbsp;
more than 100 million, this means that as

02:30:20.160 --> 02:30:29.040
much as 20% of the world's population&nbsp;
now lived in Darius' Persian Empire.

02:30:29.040 --> 02:30:34.640
But throughout the years of rebellion,&nbsp;
Darius had seen just how fragile the

02:30:34.640 --> 02:30:40.960
empire could be. He was determined&nbsp;
to bring about a number of reforms

02:30:40.960 --> 02:30:48.319
designed to strengthen it and turn it&nbsp;
into a power that could last. To help

02:30:48.319 --> 02:30:54.479
him with the administration of this unwieldy&nbsp;
territory, Darius reorganized the empire,

02:30:54.479 --> 02:31:03.439
dividing it into 20 regions over which governors&nbsp;
ruled. These governors were called kh-sha-thra-pavan,

02:31:03.439 --> 02:31:12.719
which would enter Greek as the word ‘satrap’. These&nbsp;
regions would thus become known as satrapies.

02:31:14.000 --> 02:31:22.000
Darius also issued a standard currency&nbsp;
based on gold and silver coins called darics,

02:31:22.000 --> 02:31:30.319
mostly used in the Western Empire. These were&nbsp;
stamped with an image of a king holding a bow,

02:31:30.319 --> 02:31:37.200
and would soon be found all around the&nbsp;
ancient world. He also standardized a

02:31:37.200 --> 02:31:47.920
system of weights and measures, allowing for a&nbsp;
level of coordination in the Achaemenid economy.

02:31:47.920 --> 02:31:53.760
The economy is actually one of the few areas&nbsp;
where the Persians themselves are able to

02:31:53.760 --> 02:32:03.120
speak in the light of history, and that is due&nbsp;
to one remarkable find that occurred in 1933.

02:32:04.880 --> 02:32:12.479
In that year, archaeologists excavating the ruined&nbsp;
palaces of Persepolis uncovered two small chambers

02:32:12.479 --> 02:32:20.399
within a bastion along the fortification wall at&nbsp;
the edge of the great stone terrace. There, they

02:32:20.399 --> 02:32:28.080
discovered a vast cache of tens of thousands&nbsp;
of clay tablets and fragments. These texts,

02:32:28.080 --> 02:32:34.960
which today are known as the Persepolis Fortification&nbsp;
Tablets, offer a rare glimpse into the workings

02:32:34.960 --> 02:32:43.040
of the Achaemenid administrative system. They are&nbsp;
written almost exclusively in Elamite, but some

02:32:43.040 --> 02:32:51.359
also appear in Phrygian, Aramaic, Old Persian, and&nbsp;
even Greek, and record the collection, transfer, and

02:32:51.359 --> 02:32:58.080
storage of goods in the region around Persepolis,&nbsp;
controlling the movements of grain and fruit,

02:32:58.080 --> 02:33:06.080
sheep, goats, cattle and poultry, as well&nbsp;
as flour, bread, beer, wine, fruits, oil,

02:33:06.080 --> 02:33:13.680
meat, and animal hides. These resources were&nbsp;
distributed to temples, members of the royal

02:33:13.680 --> 02:33:23.200
family, courtiers, priests, religious officials,&nbsp;
administrators, travelers, laborers, and artisans.

02:33:23.200 --> 02:33:31.359
The following tablet written in Elamite shows&nbsp;
the transfer of barley in the year 501 BC.

02:33:33.680 --> 02:33:39.840
130 liters of barley from the possessions of&nbsp;
Amavrta have been received by Barik-'El as his

02:33:39.840 --> 02:33:47.840
rations. Given in the town of Ithema,&nbsp;
in the 21st year in the month Shibar.

02:33:47.840 --> 02:33:56.080
Other tablets describe payments in&nbsp;
silver made to important officials.

02:33:56.080 --> 02:34:02.559
To Shaka the treasurer, Budkama declares that&nbsp;
Herdkama, the Egyptian, was the chief of a team

02:34:02.560 --> 02:34:08.880
of 100 laborers, and is entitled to three&nbsp;
karsha and two and a half shekels of silver

02:34:08.880 --> 02:34:20.399
as his wage. The historian Lloyd Llewellyn&nbsp;
Jones describes this administrative regime.

02:34:20.399 --> 02:34:25.599
Nothing was too trivial to be logged;&nbsp;
the number of nails needed to repair a

02:34:25.600 --> 02:34:31.680
wooden boat in Upper Egypt, or the fact that a&nbsp;
plague of locusts meant that a mud-brick wall

02:34:31.680 --> 02:34:39.200
could not be built in Bactria; each and every&nbsp;
case was individually recorded, signed off,

02:34:39.200 --> 02:34:52.800
reported to the central administration&nbsp;
in Persia, and methodically filed away.

02:34:52.800 --> 02:34:58.479
At the old Elamite capital of Susa,&nbsp;
Darius would construct a palace that

02:34:58.479 --> 02:35:03.280
for much of the empire's history would&nbsp;
act as the buzzing hive mind of this

02:35:03.280 --> 02:35:11.040
administration. Susa was well connected by&nbsp;
road to all parts of the empire, and also by

02:35:11.040 --> 02:35:16.720
a canal that linked it to the Euphrates&nbsp;
River, and from there the Persian Gulf.

02:35:17.359 --> 02:35:24.479
As a result, at Susa, messengers would come&nbsp;
and go, day in and day out, bearing tablets and

02:35:24.479 --> 02:35:35.120
missives, keeping this machinery moving and the&nbsp;
resources of the empire flowing out to its people.

02:35:35.120 --> 02:35:40.640
As a testament to his vision of an empire&nbsp;
that brought peoples together, this palace

02:35:40.640 --> 02:35:46.479
would form an architectural representation&nbsp;
of everything the empire had achieved,

02:35:46.479 --> 02:35:52.080
as Darius describes in one inscription.

02:35:52.080 --> 02:35:59.200
Yaka timber was brought from Gandara and from&nbsp;
Carmania. The gold was brought from Sardis and

02:35:59.200 --> 02:36:08.240
from Bactria. The precious stone lapits lazuli&nbsp;
and carnelian was brought from Sogdiana. The stone-

02:36:08.240 --> 02:36:15.200
cutters who wrought the stone were Ionians&nbsp;
and Sardians. The goldsmiths were Medes and

02:36:15.200 --> 02:36:22.080
Egyptians. The men who wrought the wood were&nbsp;
Sardinians and Egyptians. The men who wrought

02:36:22.080 --> 02:36:31.359
the baked brick were Babylonians. The men who&nbsp;
adorned the wall, those were Medes and Egyptians.

02:36:33.280 --> 02:36:39.519
Darius also commissioned a new palace that&nbsp;
would be built at the site of Persepolis,

02:36:39.520 --> 02:36:46.399
lined with a series of beautiful reliefs that&nbsp;
formed an artistic representation of his vision,

02:36:46.399 --> 02:36:52.719
showing scenes of all the different peoples&nbsp;
of the empire wearing their distinctive dress,

02:36:52.720 --> 02:36:58.720
all coming to bring tribute to the King of Kings.

02:37:03.520 --> 02:37:11.280
Partly due to their roots in nomadic culture, the&nbsp;
Persian royal court was mobile, and under Darius,

02:37:11.280 --> 02:37:18.479
they traveled between royal centers throughout&nbsp;
the year. During the sweltering summer months,

02:37:18.479 --> 02:37:25.519
the king and his entourage, eunuchs, servants,&nbsp;
bodyguards, children, and the palace women moved

02:37:25.520 --> 02:37:32.240
up into the mountains to the summer capital&nbsp;
of Ecbatana, but when the cold winters brought

02:37:32.240 --> 02:37:39.120
snow to the hills, the court would move to the&nbsp;
lowlands in the foothills of the Zagros Mountains,

02:37:39.120 --> 02:37:50.000
and the buzzing nerve center of Susa. Spring&nbsp;
festivals they would carry out in the Persepolis.

02:37:50.000 --> 02:37:54.640
Perhaps partly due to his experience&nbsp;
of marching armies back and forth,

02:37:54.640 --> 02:37:59.120
putting down ceaseless rebellions&nbsp;
in the first years of his reign,

02:37:59.120 --> 02:38:08.000
one of Darius' first priorities was&nbsp;
to improve the empire's road system.

02:38:08.000 --> 02:38:15.600
Chief among these crucial arteries was the&nbsp;
highway known as the Royal Road. Some sections

02:38:15.600 --> 02:38:22.800
of this highway were already ancient, and had been&nbsp;
maintained by the Assyrian and Babylonian empires,

02:38:22.800 --> 02:38:28.640
but Darius improved and expanded it until&nbsp;
it stretched from the empire's westernmost

02:38:28.640 --> 02:38:35.760
city of Sardis near the Mediterranean, all the way&nbsp;
through Asia Minor and northern Mesopotamia until

02:38:35.760 --> 02:38:44.640
it reached the winter capital of Susa at the foot&nbsp;
of the Zagros Mountains. Herodotus describes this

02:38:44.640 --> 02:38:53.359
well-made highway. All along the road are royal&nbsp;
staging posts and excellent rest houses, and,

02:38:53.359 --> 02:39:01.280
as it runs through inhabited country, the entire&nbsp;
road is safe. If the Royal Road had been measured

02:39:01.280 --> 02:39:10.559
correctly, then the whole journey is exactly&nbsp;
ninety days by foot. This Royal Road allowed the

02:39:10.560 --> 02:39:21.040
transfer of information at a speed yet unknown&nbsp;
in the ancient world, as Herodotus describes.

02:39:21.040 --> 02:39:27.519
There is nothing that travels faster and&nbsp;
yet is still mortal than these couriers.

02:39:27.520 --> 02:39:32.640
It is said that there are as many horses&nbsp;
and men posted at intervals as there are

02:39:32.640 --> 02:39:39.040
days required for the entire journey, so&nbsp;
that one horse and one man are assigned to

02:39:39.040 --> 02:39:45.920
each day; and neither snow nor rain nor&nbsp;
heat nor dark of night keeps them from

02:39:45.920 --> 02:39:51.439
completing their appointed course&nbsp;
as swiftly as possible. The first

02:39:51.439 --> 02:39:56.240
courier passes on the instructions to&nbsp;
the second, the second to the third,

02:39:56.240 --> 02:40:03.519
and from there they are transmitted from one to&nbsp;
another as in the torch race among the Greeks.

02:40:10.960 --> 02:40:19.600
It was along one of these roads, in the year 499&nbsp;
BC, that a messenger would have ridden, carrying

02:40:19.600 --> 02:40:26.479
news to Darius of a worrying development&nbsp;
in the westernmost part of his empire.

02:40:26.479 --> 02:40:45.120
These were the Greek-speaking coastal regions&nbsp;
of Asia Minor, or what is now Turkey.

02:40:45.120 --> 02:40:51.439
These areas had once been conquered by the&nbsp;
wealthy king Croesus of Lydia, and were then

02:40:51.439 --> 02:40:59.759
absorbed by Cyrus. By this time, they had been&nbsp;
ruled by Persia for the last forty years, but now

02:40:59.760 --> 02:41:13.680
a messenger brought news that they had exploded in&nbsp;
revolt, and worst of all, they had outside help.

02:41:13.680 --> 02:41:18.399
The Greek states along the western&nbsp;
stretch of the coast of Lydia were

02:41:18.399 --> 02:41:25.519
divided into three main groups; the&nbsp;
Aeolians, the Ionians, and the Dorians,

02:41:25.520 --> 02:41:33.040
who all spoke related dialects of Greek.&nbsp;
It was the Ionians that had by this time

02:41:33.040 --> 02:41:40.720
had enough of Persian rule. These were&nbsp;
a group of proud and wealthy cities in

02:41:40.720 --> 02:41:48.080
Asia Minor that were traditionally believed to&nbsp;
have once been colonies of the city of Athens.

02:41:49.200 --> 02:41:57.280
The Persians had never really worked out how best&nbsp;
to rule over independent Greek city-states. In much

02:41:57.280 --> 02:42:02.960
of their empire, they would rely on already&nbsp;
existing structures of power to rule over

02:42:02.960 --> 02:42:10.479
conquered subjects. For instance, in the Hebrew&nbsp;
world, they relied on local priesthoods to keep

02:42:10.479 --> 02:42:18.639
the peace, and in Egypt, they adopted the power of&nbsp;
the pharaohs and temple priests. These provinces

02:42:18.640 --> 02:42:24.399
would then be appointed satraps to lead them,
who were almost always Persians appointed by the

02:42:24.399 --> 02:42:32.160
King of Kings. Very occasionally they were local&nbsp;
rulers who were allowed to keep most elements of

02:42:32.160 --> 02:42:38.240
their previous rule and the privileges of their&nbsp;
position, so long as they swore allegiance to the

02:42:38.240 --> 02:42:47.359
Persian Empire. According to Persian customs, this&nbsp;
swearing of allegiance was done by offering the

02:42:47.359 --> 02:42:56.639
King of Kings a gift of earth and water. These&nbsp;
were the elements crucial for life, two of the

02:42:56.640 --> 02:43:05.280
three holy elements in Iranian belief, and they&nbsp;
represented the elemental power of the monarch.

02:43:05.280 --> 02:43:12.639
But each Greek city-state was ruled by a chaotic&nbsp;
mess of aristocratic factions sharing power in

02:43:12.640 --> 02:43:19.439
complicated arrangements. For this reason,&nbsp;
the Persians had simply settled for choosing

02:43:19.439 --> 02:43:27.359
a Greek from each city-state and appointing him&nbsp;
ruler. These rulers the Greeks referred to with

02:43:27.359 --> 02:43:38.319
a word they had loaned from Lydian, meaning&nbsp;
‘monarch’. That word was ‘tyrannos’, or ‘tyrant’.

02:43:38.319 --> 02:43:43.439
In his work Politics, the Greek&nbsp;
writer Aristotle describes the

02:43:43.439 --> 02:43:51.439
difference between a king and a tyrant.&nbsp;
Tyranny is monarchy exercising the rule

02:43:51.439 --> 02:43:58.559
of a master. Kings rule according to law&nbsp;
over voluntary subjects, but tyrants over

02:43:58.560 --> 02:44:08.960
involuntary. The one are guarded by their fellow&nbsp;
citizens. The others are guarded against them.

02:44:08.960 --> 02:44:15.600
These Greek tyrants found themselves in a&nbsp;
difficult position. As Greeks themselves,

02:44:15.600 --> 02:44:21.439
they soaked up all the anger of their people&nbsp;
towards Persian rule, and they were often

02:44:21.439 --> 02:44:29.759
incompetent, corrupt, and poorly suited to&nbsp;
rule. Partly as a result of this system,

02:44:29.760 --> 02:44:38.960
by the year 499 BC, all of Ionia was bubbling&nbsp;
over with rebellion. The man who would throw a

02:44:38.960 --> 02:44:50.240
spark into this dry tinder was named Aristagoras,&nbsp;
the Greek tyrant of the Ionian city of Miletus.

02:44:53.279 --> 02:45:00.800
Miletus was a fine port town that was known as&nbsp;
the Jewel of Ionia, and its tyrant Aristagoras

02:45:00.800 --> 02:45:07.439
was an unlikely revolutionary. In fact, he had&nbsp;
ruled his city on behalf of the Persians for

02:45:07.439 --> 02:45:17.040
the last twelve years, but he had done a poor&nbsp;
job. After attempting a failed invasion of

02:45:17.040 --> 02:45:23.920
the island of Naxos on behalf of the empire,&nbsp;
he found himself deeply in debt and wildly

02:45:23.920 --> 02:45:30.640
unpopular among his people. Fearing that the&nbsp;
Persians would replace him as the tyrant of

02:45:30.640 --> 02:45:41.680
Miletus due to his incompetence, he decided&nbsp;
to change tactics, as Herodotus describes.

02:45:41.680 --> 02:45:46.880
It was likely, he thought, that his&nbsp;
lordship of Miletus would be taken

02:45:46.880 --> 02:45:55.840
away from him. With all these fears&nbsp;
in mind, he began to plan revolt.

02:45:55.840 --> 02:46:02.560
But Aristagoras knew that rebelling against&nbsp;
the Persian Empire would be useless unless he

02:46:02.560 --> 02:46:10.000
could get some outside help. To this end,&nbsp;
he crossed the sea to Greece in secret,

02:46:10.000 --> 02:46:17.760
hoping to find allies. First, he approached the&nbsp;
most powerful city in the large southern peninsula

02:46:17.760 --> 02:46:27.200
known as the Peloponnese, the city of Sparta.&nbsp;
The Spartans had for centuries cultivated a

02:46:27.200 --> 02:46:34.080
powerful mythos about themselves, and were widely&nbsp;
regarded as the major military power in Greece.

02:46:34.960 --> 02:46:42.160
This reputation was sufficient that Sparta&nbsp;
itself had never seen fit to build a city wall,

02:46:42.160 --> 02:46:51.599
boasting instead that its soldiers were all the&nbsp;
wall it needed. Aristagoras knew that if his rebellion

02:46:51.600 --> 02:46:59.840
was to be a success, he would need the help of&nbsp;
the Spartans. He went to appeal to one of Sparta's

02:46:59.840 --> 02:47:12.000
two kings, a man named Cleomenes, and with him he&nbsp;
brought a novel innovation, as Herodotus recounts.

02:47:12.000 --> 02:47:19.600
Aristagoras, the despot of Miletus, came to&nbsp;
Sparta, and when he had audience of the king,

02:47:19.600 --> 02:47:23.200
he brought with him a bronze tablet on which the

02:47:23.200 --> 02:47:29.439
map of all the earth was engraved,&nbsp;
and all the sea and all the rivers.

02:47:30.880 --> 02:47:36.720
“All the Spartans would need to do,” he told&nbsp;
the king, “was cross into Asia, march to the

02:47:36.720 --> 02:47:45.680
Persian capital of Susa, and kill King Darius.”&nbsp;
The Spartan king began to suspect that this all

02:47:45.680 --> 02:47:55.920
sounded a bit too good to be true. The king asked&nbsp;
Aristagoras how many days journey it was from the

02:47:55.920 --> 02:48:05.520
Ionian Sea to the Persian king. He said that&nbsp;
it was a three-month journey in land. At that,

02:48:05.520 --> 02:48:13.120
Cleomenes cut short all the rest that Aristagoras&nbsp;
began to tell him about the journey, and bade his

02:48:13.120 --> 02:48:19.519
guests depart from Sparta before sunset. “For&nbsp;
never,” he said, “would the Spartans listen to

02:48:19.520 --> 02:48:27.121
the plan if Aristagoras desired to lead&nbsp;them
to a three-month journey from the sea.”

02:48:34.399 --> 02:48:39.120
The refusal of King Cleomenes
partly had to do with the unique

02:48:39.120 --> 02:48:47.359
characteristic of Sparta as the&nbsp;
Greek world's biggest slave state.

02:48:47.359 --> 02:48:56.000
Like most Greek city-states, Sparta was a society&nbsp;
built on slavery, but whereas other cities like

02:48:56.000 --> 02:49:02.880
Athens kept slaves to work in households and&nbsp;
workshops, and usually had a slave population

02:49:02.880 --> 02:49:09.359
a little larger than their free population,&nbsp;
Sparta was in a different league entirely.

02:49:10.000 --> 02:49:18.560
Practically its entire agricultural sector ran&nbsp;
on a vast slave class known as helots, a kind of

02:49:18.560 --> 02:49:26.000
laboring serf bound to the land, who outnumbered&nbsp;
the free population by perhaps as many as ten to

02:49:26.000 --> 02:49:36.800
one, and, crucially, these helots were Greek. Other&nbsp;
Greek cities held a taboo against holding other

02:49:36.800 --> 02:49:44.640
Greeks as slaves, and their slave populations were&nbsp;
made up of Scythians, Thracians, and other peoples

02:49:44.640 --> 02:49:54.720
who had been captured in piracy or war. In Sparta,&nbsp;
this helot underclass was made up of whole Greek

02:49:54.720 --> 02:50:02.160
ethnicities that had been conquered long ago,&nbsp;
and they were reviled and brutally mistreated.

02:50:03.120 --> 02:50:12.000
The Greek writer Myron of Priene writes the&nbsp;
following description of the helots’ lot.

02:50:12.000 --> 02:50:16.160
They assigned to the helots every&nbsp;
shameful task leading to disgrace,

02:50:16.160 --> 02:50:20.160
for they ordained that each one&nbsp;
of them must wear a dog-skin cap

02:50:20.160 --> 02:50:25.840
and wrap himself in skins and receive a&nbsp;
stipulated number of beatings every year,

02:50:25.840 --> 02:50:31.120
regardless of any wrongdoing, so that&nbsp;
they would never forget they were slaves.

02:50:33.200 --> 02:50:39.279
The helots were even ritually murdered each&nbsp;
year in a little understood ceremony known

02:50:39.279 --> 02:50:48.160
as the Krypteia, a word meaning ‘secret acts’.&nbsp;
Understandably unhappy with their condition,

02:50:48.160 --> 02:50:54.160
the helots rose up in rebellion against&nbsp;
their Spartan abusers a number of times.

02:50:55.040 --> 02:51:00.960
As a result, the Spartan military was made&nbsp;
constantly at the ready, and their soldiers

02:51:00.960 --> 02:51:08.960
carried their spears with them at all times.&nbsp;
Cleomenes must have known that if the Spartan

02:51:08.960 --> 02:51:15.040
army was away from home for at least six months&nbsp;
in Persia, the helots would likely take the

02:51:15.040 --> 02:51:23.600
opportunity to rebel, and Sparta would burn.&nbsp;
Despite its great reputation for warfare,

02:51:23.600 --> 02:51:30.080
the Spartan army was tied down in its lands,&nbsp;
and was all but useless for anything but the

02:51:30.080 --> 02:51:39.120
briefest and nearest campaigns. Discouraged,&nbsp;
Aristagoras left, and traveled to appeal to the

02:51:39.120 --> 02:51:47.920
perhaps more unlikely allies. This&nbsp;
was the Greek city-state of Athens.

02:51:56.960 --> 02:52:01.200
Although supposedly the mother&nbsp;
city of the Ionian colonies,

02:52:01.200 --> 02:52:08.800
the city of Athens had no great reputation for&nbsp;
warfare, and it was at that time in a state of

02:52:08.800 --> 02:52:16.479
some political upheaval. Until recently,&nbsp;
it had been ruled by a tyrant of its own,

02:52:16.479 --> 02:52:22.160
a man named Hippias, but he had&nbsp;
been overthrown, and in his place,

02:52:22.160 --> 02:52:30.080
the Athenians had brought in a radical system.&nbsp;
This was an emerging form of government named

02:52:30.080 --> 02:52:40.080
after the Greek words ‘demos’, or ‘people’, and&nbsp;
‘kratos’, meaning ‘power’. That name was democracy.

02:52:41.439 --> 02:52:47.439
The Athenian system allowed its citizens to&nbsp;
participate in government through various councils

02:52:47.439 --> 02:52:54.399
and committees, and enabled them to vote on what&nbsp;
policies and actions the government should take,

02:52:54.399 --> 02:53:02.559
usually by a show of hands with special bronze&nbsp;
ballots or using white and black stones.

02:53:03.680 --> 02:53:11.040
Athens was not the only Greek democracy or the&nbsp;
first one, but it was the newest, largest, and the

02:53:11.040 --> 02:53:21.040
most powerful city yet to adopt it. Democracy in&nbsp;
Athens was only available to adult male citizens

02:53:21.040 --> 02:53:26.560
and women slaves, and the third or so of the&nbsp;
population that were considered citizens of

02:53:26.560 --> 02:53:34.560
other cities were excluded. In reality, only about&nbsp;
a third of the adult population was actually given

02:53:34.560 --> 02:53:41.359
any right to political participation, but it was&nbsp;
still a relatively progressive system for the

02:53:41.359 --> 02:53:50.479
time. The Greek critics of democracy argued that the&nbsp;
system had merely replaced the whims of a king or

02:53:50.479 --> 02:53:59.679
tyrant with the whims of the mob, which could&nbsp;
be no less capricious, arbitrary, or foolish.

02:53:59.680 --> 02:54:07.200
And when Aristagoras arrived in Athens that year,&nbsp;
pleading for help in his foolhardy rebellion,

02:54:07.200 --> 02:54:18.479
some would say that the Athenian people proved&nbsp;
their critics right, as Herodotus describes.

02:54:18.479 --> 02:54:24.959
Coming before the people, Aristagoras spoke&nbsp;
to the same effect as at Sparta of the good

02:54:24.960 --> 02:54:31.600
things of Asia, and how the Persians in war&nbsp;
were want to carry neither shield nor spear,

02:54:31.600 --> 02:54:40.399
and could easily be overcome. Truly, it would seem&nbsp;
that it is easier to deceive many than one, for he

02:54:40.399 --> 02:54:51.120
could not deceive King Cleomenes of Sparta, one&nbsp;
single man, but 30,000 Athenians he could. The

02:54:51.120 --> 02:54:59.519
Athenians then were won over, and voted the&nbsp;
sending of twenty ships in aid of the Ionians.

02:55:01.600 --> 02:55:16.560
The tiny city of Athens had just voted to attack&nbsp;
the largest empire that the world had ever seen.

02:55:24.880 --> 02:55:33.600
The Athenians’ twenty ships landed in Asia&nbsp;
Minor in 498 BC, packed with soldiers.

02:55:33.600 --> 02:55:38.800
There, they met with the Ionian Greeks&nbsp;
of Ephesus, who guided them through the

02:55:38.800 --> 02:55:44.960
mountains to their target, the&nbsp;
old Lydian capital of Sardis.

02:55:46.720 --> 02:55:54.319
Sardis was the home of a Persian satrap who&nbsp;
was the brother of the King of Kings, Darius.

02:55:54.319 --> 02:56:01.040
It was home to a Persian military headquarters&nbsp;
and a large armory, and the Greeks hoped that

02:56:01.040 --> 02:56:09.760
by seizing the city, they would strike a lethal&nbsp;
blow to Persian rule. The Greeks moved quickly

02:56:09.760 --> 02:56:17.359
through the rocky valleys and took the unprepared&nbsp;
Persian garrison by surprise, breaking into the

02:56:17.359 --> 02:56:25.200
city's lower reaches. The Persians retreated&nbsp;
and holed up in the towering citadel that

02:56:25.200 --> 02:56:35.200
still looked down from the top of Mount Tmolus,&nbsp;
just as King Croesus had half a century before.

02:56:35.200 --> 02:56:39.599
While the Greeks camped in&nbsp;
the city, a fire broke out,

02:56:39.600 --> 02:56:51.359
whether accidentally or not, and it soon&nbsp;
spread. The great capital of Sardis burned.

02:56:51.359 --> 02:56:58.000
The greater part of the houses in Sardis&nbsp;
were of reeds, and as many as were of brick;

02:56:58.000 --> 02:57:05.279
even they had roofs of reeds. So it was that&nbsp;
when one of these was set afire by a soldier,

02:57:05.279 --> 02:57:12.559
the flames spread from house to house all&nbsp;
over the whole city. So, Sardis was burned,

02:57:12.560 --> 02:57:18.960
and therein the temple of Kybele,&nbsp;
the goddess of the country.

02:57:22.479 --> 02:57:31.359
The once grand city of Sardis was now a smoking&nbsp;
ruin. The Athenians knew that a Persian army must

02:57:31.359 --> 02:57:37.599
have been racing towards them at that very moment&nbsp;
to take the city back, and with the temple of

02:57:37.600 --> 02:57:44.800
Kybele destroyed, they now feared that the gods&nbsp;
themselves might also have turned against them.

02:57:45.840 --> 02:57:53.760
The Athenians began to wonder if perhaps this&nbsp;
whole venture had been a mistake. They fled

02:57:53.760 --> 02:58:01.600
the ruined city and pelted back to the coast&nbsp;
and their ships, and along the Royal Road of

02:58:01.600 --> 02:58:12.640
the Persian Empire, the news raced back to King&nbsp;
Darius at the pace of the empire's fastest horses.

02:58:17.520 --> 02:58:24.319
When Darius heard of the burning of the city&nbsp;
of Sardis by this group of rebels, he must have

02:58:24.319 --> 02:58:31.679
been astonished and enraged. His own people&nbsp;
rebelling was one thing, but the intervention

02:58:31.680 --> 02:58:39.520
of the Athenians was quite another. These&nbsp;
insignificant people from across the Aegean Sea

02:58:39.520 --> 02:58:46.560
had meddled completely unprovoked in his empire,&nbsp;
fomented a rebellion, landed a surprise attack

02:58:46.560 --> 02:58:53.120
on one of his most revered cities, and burned&nbsp;
it to the ground, all before scuttling back to

02:58:53.120 --> 02:59:00.479
their ships and sailing away. To the great King&nbsp;
of Kings, the Athenians must have seemed little

02:59:00.479 --> 02:59:09.919
better than pirates, as Herodotus recounts. When&nbsp;
it was reported to Darius that Sardis had been

02:59:09.920 --> 02:59:17.359
taken and burnt by the Athenians, he asked who the&nbsp;
Athenians were, and after receiving the answer,

02:59:17.359 --> 02:59:26.080
he called for his bow. This he took, and, placing an&nbsp;
arrow on it, shot it into the sky, praying as he

02:59:26.080 --> 02:59:35.120
sent it aloft. O Zeus, grant me vengeance on the&nbsp;
Athenians. Then he ordered one of his servants to

02:59:35.120 --> 02:59:49.040
say to him three times whenever dinner was set&nbsp;
before him, "Master, remember the Athenians."

02:59:49.040 --> 02:59:55.840
The Athenian Greeks loved repeating this story as&nbsp;
a testament to the king's obsession with revenge

02:59:55.840 --> 03:00:03.359
against the city of Athens for daring to stand&nbsp;
up to the empire. They loved imagining the name

03:00:03.359 --> 03:00:10.080
of their city being spoken in the great court&nbsp;
of Persia, but from the Persian perspective,

03:00:10.080 --> 03:00:16.880
we might also read it another way, that the&nbsp;
Athenians were at that time so insignificant

03:00:16.880 --> 03:00:25.760
that without constant reminders, King Darius&nbsp;
feared he might forget about them completely.

03:00:28.720 --> 03:00:35.520
Darius was a man who ruled by a code, and&nbsp;
he inscribed this code of principles into

03:00:35.520 --> 03:00:42.000
the outer wall of his tomb at Naqsh-i&nbsp;
Rustam. It's these principles that

03:00:42.000 --> 03:00:49.359
must have been running through his mind when&nbsp;
considering how to deal with the Athenians.

03:00:51.040 --> 03:01:01.120
King Darius says, "I am friend of the right.&nbsp;
Of wrong, I am not a friend. It is not my wish

03:01:01.120 --> 03:01:08.800
that the weak should have harm done him by the&nbsp;
strong, nor is it my wish that the strong should

03:01:08.800 --> 03:01:17.279
have harm done him by the weak. The right,&nbsp;
that is my desire. The man who is cooperative

03:01:17.279 --> 03:01:35.359
according to his cooperation, I reward him. Who&nbsp;
does harm, him according to the harm I punish.”

03:01:35.359 --> 03:01:43.120
Only two years later, that punishment&nbsp;
would come in the form of an invasion.

03:02:05.439 --> 03:02:11.919
The Greek mainland of Europe is separated from&nbsp;
Asia by a narrow channel that connects the

03:02:11.920 --> 03:02:20.560
Mediterranean to the Black Sea, and in places, this&nbsp;
channel is only a mile or so wide. The narrowest

03:02:20.560 --> 03:02:31.200
of these straits are known as the Bosphorus and&nbsp;
the Dardanelles. For his 492 BC invasion, Darius

03:02:31.200 --> 03:02:38.639
appointed one of his own son-in-laws to lead&nbsp;
the campaign, a young general named Mardonius.

03:02:39.359 --> 03:02:45.839
He ordered him to cross into Europe with&nbsp;
a force of about 30,000 men, a small army

03:02:45.840 --> 03:02:54.000
by Persian standards, designed to move&nbsp;
quickly and need minimal supplies. They

03:02:54.000 --> 03:03:00.560
crossed at the straits known today as the&nbsp;
Dardanelles, but which in ancient times was

03:03:00.560 --> 03:03:07.840
known as the Hellespont, or the Sea of&nbsp;
Helles, named after a mythical princess who

03:03:07.840 --> 03:03:16.640
drowned after falling from a flying golden&nbsp;
ram in the myth of the golden fleece.

03:03:16.640 --> 03:03:20.080
These straits are about three kilometers across

03:03:20.080 --> 03:03:28.880
at their narrowest point, and Mardonius would&nbsp;
have ferried his men over using ships.

03:03:28.880 --> 03:03:36.800
Once in Europe, Mardonius subjected the people of&nbsp;
Thrace in what is now Eastern Greece and Bulgaria,

03:03:36.800 --> 03:03:43.840
and then marched south to the mountainous kingdom&nbsp;
of Macedon, which they also subjugated and made a

03:03:43.840 --> 03:03:51.840
client state of the empire. With this large&nbsp;
Persian army now on the doorstep of mainland

03:03:51.840 --> 03:03:59.200
Greece, Darius sent an offer to the cities of&nbsp;
Athens and Sparta, requesting that they lay down

03:03:59.200 --> 03:04:08.639
their arms, swear allegiance to him, and give&nbsp;
him the customary offering of earth and water.

03:04:08.640 --> 03:04:17.359
Herodotus recounts their reaction.&nbsp;
When Darius sent men with this purpose,

03:04:17.359 --> 03:04:25.920
those who made the request were cast at the one&nbsp;
city into a pit, and at the other into a well,

03:04:25.920 --> 03:04:36.560
and bidden to obtain their earth and&nbsp;
water for the king from these locations.

03:04:36.560 --> 03:04:42.319
It's not clear from Herodotus whether these men&nbsp;
were killed or eventually fished out from the

03:04:42.319 --> 03:04:49.439
well, but either way, mistreating a messenger&nbsp;
in this way was considered an abhorrent act in

03:04:49.439 --> 03:04:56.319
Persia, and when Darius heard how his ambassadors&nbsp;
had been abused, it must have strengthened his

03:04:56.319 --> 03:05:03.840
belief that he was dealing with the very worst&nbsp;
of barbarians, and steeled his resolve to crush

03:05:03.840 --> 03:05:13.120
these tiny cities beneath his foot. But the&nbsp;
general Mardonius met with some bad luck on

03:05:13.120 --> 03:05:20.800
the journey. His army was ambushed during&nbsp;
the night by a people known as the Brygi,

03:05:20.800 --> 03:05:28.080
a Thracian tribe who killed many of his men.&nbsp;
Mardonius himself was even injured when he

03:05:28.080 --> 03:05:34.399
was thrown from his horse during the battle,&nbsp;
and at the same time, another force sent by

03:05:34.399 --> 03:05:45.679
ship across the Aegean was wrecked in a&nbsp;
storm off the rocky coast of Mount Athos.

03:05:45.680 --> 03:05:48.960
It was the first intimation the Persians would get

03:05:48.960 --> 03:05:56.800
that conquering Greece might&nbsp;
not be as easy as it seemed.

03:06:04.800 --> 03:06:11.840
Not discouraged, two years later, Darius sent&nbsp;
another force of about 30,000 men on a fleet

03:06:11.840 --> 03:06:19.760
of ships sailing for Athens. These hopped from&nbsp;
island to island across the Aegean, capturing

03:06:19.760 --> 03:06:28.880
them for the empire. With them they brought men,&nbsp;
equipment, supplies, and horses, and even the old

03:06:28.880 --> 03:06:40.720
tyrant ruler of Athens, Hippias, who they intended&nbsp;
to put back on the throne as a Persian puppet.

03:06:40.720 --> 03:06:47.359
In early September of 490 BC, they&nbsp;
finally reached the coast of Attica,

03:06:47.359 --> 03:06:54.399
the region in which Athens sits.&nbsp;
There, on the advice of Hippias, they

03:06:54.399 --> 03:07:16.319
landed at a bay about forty kilometers, or twenty-five
miles, northeast of Athens at a place called Marathon.

03:07:16.319 --> 03:07:22.240
When the Athenians heard of the Persian army's&nbsp;
landing, they gathered every single available

03:07:22.240 --> 03:07:29.040
fighting man in the city, and marched out&nbsp;
to meet them. The Persians had chosen their

03:07:29.040 --> 03:07:35.600
landing spot because the Bay of Marathon was&nbsp;
one of the few large open spaces in Attica.

03:07:36.160 --> 03:07:42.880
It was a stretch of beach rising to a flat&nbsp;
plain before quickly shooting up to rocky

03:07:42.880 --> 03:07:51.120
and impossible highlands broken by only a&nbsp;
couple of narrow passes. The Greeks knew

03:07:51.120 --> 03:08:00.720
the area well, and quickly moved to shut&nbsp;
off the two main passes out of the bay.

03:08:00.720 --> 03:08:09.760
From there they looked on as the Persian&nbsp;
expeditionary force unloaded on the sand.

03:08:09.760 --> 03:08:17.439
Over the last fifty-six years of intermittent conflict,&nbsp;
no Greek army had ever beaten a Persian one in

03:08:17.439 --> 03:08:23.519
battle, and this must have been playing through&nbsp;
their minds as they watched the Persian ships

03:08:23.520 --> 03:08:31.520
landing one by one on the shore. For a time,&nbsp;
both armies stood and watched one another,

03:08:31.520 --> 03:08:39.920
and neither were in a hurry to begin&nbsp;
the battle, as Herodotus recounts.

03:08:39.920 --> 03:08:46.640
The Athenian generals were of divided&nbsp;
opinion, some advocating not fighting

03:08:46.640 --> 03:08:55.760
because they were too few to attack the army&nbsp;
of the Persians; others advocating fighting.

03:08:55.760 --> 03:08:59.359
While they stood and watched&nbsp;
their enemy mass on the beach,

03:08:59.359 --> 03:09:05.759
the Athenians were joined by men from the city&nbsp;
of Plataea, and they had sent out word to other

03:09:05.760 --> 03:09:13.840
allies. One of these messengers was a man by&nbsp;
the name of Pheidippides, who had set out on a

03:09:13.840 --> 03:09:23.920
journey of more than 240 kilometers over rocky
mountainous terrain to ask for aid from the city of Sparta.

03:09:24.720 --> 03:09:32.240
The Greeks had nothing like the sophisticated road&nbsp;
system of the Persian Empire, or the waystations

03:09:32.240 --> 03:09:39.359
where horse riding messengers could swap out their&nbsp;
tired horses. The Greeks were mostly not great

03:09:39.359 --> 03:09:46.719
horse riders, and when they did ride, they did so&nbsp;
without stirrups or a saddle, making for a slow and

03:09:46.720 --> 03:09:54.000
uncomfortable ride. For this reason, if you wanted&nbsp;
a message delivered in Greece at this time, you

03:09:54.000 --> 03:10:02.800
simply sent a runner who trained his whole life&nbsp;
for long-distance journeys of this kind.

03:10:02.800 --> 03:10:09.359
Pheidippides must have known that countless lives,&nbsp;
and perhaps the freedom of his country, depended

03:10:09.359 --> 03:10:18.000
on him making that journey swiftly. But when&nbsp;
he arrived in Sparta, he would be disappointed.

03:10:22.640 --> 03:10:30.240
He reached Sparta on the very next day after&nbsp;
quitting the city of Athens. Upon his arrival,

03:10:30.240 --> 03:10:35.040
he went before the rulers and&nbsp;
said to them, "Men of Sparta,

03:10:35.040 --> 03:10:40.399
the Athenians beseech you to hasten&nbsp;
to their aid and not allow that state,

03:10:40.399 --> 03:10:46.719
which is the most ancient in all Greece,&nbsp;
to be enslaved by the barbarians."

03:10:46.720 --> 03:10:53.840
The Spartans wished to help the Athenians, but&nbsp;
were unable to, as it was then the ninth day of

03:10:53.840 --> 03:11:08.960
the first decade, and they could not march out of&nbsp;
Sparta when the moon had not reached the full.

03:11:08.960 --> 03:11:15.520
The Spartans were at that time celebrating&nbsp;
their annual festival of the Carneia, during which

03:11:15.520 --> 03:11:23.680
campaigning was forbidden. Despite their carefully&nbsp;
cultivated reputation for never backing down from

03:11:23.680 --> 03:11:30.560
a fight, it was surprisingly common whenever it&nbsp;
was called upon for the city of Sparta to have

03:11:30.560 --> 03:11:38.720
something else terribly important to be doing. The&nbsp;
Spartans would not even leave Sparta for another

03:11:38.720 --> 03:11:46.399
week, and the march would take them at least&nbsp;
another three days. Pheidippides set out on the road back

03:11:46.399 --> 03:11:58.160
to Athens to bring the bad news of this delay to&nbsp;
the soldiers stuck back on the beach at Marathon.

03:11:58.160 --> 03:12:03.680
Outnumbered at least two to one, the&nbsp;
Athenians elected to sit and wait

03:12:03.680 --> 03:12:12.880
for the Spartan reinforcements to arrive,
but then something forced their hand. We're

03:12:12.880 --> 03:12:20.640
not entirely sure why the battle began when it&nbsp;
did, before any Spartan reinforcements appeared,

03:12:20.640 --> 03:12:28.080
but it's possible that the Persians had come&nbsp;
up with an idea. By now they had realized that

03:12:28.080 --> 03:12:33.840
with every Athenian fighter waiting there&nbsp;
on the beach, blocking their way inland,

03:12:33.840 --> 03:12:41.439
the city of Athens must be all but defenseless.&nbsp;
The Persians may have begun to load up their

03:12:41.439 --> 03:12:49.599
ships, perhaps putting the horses on board first,&nbsp;
preparing to set sail for the city immediately.

03:12:50.800 --> 03:12:56.479
Traveling by sea, they would be able to strike&nbsp;
at Athens before the Athenians were able to run

03:12:56.479 --> 03:13:06.000
the twenty-five miles home by foot in their heavy
armor. Once they saw this Persian plan unfolding,

03:13:06.000 --> 03:13:14.880
the Athenians had no choice but to attack right&nbsp;
away. They advanced, breaking into a run across

03:13:14.880 --> 03:13:26.000
the marshy plain, and smashed into the lightly-&nbsp;
armored Persian infantry, as Herodotus recounts.

03:13:26.000 --> 03:13:33.920
The two armies fought together on the plain of&nbsp;
Marathon for a length of time, and in the mid

03:13:33.920 --> 03:13:39.680
battle, where the Persians themselves and the&nbsp;
Scythians had the place, the barbarians were

03:13:39.680 --> 03:13:46.800
victorious, and broke and pursued the Greeks&nbsp;
into the inner country. But on the two wings,

03:13:46.800 --> 03:13:53.359
the Athenians and the Plataeans defeated the&nbsp;
enemy. Having so done, they suffered the

03:13:53.359 --> 03:14:00.160
rooted barbarians to fly at their ease, and&nbsp;
joining the two wings in one, fell upon those

03:14:00.160 --> 03:14:07.359
who had broken their own center, and fought and&nbsp;
conquered them. These likewise fled, and now the

03:14:07.359 --> 03:14:14.799
Athenians hung upon the runaways and cut them&nbsp;
down, chasing them all the way to the shore.

03:14:16.399 --> 03:14:22.879
It's speculated that the Persian cavalry, either&nbsp;
half-loaded onto the boats already or simply

03:14:22.880 --> 03:14:31.600
useless on the marshy plain, were unable to help&nbsp;
the trapped foot soldiers. The Persian forces were

03:14:31.600 --> 03:14:39.600
routed, and Herodotus claims that many thousands&nbsp;
were killed on the beach. The Greeks managed to

03:14:39.600 --> 03:14:47.040
capture seven of the Persian ships, but the rest&nbsp;
of the fleet escaped, and now attempted to play

03:14:47.040 --> 03:14:58.080
the final card available to them, a last ditch&nbsp;
attempt to attack the undefended city of Athens.

03:14:58.080 --> 03:15:05.200
The remainder of the barbarians pushed off, hoping to&nbsp;
reach Athens before the return of the Athenians,

03:15:05.200 --> 03:15:10.319
but the Athenians, with all possible&nbsp;
speed, marched away to the defense of

03:15:10.319 --> 03:15:20.160
their city, and succeeded in reaching Athens&nbsp;
before the appearance of the barbarians.

03:15:23.760 --> 03:15:29.120
The Greeks had run half the afternoon&nbsp;
through the blazing sun at a distance of

03:15:29.120 --> 03:15:37.519
just over twenty-five miles, about the distance
of what we today commemorate as a marathon.

03:15:38.560 --> 03:15:43.520
When the Persians arrived off the coast&nbsp;
of Athens in the Bay of Phalerum, they saw

03:15:43.520 --> 03:15:49.680
with some astonishment that the Athenians&nbsp;
had arrived back to defend their city, and

03:15:49.680 --> 03:15:59.120
were now standing on the city walls with their&nbsp;
bright shields and helmets flashing in the sun.

03:15:59.120 --> 03:16:06.880
The barbarian fleet arrived and laid off Phalerum,&nbsp;
which was at the time the harbor of Athens,

03:16:07.680 --> 03:16:21.439
but after resting a while upon their oars,&nbsp;
they departed and sailed away to Asia.

03:16:21.439 --> 03:16:27.839
The Battle of Marathon has long been considered&nbsp;
a turning point in the history of Athens.

03:16:28.960 --> 03:16:35.120
Although the Persian army that Darius sent was&nbsp;
only a relatively small expeditionary force,

03:16:35.120 --> 03:16:42.239
it had been beaten by a Greek army only half&nbsp;
its size. The Athenians had proven that they

03:16:42.239 --> 03:16:48.639
could fight by themselves without the aid of&nbsp;
Sparta, and they had shown that by carefully

03:16:48.640 --> 03:16:56.480
choosing the battlefield, the Persian forces,&nbsp;
previously thought unbeatable, could be overcome.

03:16:58.000 --> 03:17:05.359
The Greek dead of Marathon were cremated, and their&nbsp;
ashes buried on the battlefield beneath two great

03:17:05.359 --> 03:17:21.759
mounds of earth. On the tomb of the Athenians,&nbsp;
the poet Simonides wrote the following epigraph.

03:17:26.560 --> 03:17:29.120
Fighting at the forefront of the Greeks,

03:17:29.120 --> 03:17:38.880
the Athenians at Marathon laid&nbsp;
low the army of the gilded Medes.

03:17:38.880 --> 03:17:44.880
Two days after the battle, Herodotus&nbsp;
describes how 2,000 Spartans arrived

03:17:44.880 --> 03:17:50.080
on the beach at Marathon and&nbsp;
saw the mounds of the dead.

03:17:51.600 --> 03:17:58.560
After the full moon, 2,000 Spartans came to&nbsp;
Athens. Although they came too late for the

03:17:58.560 --> 03:18:04.479
battle, they desired to see the Persians,&nbsp;
so they went to Marathon and saw them,

03:18:04.479 --> 03:18:14.000
and they departed again, praising&nbsp;
the Athenians and their achievement.

03:18:14.000 --> 03:18:18.880
For the Spartans, the fact that Athens&nbsp;
had fought and won without them would

03:18:18.880 --> 03:18:27.680
be a sore point that would last for at least&nbsp;
the next decade. As for the great King Darius,

03:18:27.680 --> 03:18:32.319
when news reached him of the defeat&nbsp;
at Marathon, we can only imagine the

03:18:32.319 --> 03:18:40.719
frosty atmosphere at court. Herodotus&nbsp;
renders one version of his reaction.

03:18:42.800 --> 03:18:50.479
The message about the Battle of Marathon came to&nbsp;
King Darius, so he was now more furious than ever

03:18:50.479 --> 03:18:57.279
and even more resolved to march against Greece.&nbsp;
He immediately sent messengers to each city,

03:18:57.279 --> 03:19:03.040
ordering them to prepare a much larger&nbsp;
force than before, as well as ships,

03:19:03.040 --> 03:19:10.560
horses, grain, and vessels. As a result of&nbsp;
these demands, Asia was astir for three

03:19:10.560 --> 03:19:23.600
years, with the best men enrolled for service&nbsp;
against Greece and getting ready for war.

03:19:23.600 --> 03:19:28.560
But by the time this massive force&nbsp;
was ready to set sail for Greece,

03:19:28.560 --> 03:19:37.359
events in the empire overtook the great king.&nbsp;
Darius' increasing demands for men and grain to

03:19:37.359 --> 03:19:43.439
service his Greek wars had caused resentment&nbsp;
in the various satrapies of the empire, and

03:19:43.439 --> 03:19:50.719
especially in Egypt. The defeat at Marathon&nbsp;
may also have emboldened some who wished to

03:19:50.720 --> 03:20:01.520
break free of the empire. Now around 486 BC,&nbsp;
Egypt rose up against its Persian governor.

03:20:01.520 --> 03:20:10.319
The army that Darius had gathered to conquer&nbsp;
Greece now sailed for Egypt instead. Darius,

03:20:10.319 --> 03:20:18.399
now a relatively old man of sixty-five, prepared to&nbsp;
go with them, but before he could depart,

03:20:18.399 --> 03:20:30.399
the king was taken suddenly ill. The Greek&nbsp;
writer Ctesias records the final days of Darius.

03:20:30.399 --> 03:20:45.839
Darius went back to Persia and made two sacrifices,&nbsp;
and after an illness of thirty days, he passed away.

03:20:45.840 --> 03:20:53.359
Darius had been king for thirty-six years, and though&nbsp;
his rule had started in scandal and lies,

03:20:53.359 --> 03:21:00.399
he had ushered in an era of stability and&nbsp;
strength. Across the empire, Persians mourned

03:21:00.399 --> 03:21:08.319
for their king. They put out their sacred fires&nbsp;
in recognition of their grief, shaved their heads,

03:21:08.319 --> 03:21:17.679
and clipped the manes of their horses as a&nbsp;
sign of respect. On his tomb at Naqsh-i Rustam,

03:21:17.680 --> 03:21:24.960
Darius had carved an illustration of his throne,&nbsp;
supported from beneath by row upon row of people,

03:21:24.960 --> 03:21:32.640
each dressed in a distinctive fashion of one&nbsp;
of the peoples of the empire, and alongside it,

03:21:32.640 --> 03:21:40.880
he wrote the following inscription&nbsp;
that would serve as his epitaph.

03:21:40.880 --> 03:21:48.800
If now you shall think how many other countries&nbsp;
which King Darius held, look at the sculptures

03:21:48.800 --> 03:21:59.200
who bear the throne; then shall you know the&nbsp;
spear of a Persian man has gone forth far. Then

03:21:59.200 --> 03:22:08.479
shall it become known to you a Persian man&nbsp;
has delivered battle far indeed from Persia.

03:22:11.200 --> 03:22:17.519
The throne of the empire now passed&nbsp;
to one of the oldest sons of Darius,

03:22:17.520 --> 03:22:22.000
a man who in Old Persian was named Kh-sha-yarsha,

03:22:22.000 --> 03:22:33.040
a name which means ‘he who rules over heroes’,&nbsp;
but the Greeks would call him Xerxes.

03:22:33.040 --> 03:22:38.479
In the days that followed, this Xerxes&nbsp;
would have traveled to Pasargadae,

03:22:38.479 --> 03:22:44.639
the old capital of Cyrus, to be crowned,&nbsp;
and there he would enter the sanctuary

03:22:44.640 --> 03:22:54.880
of the goddess Anahita. Plutarch describes&nbsp;
the ceremony that would have ensued inside.

03:22:54.880 --> 03:23:01.840
There is a temple dedicated to a warlike goddess.&nbsp;
The royal person to be initiated must enter it,

03:23:01.840 --> 03:23:09.120
must strip himself of his own robe, and put on the&nbsp;
one that Cyrus I wore before he was king.

03:23:09.120 --> 03:23:17.599
Then, having devoured a cake of figs, he must chew&nbsp;
turpentine resin and drink a cup of sour milk.

03:23:19.120 --> 03:23:25.680
This ritual was supposed to remind each new king&nbsp;
of the hard life that the founder of the empire

03:23:25.680 --> 03:23:34.080
had lived and the meager foods he had subsisted&nbsp;
on while on campaign, a ceremony designed to

03:23:34.080 --> 03:23:43.120
remind them that being king involved hardship&nbsp;
and sacrifice. When he left that sanctuary,

03:23:43.120 --> 03:23:50.640
Xerxes was the new King of Kings, King of the&nbsp;
Four Quarters of the World, and emperor of

03:23:50.640 --> 03:23:59.600
the Persians. Perhaps throughout this ceremony,&nbsp;
while the priests chanted their songs around him,

03:23:59.600 --> 03:24:06.479
his father's last words to him would&nbsp;
have echoed in his head. We will never

03:24:06.479 --> 03:24:13.359
know what those might have been, but given the&nbsp;
choices that Xerxes would make during his rule,

03:24:13.359 --> 03:24:18.960
it might not be far-fetched to imagine&nbsp;
that Darius had made his son promise him

03:24:18.960 --> 03:24:29.920
that no matter what, he would make the&nbsp;
Athenians pay for what they had done.

03:24:51.840 --> 03:24:59.680
When Xerxes got to the throne, the first six years&nbsp;
of his reign was spent crushing the revolt still

03:24:59.680 --> 03:25:08.000
ongoing in Egypt, and then putting down another two&nbsp;
that arose in Babylon. But the moment his empire

03:25:08.000 --> 03:25:15.840
was secure, he turned his sights on the prize that&nbsp;
had slipped from his father's grasp, and where the

03:25:15.840 --> 03:25:27.279
empire's great humiliation had taken place. In the&nbsp;
spring of 480 BC, the army of Xerxes was ready,

03:25:27.279 --> 03:25:35.359
a large force of perhaps 60 to 80,000 soldiers,&nbsp;
more than twice the size of the army that had

03:25:35.359 --> 03:25:44.319
been beaten at Marathon. At the head of these men,&nbsp;
he marched out from the Lydian capital of Sardis

03:25:44.319 --> 03:25:52.639
and towards the crossing of the Hellespont. With&nbsp;
him, he brought a man with direct experience of

03:25:52.640 --> 03:26:06.800
fighting in Greece, the general that had led his&nbsp;
father's campaign, the now middle-aged Mardonius.

03:26:06.800 --> 03:26:12.160
To cross the narrow sea channel of&nbsp;
the Hellespont, Xerxes ordered a

03:26:12.160 --> 03:26:19.599
remarkable piece of infrastructure to be&nbsp;
built; two great floating pontoon bridges,

03:26:19.600 --> 03:26:26.479
each made out of more than 300 ships tied&nbsp;
together with ropes of flax and papyrus,

03:26:26.479 --> 03:26:34.319
and with a wooden road surface laid across them.&nbsp;
These bridges even had canvas screens on either

03:26:34.319 --> 03:26:41.759
side so that the horses would not become scared&nbsp;
at the sight of the rocking waters beneath them.

03:26:43.200 --> 03:26:49.679
These bridges would stretch more than 1.4&nbsp;
kilometers across the waters of the Hellespont,

03:26:49.680 --> 03:26:56.800
making them the longest bridges that the world&nbsp;
had ever seen, and they crossed a stretch of sea

03:26:56.800 --> 03:27:04.160
that experiences some of the strongest currents&nbsp;
in the Mediterranean. It was a clear statement

03:27:04.160 --> 03:27:10.800
of the empire's ambition, resources, and&nbsp;
determination to crush their enemies.

03:27:13.040 --> 03:27:18.160
But the weather would conspire&nbsp;
against Xerxes’ ambition,

03:27:18.160 --> 03:27:26.160
and Herodotus describes one&nbsp;
account of his furious reaction.

03:27:26.160 --> 03:27:32.479
But no sooner had the strait been bridged&nbsp;
than a great storm swept down and broke

03:27:32.479 --> 03:27:40.239
and scattered all the work. When Xerxes heard&nbsp;
of that, he was very angry and gave command

03:27:40.239 --> 03:27:48.479
that the Hellespont be scourged with 300 lashes,&nbsp;
and a pair of fetters be thrown into the sea.

03:27:48.479 --> 03:28:02.799
“Thou bitter water,” they should say. “Our master&nbsp;
thus punishes thee, because thou didst him wrong.”

03:28:02.800 --> 03:28:08.640
This legend of Xerxes ordering the sea&nbsp;
to be whipped is likely a Greek tale

03:28:08.640 --> 03:28:14.960
designed to make the king look despotic and&nbsp;
ridiculous, and in fact, with everything we

03:28:14.960 --> 03:28:21.760
know about the Persian reverence for water,&nbsp;
it seems incredibly unlikely. We can be sure

03:28:21.760 --> 03:28:27.200
that Xerxes would have offered prayers and&nbsp;
offerings to the waters before crossing them,

03:28:27.200 --> 03:28:34.880
and perhaps it is a Greek misunderstanding of&nbsp;
these ceremonies that Herodotus is recounting.

03:28:34.880 --> 03:28:41.920
For much of the story that follows, for better&nbsp;
or worse, Herodotus is our only source. He was

03:28:41.920 --> 03:28:47.279
certainly interested in portraying the truth&nbsp;
of past events, but he was also trying to tell

03:28:47.279 --> 03:28:55.279
a ripping story that glorified the exploits of&nbsp;the
Greeks. Herodotus was writing about fifty years

03:28:55.279 --> 03:29:01.840
after the Persian Wars, and by that time, this&nbsp;
conflict had taken on epic proportions in the

03:29:01.840 --> 03:29:09.120
Greek imagination. To the Greeks, the Persian&nbsp;
Wars held a similar place as the Second World

03:29:09.120 --> 03:29:17.120
War to us today, a great clash between good and&nbsp;
evil, a fight over the nature of civilization,

03:29:17.120 --> 03:29:23.760
and the fiery conflict in which the world as&nbsp;
they knew it had been born. For this reason,

03:29:23.760 --> 03:29:41.520
the account of Herodotus is a crucial source,&nbsp;
but one that has to be treated very carefully.

03:29:53.439 --> 03:30:00.000
With his bridges suitably repaired,
Xerxes marched into Europe, and there

03:30:00.000 --> 03:30:08.160
he would meet with remarkable success. He&nbsp;
marched through his subject of Thrace, and

03:30:08.160 --> 03:30:16.479
received help from his allies in&nbsp;
Macedon, a king named Alexander.

03:30:16.479 --> 03:30:23.359
Xerxes was marching to war, but he was also&nbsp;
demonstrating the power and breadth of his empire.

03:30:24.000 --> 03:30:30.640
He ensured that his army was made up of one&nbsp;
unit from every one of the empire's provinces,

03:30:30.640 --> 03:30:37.359
a colorful and garish display that would&nbsp;
have had a simple message; the entire world

03:30:37.359 --> 03:30:48.960
is marching against Greece. You are either with me&nbsp;
or against me. From Macedon, Xerxes marched south,

03:30:48.960 --> 03:30:54.399
his army moving in three columns, each with&nbsp;
a separate route so they wouldn't clog the

03:30:54.399 --> 03:31:02.479
road. They made such an impressive sight that many&nbsp;
generations later, the local Thracians still pointed

03:31:02.479 --> 03:31:10.959
out to travelers the road along which the great&nbsp;
army had traveled. The size of the force was such

03:31:10.960 --> 03:31:19.920
that Greek writers like Herodotus would inflate&nbsp;it
to the absurd size of two or three million men, but

03:31:19.920 --> 03:31:27.040
modern analysis of the constraints of supply and&nbsp;
transport in the ancient world reckon that about

03:31:27.040 --> 03:31:36.479
100,000 soldiers is a reasonable estimate for the&nbsp;
maximum possible size of an army at this time.

03:31:36.479 --> 03:31:43.359
Along the way, the engineers of Xerxes improved&nbsp;
the roads and built bridges, cutting through the

03:31:43.359 --> 03:31:52.000
mountains and bending the landscape to his will.&nbsp;
At the peninsula of Mount Athos, where one of his

03:31:52.000 --> 03:31:58.160
father's fleets had been wrecked in a storm,&nbsp;
Xerxes ordered the digging of a mile-long canal

03:31:58.160 --> 03:32:05.359
that cut through the isthmus and allowed his ships&nbsp;
to avoid sailing around the dangerous headland.

03:32:07.359 --> 03:32:14.479
On the way, Herodotus describes with perhaps&nbsp;
some exaggeration the army draining lakes dry

03:32:14.479 --> 03:32:22.639
while watering their pack animals, but it's true&nbsp;
that supplying this great army was no easy task.

03:32:22.640 --> 03:32:28.560
For that reason, they never strayed far from the&nbsp;
sea, where the Persian navy was able to support

03:32:28.560 --> 03:32:37.040
them and continually bring food and fodder for&nbsp;
the animals. Behind them, an ants’ trail of supply

03:32:37.040 --> 03:32:44.160
carts must have led back along the road, bringing&nbsp;
supplies over from their crucial bridges of boats,

03:32:44.160 --> 03:32:51.120
and supply depots that had been set up years&nbsp;
in advance fed the soldiers on their march.

03:32:52.800 --> 03:33:02.000
On their way, Herodotus describes the Persians&nbsp;
suffering problems with the local Greek wildlife.

03:33:02.000 --> 03:33:09.120
As Xerxes thus marched, lions attacked&nbsp;
the camels that carried his provisions.

03:33:09.120 --> 03:33:14.960
Nightly they would come down out&nbsp;
of their lairs and made havoc.

03:33:16.800 --> 03:33:22.880
Despite these challenges, Xerxes' army&nbsp;
soon passed the towering gray rock faces

03:33:22.880 --> 03:33:33.200
of Mount Olympus, and marched south into&nbsp;
the large fertile plains of Thessaly.

03:33:33.200 --> 03:33:38.639
Ahead of his advance he sent messengers&nbsp;
to the northern Greek regions and cities,

03:33:38.640 --> 03:33:43.120
demanding that they give him&nbsp;
offerings of earth and water.

03:33:44.080 --> 03:33:52.080
Many Greeks did so, and thereby went over to&nbsp;
the Persian side. These included the Greeks

03:33:52.080 --> 03:34:02.880
of Thessaly and Thebes, who hated the Athenians,
and even the people of the sacred center of Delphi.

03:34:02.880 --> 03:34:07.200
Some of these Greeks must have felt&nbsp;
that they had no other choice when

03:34:07.200 --> 03:34:12.000
faced with the might of Persia,&nbsp;
while others may have reveled in

03:34:12.000 --> 03:34:18.560
the opportunity to shift the dominance&nbsp;
of Athens and Sparta in the Greek world.

03:34:18.560 --> 03:34:29.279
Others chose their stance simply due to petty&nbsp;
rivalries within Greece, as Herodotus describes.

03:34:29.279 --> 03:34:35.040
The Phocians alone of all that region&nbsp;
would not take the Persians’ side,

03:34:35.040 --> 03:34:41.760
and that for no other reason than their hatred&nbsp;
of the Thessalians. Had the Thessalians aided

03:34:41.760 --> 03:34:50.080
the Greek side, then the Phocians would&nbsp;
certainly have stood for the Persians.

03:34:50.080 --> 03:34:55.600
But to Athens and Sparta, King&nbsp;
Xerxes sent no messengers,

03:34:55.600 --> 03:35:03.920
remembering bitterly how they had mistreated his&nbsp;
father's ambassadors a generation earlier. The

03:35:03.920 --> 03:35:10.960
Greeks who chose to stand up to the empire&nbsp;
were now outnumbered. They needed to find a

03:35:10.960 --> 03:35:16.960
way to gain an advantage, and they would&nbsp;
do this by using the landscape of Greece

03:35:16.960 --> 03:35:26.880
itself, a landscape of mountainous&nbsp;
highlands broken by narrow passes.

03:35:26.880 --> 03:35:33.120
Xerxes and his army were following the sea&nbsp;
shore, staying close to their supply ships,

03:35:33.120 --> 03:35:39.439
and their route would take them along one narrow&nbsp;
passage between the sea and the mountains.

03:35:40.319 --> 03:35:46.319
As the summer came to an end, this was the&nbsp;
place that the allied Greeks chose to defend

03:35:46.319 --> 03:35:57.920
the whole of the south, a place about 200 kilometers&nbsp;
northwest of Athens at a site called Thermopylae.

03:35:57.920 --> 03:36:03.520
Herodotus describes their deliberation.

03:36:03.520 --> 03:36:08.720
The Greeks consulted together how&nbsp;
and where they should stand to fight.

03:36:09.359 --> 03:36:15.279
The council that prevailed was that they&nbsp;
should guard the pass of Thermopylae,

03:36:15.279 --> 03:36:24.960
for they saw that it was narrower than&nbsp;the pass
into Thessaly, and moreover, nearer home.

03:36:24.960 --> 03:36:32.800
The name Thermopylae means ‘hot gates’, so named for&nbsp;
the sulfurous thermal springs that rise up out

03:36:32.800 --> 03:36:40.640
of the earth nearby. One legend has it that the&nbsp;
waters here are hot because it was here that the

03:36:40.640 --> 03:36:49.680
hero Heracles had tried to wash off the poison of&nbsp;
the fearsome Hydra. Today, the battlefield looks

03:36:49.680 --> 03:36:56.160
very different, since silt buildup from the&nbsp;
nearby Spercheios River has pushed back the

03:36:56.160 --> 03:37:06.000
ancient coastline and created a wide plane where&nbsp;
once a rocky bay stood. But in ancient times,

03:37:06.000 --> 03:37:13.040
the sea would have lapped close up to the sheer-&nbsp;
sided slope of Mount Kallidromos, creating a number

03:37:13.040 --> 03:37:22.000
of narrow bottlenecks which the Greeks called&nbsp;
gates. In ancient times, the Phocian people had

03:37:22.000 --> 03:37:28.880
built a wall at the pass of Thermopylae to keep&nbsp;
out the hated Thessalians, a rivalry that still

03:37:28.880 --> 03:37:39.520
burned to that day. But now this crumbling Phocian&nbsp;
wall would help repel a much different enemy.

03:37:39.520 --> 03:37:46.560
The Greeks hoped that with 20 to 30,000 heavily&nbsp;
armored hoplites holding the pass of Thermopylae,

03:37:46.560 --> 03:37:55.201
the Persians would have no hope but to turn back,&nbsp;
but things would not go according to their plan.

03:37:56.399 --> 03:38:05.519
This was partly because August&nbsp;
was the Greek season of leisure.

03:38:05.520 --> 03:38:10.720
The harvest had been brought in. The&nbsp;
days were long and languid, and the

03:38:10.720 --> 03:38:14.640
Olympic festival was taking place across Greece.

03:38:15.600 --> 03:38:21.680
This was a religious celebration of the king&nbsp;
of the gods, Zeus, combined with a series

03:38:21.680 --> 03:38:29.680
of athletic challenges held at the religious&nbsp;
sanctuary of Olympia every four years. Greeks

03:38:29.680 --> 03:38:36.640
had long observed a truce during the games so that&nbsp;
athletes and religious pilgrims could travel the

03:38:36.640 --> 03:38:45.920
roads without fear, and no one wanted to go to war&nbsp;
during the festival. In their rocky peninsula, the

03:38:45.920 --> 03:38:52.880
Spartans were once again celebrating their annual&nbsp;
festival of the Carneia when military campaigning

03:38:52.880 --> 03:39:00.800
was officially restricted. Perhaps if the Greeks&nbsp;
had realized how quickly the Persian army was

03:39:00.800 --> 03:39:11.439
advancing, they would have felt more urgency to&nbsp;
rush to the battlefield, as Herodotus describes.

03:39:11.439 --> 03:39:20.239
They intended, when they had celebrated the Carneian&nbsp;
festival, to leave a garrison in Sparta and hasten

03:39:20.239 --> 03:39:27.679
in full force to join the army. The rest of&nbsp;
the allies also intended to act similarly,

03:39:27.680 --> 03:39:33.600
for it had happened that the Olympic&nbsp;
festival fell exactly at this same period.

03:39:34.319 --> 03:39:43.599
None of them looked to see the contest&nbsp;
at Thermopylae decided so speedily.

03:39:43.600 --> 03:39:50.239
But rebuilding the Phocian wall would take time,&nbsp;
and they wanted to make sure it was ready when

03:39:50.239 --> 03:39:57.920
the main army arrived. To secure the pass&nbsp;
and begin the work of rebuilding this wall,

03:39:57.920 --> 03:40:04.399
the Spartans bent the rules and sent&nbsp;
a small unit of only 300 soldiers

03:40:04.399 --> 03:40:20.239
led by a son of King Cleomenes, a man whose&nbsp;
name meant ‘son of the lion’. His name was Leonidas.

03:40:20.239 --> 03:40:27.200
Leonidas and his small contingent were to rendezvous
at Thermopylae with a number of soldiers gathered

03:40:27.200 --> 03:40:34.720
from other Greek allies, totaling about 7,000&nbsp;
men, and ensure that no Persian advance party

03:40:34.720 --> 03:40:43.040
slipped through the pass. It was not a large&nbsp;
army, but it wasn't small either. In fact,

03:40:43.040 --> 03:40:48.960
it was only a few thousand smaller than the&nbsp;
force that had beat the Persians at Marathon.

03:40:50.560 --> 03:41:03.040
But Xerxes' army had moved&nbsp;
faster than anyone realized.

03:41:03.040 --> 03:41:08.239
The Persians arrived at the pass of&nbsp;
Thermopylae in early August to find

03:41:08.239 --> 03:41:17.920
only this small holding force stationed between&nbsp;
the mountains and the sea, blocking their way.

03:41:17.920 --> 03:41:27.680
The Greeks under Leonidas were taken completely&nbsp;
by surprise, and an awkward standoff ensued.

03:41:27.680 --> 03:41:34.880
At first, Xerxes didn't believe that the Greeks&nbsp;
actually intended to fight in this narrow pass.

03:41:34.880 --> 03:41:42.640
They were outnumbered as much as ten to one, and&nbsp;
in fact, the Persian king waited there for four days,

03:41:42.640 --> 03:41:50.080
expecting the Greeks to withdraw. But on&nbsp;
the fourth day, they were still there,

03:41:50.080 --> 03:42:02.319
blocking his only path. Frustrated at the lack&nbsp;
of progress, Xerxes ordered his men to attack.

03:42:02.319 --> 03:42:09.279
But the Greeks were perfectly suited to this&nbsp;
kind of warfare. Greek hoplites were heavily

03:42:09.279 --> 03:42:17.920
armored and carried large round shields, fighting&nbsp;
in a shield wall with long, seven-foot spears that kept

03:42:17.920 --> 03:42:25.840
their enemy at bay. On an open battlefield, they&nbsp;
were naturally weak to cavalry and vulnerable to

03:42:25.840 --> 03:42:32.479
being surrounded, but in the narrow paths&nbsp;
of Thermopylae, these weaknesses evaporated,

03:42:32.479 --> 03:42:39.919
and they simply refused to budge. Persian&nbsp;
warriors on the whole were lightly equipped,

03:42:39.920 --> 03:42:46.000
designed to move fast and travel long distances&nbsp;
across the empire to fight wherever they were

03:42:46.000 --> 03:42:53.680
needed. They were also from a culture with nomadic&nbsp;
warrior roots that may have viewed the heavy armor

03:42:53.680 --> 03:43:02.239
of the Greeks as an expression of cowardice. The&nbsp;
Greeks in turn looked down on the Persian tactics,

03:43:02.239 --> 03:43:12.880
and considered the bow and arrow to be a cowardly&nbsp;
weapon. Herodotus describes the ensuing combat.

03:43:12.880 --> 03:43:19.920
When the Persians moved forward and attacked the&nbsp;
Greeks, there fell many of them, and others kept

03:43:19.920 --> 03:43:27.199
coming up continually. And during these onsets,&nbsp;
it is said that the king, looking on, three times

03:43:27.199 --> 03:43:36.160
leapt up from his seat, struck with fear for&nbsp;
his army. Next, the Persians tried to pelt the

03:43:36.160 --> 03:43:42.720
Greeks with arrows to weaken their position,&nbsp;
but this bombardment only rained down on the

03:43:42.720 --> 03:43:50.320
broad shields of the hoplites, and soon the&nbsp;
Greeks were even cracking jokes about it.

03:43:52.000 --> 03:43:59.279
The Spartan Dienekes is said to have proved&nbsp;
himself the best man of all. Being informed

03:43:59.279 --> 03:44:04.160
by one of the men of Trachis that when&nbsp;
the barbarians discharged their arrows,

03:44:04.160 --> 03:44:09.680
they obscured the light of the sun by&nbsp;
the multitude of the arrows, he was not

03:44:09.680 --> 03:44:16.960
dismayed by this. He said that their guest&nbsp;
from Trachis brought them very good news,

03:44:16.960 --> 03:44:27.040
for if the Medes obscured the light of the sun,&nbsp;
the battle against them would be in the shade.

03:44:27.040 --> 03:44:34.479
The fighting went on for three days. Throughout&nbsp;
this time, the Greeks rotated out the men who

03:44:34.479 --> 03:44:40.239
fought at the front of their lines so they&nbsp;
didn't become exhausted, and by this time,

03:44:40.239 --> 03:44:48.160
Xerxes' frustration must have grown to genuine&nbsp;
concern. The pass of Thermopylae had been held to

03:44:48.160 --> 03:44:55.760
great effect by only 7,000 men, and he began to&nbsp;
realize that if the main force of Greeks arrived,

03:44:55.760 --> 03:45:02.720
probably three or four times that number, it&nbsp;
might hold out forever, and his invasion of Greece

03:45:02.720 --> 03:45:13.279
would stop right there on the rocky shore of the&nbsp;
Malian Gulf. But in the end, Xerxes would prevail,

03:45:13.279 --> 03:45:19.599
and his victory would come not at the tip of&nbsp;
a spear but with Persian experience, at the

03:45:19.600 --> 03:45:27.840
careful and meticulous gathering of intelligence.&nbsp;
Wherever they went, they were adept at developing

03:45:27.840 --> 03:45:35.840
a network of spies and informers, and everywhere&nbsp;
the flash of Persian gold, each coin stamped with

03:45:35.840 --> 03:45:44.080
the symbol of an archer, paved the way to&nbsp;
the information they needed. At Thermopylae,

03:45:44.080 --> 03:45:50.319
they soon found a local man who was able to&nbsp;
show them another pass through the mountains,

03:45:50.319 --> 03:45:59.599
concealed with forests of oak. Ephialtes,&nbsp;
the son of Eurydemus, came to Xerxes and was

03:45:59.600 --> 03:46:06.800
admitted to a conference. Stirred by the hope&nbsp;
of receiving a rich reward at the king's hands,

03:46:06.800 --> 03:46:13.199
he had come to tell him of the pathway which&nbsp;
led across the mountain to Thermopylae, by which

03:46:13.199 --> 03:46:21.920
disclosure he brought destruction on the band of&nbsp;
Greeks, who had there withstood the barbarians.

03:46:24.800 --> 03:46:30.479
This path would allow them to cut off,&nbsp;
surround, and utterly destroy the army,

03:46:30.479 --> 03:46:36.719
blocking the Thermopylae Pass. When&nbsp;
the Greeks heard of the Persian plan,

03:46:36.720 --> 03:46:44.400
they saw that they would be surrounded, and&nbsp;
King Leonidas knew that the battle was lost.

03:46:45.600 --> 03:46:52.000
He ordered the rest of the army to retreat,&nbsp;
and stayed behind with his royal bodyguard and

03:46:52.000 --> 03:47:02.800
some assorted Thespian and Theban allies&nbsp;
to hold the pass a little while longer.

03:47:02.800 --> 03:47:07.840
This was an act of personal bravery&nbsp;
by the Spartans who remained, but it

03:47:07.840 --> 03:47:13.120
was also a tactical necessity.&nbsp;
If the whole army retreated,

03:47:13.120 --> 03:47:21.519
Persian heavy cavalry would have pursued&nbsp;
them and likely cut them down to a man.

03:47:21.520 --> 03:47:28.239
Spartan hoplites had also been raised within&nbsp;
a brutal warrior culture that demanded their

03:47:28.239 --> 03:47:36.479
sacrifice in battle. Men who returned from&nbsp;
losing battles were often treated as cowards

03:47:36.479 --> 03:47:44.879
and shunned in Spartan society. Even two men&nbsp;
who Leonidas sent away from Thermopylae due

03:47:44.880 --> 03:47:54.560
to injuries were treated as outcasts when they&nbsp;
returned to the city, as Herodotus describes.

03:47:54.560 --> 03:48:02.720
When Aristodemus returned to Sparta, reproach and&nbsp;
disgrace awaited him. No Spartan would give him

03:48:02.720 --> 03:48:12.160
a light to kindle his fire, or so much as address&nbsp;
a word to him. All spoke of him as the coward.

03:48:12.160 --> 03:48:19.680
Another of the 300 is likewise said to have&nbsp;
survived the battle, a man named Pantites. He,

03:48:19.680 --> 03:48:31.120
they said, on his return to Sparta found himself&nbsp;
in such disesteem that he hanged himself.

03:48:31.120 --> 03:48:38.479
For Xerxes, the battle at Thermopylae had been&nbsp;
a resounding victory. He had surprised his

03:48:38.479 --> 03:48:44.719
enemy before their reinforcements were able to&nbsp;
arrive, outmaneuvered them on their home soil,

03:48:44.720 --> 03:48:51.199
and forced them to retreat from the choke point&nbsp;
they had hoped to defend. And, thrown into the

03:48:51.199 --> 03:48:58.479
bargain, he had cut off and killed one of the&nbsp;
two kings of Sparta, meaning that a child now

03:48:58.479 --> 03:49:07.120
sat on one of its thrones. For the Greeks,&nbsp;
Thermopylae was a sorry defeat tactically and

03:49:07.120 --> 03:49:14.000
strategically, but virtually from the moment the&nbsp;
battle ended, they began putting it to another

03:49:14.000 --> 03:49:23.520
purpose; that was of propaganda. The legend of the&nbsp;
heroic last stand of Leonidas would be repeated

03:49:23.520 --> 03:49:30.800
over and over, and used as a rallying call to&nbsp;
other Greeks to fight against the Persians.

03:49:33.120 --> 03:49:37.760
Herodotus himself was so inspired&nbsp;
by the story of the battle that

03:49:37.760 --> 03:49:46.880
he claimed to have memorized the names of&nbsp;
all 300 of the Spartans who fought there.

03:49:46.880 --> 03:49:53.520
Leonidas fell fighting bravely, together with&nbsp;
many other famous Spartans, whose names I have

03:49:53.520 --> 03:50:05.359
taken care to learn on account of their great&nbsp;
worthiness, as indeed I have those of all the 300.

03:50:05.359 --> 03:50:11.279
At the same time that the battle of Thermopylae&nbsp;
was going on, the Greek fleet had also clashed

03:50:11.279 --> 03:50:18.319
with the Persian navy at the nearby straits of&nbsp;
Artemisium, and on the sea, the contest was

03:50:18.319 --> 03:50:25.519
a little more even. Both sides took heavy&nbsp;
losses, but the heavily outnumbered Greek

03:50:25.520 --> 03:50:32.880
fleet was forced to retreat when they heard&nbsp;
about the defeat at Thermopylae. Their ships

03:50:32.880 --> 03:50:43.199
were scattered, and limped home to the island of&nbsp;
Salamis, which sits just off the Athenian coast.

03:50:43.199 --> 03:50:47.519
With the final choke point on&nbsp;
the way to Athens now overcome,

03:50:47.520 --> 03:50:59.840
the Persian army eagerly advanced into southern&nbsp;
Greece, looting and burning as they went.

03:50:59.840 --> 03:51:07.040
The Athenians hoped that the Spartans would help&nbsp;
defend their city, but they would be disappointed.

03:51:07.920 --> 03:51:15.040
Sparta withdrew all its forces right back to the&nbsp;
Peloponnese peninsula, where they began building

03:51:15.040 --> 03:51:21.760
a wall across its narrow isthmus of Corinth,&nbsp;
trying to achieve there what they had failed

03:51:21.760 --> 03:51:32.000
to do at Thermopylae. But that meant that the&nbsp;
city of Athens was left all but defenseless.

03:51:32.000 --> 03:51:38.640
Realizing that they were now alone, the&nbsp;
Athenians fled the city. The refugees

03:51:38.640 --> 03:51:48.960
boarded ships and escaped to the nearby island&nbsp;
of Salamis, leaving Athens a ghost town.

03:51:48.960 --> 03:51:52.960
They made a proclamation that&nbsp;
every Athenian should save his

03:51:52.960 --> 03:51:58.319
children and servants as he best&nbsp;
could. Thereupon most of them sent

03:51:58.319 --> 03:52:04.960
the members of their households to&nbsp;
Troezen, and some to Aegina and Salamis.

03:52:07.120 --> 03:52:10.479
The Persians swept into the deserted city,

03:52:10.479 --> 03:52:20.080
killed a few determined defenders holed up in&nbsp;
the Acropolis, and burned Athens to the ground.

03:52:20.080 --> 03:52:23.840
Its tightly packed houses of wood and mud-brick

03:52:23.840 --> 03:52:31.760
burned swiftly. The burning of&nbsp;
Sardis had finally been avenged.

03:52:33.520 --> 03:52:39.520
Xerxes must have been delighted. In&nbsp;
only four months, he had achieved

03:52:39.520 --> 03:52:46.239
the dream of his father, and now stood&nbsp;
upon the smoldering ruins of Athens.

03:52:46.239 --> 03:52:53.199
His invasion had been a roaring success,&nbsp;
and his enemies now scattered before him.

03:52:54.239 --> 03:53:01.359
All he needed to do was round on the now isolated&nbsp;
city of Sparta, break through their makeshift

03:53:01.359 --> 03:53:09.519
Corinthian wall, and crush them completely. At&nbsp;
the sight of the Persian army on the horizon,

03:53:09.520 --> 03:53:16.239
it's likely that Sparta's helot underclass would&nbsp;
have taken the opportunity to rebel, and facing

03:53:16.239 --> 03:53:22.639
their enemies from within and without, the last&nbsp;
independent power in Greece would have fallen.

03:53:26.560 --> 03:53:32.160
But this Xerxes didn't do.

03:53:32.160 --> 03:53:40.479
Instead, he made an enormous mistake. Against&nbsp;
the advice of one of his chief naval commanders,

03:53:40.479 --> 03:53:48.239
a queen named Artemisia of Halicarnassus, he ordered&nbsp;
his fleet to round on the island of Salamis, where

03:53:48.239 --> 03:53:56.479
the Athenian refugees were sheltering, and destroy&nbsp;
what remained of the Greek ships harbored there.

03:53:58.239 --> 03:54:03.599
This Greek fleet had actually been&nbsp;
built only three years earlier, on the

03:54:03.600 --> 03:54:13.439
urging of a particular Athenian statesman&nbsp;
named Themistocles, as Herodotus recounts.

03:54:13.439 --> 03:54:20.960
Now there was a certain Athenian, by name&nbsp;
Themistocles, who had lately risen to be among

03:54:20.960 --> 03:54:28.560
their chief men. Themistocles persuaded&nbsp;the
Athenians to build two hundred ships of war,

03:54:28.560 --> 03:54:35.520
compelling the Athenians to become sailors.

03:54:35.520 --> 03:54:38.560
These ships were of the latest design,

03:54:38.560 --> 03:54:45.120
large and heavy warships that dwarfed the&nbsp;
smaller Persian ships, but they were also

03:54:45.120 --> 03:54:51.439
drastically outnumbered by the Persian&nbsp;
fleet, which had perhaps five hundred vessels.

03:54:53.920 --> 03:54:59.040
Now sure of victory, the Persians&nbsp;
sailed in and descended on the

03:54:59.040 --> 03:55:08.399
scattered Athenians, but things&nbsp;
would not go to Xerxes' plan.

03:55:08.399 --> 03:55:16.319
Once again, the Greeks chose their battlefield&nbsp;
well. In the cramped straits of Salamis,

03:55:16.319 --> 03:55:20.399
the Persian warships were forced to cram together,

03:55:20.399 --> 03:55:27.199
preventing their oars from moving. Meanwhile,&nbsp;
the Greeks knew the winds and currents of

03:55:27.199 --> 03:55:32.160
these waters; some of them would have been&nbsp;
sailing and fishing there since they were

03:55:32.160 --> 03:55:40.239
children. They rammed into the flanks of the&nbsp;
trapped Persian fleet to devastating effect.

03:55:41.680 --> 03:55:46.479
The playwright Aeschylus, likely an&nbsp;
eyewitness of the battle and who

03:55:46.479 --> 03:55:55.040
would lose his brother in the fighting, would&nbsp;
write the following description of the carnage.

03:55:55.040 --> 03:56:00.880
When the mass of their ships had been crowded in&nbsp;
the narrows, and none could render another aid,

03:56:00.880 --> 03:56:07.120
and each crashed its bronze prow against&nbsp;
each of its own line. They splintered

03:56:07.120 --> 03:56:13.920
their whole bank of oars. Then the Greek galleys&nbsp;
hemmed them in and battered them on every

03:56:13.920 --> 03:56:20.479
side. The shores and reefs were crowded&nbsp;
with dead, and every ship that formed a

03:56:20.479 --> 03:56:27.599
part of the barbarian fleet plied its&nbsp;
oars in disorderly flight. Groans and

03:56:27.600 --> 03:56:37.360
shrieks together filled the open sea until&nbsp;
the face of black night hid the scene.

03:56:47.439 --> 03:56:55.040
The battle of Salamis was a disaster.&nbsp;
Among the dead were several of Xerxes'

03:56:55.040 --> 03:57:03.359
own brothers and countless Persian noblemen&nbsp;
from the court of Persepolis. When news reached

03:57:03.359 --> 03:57:11.120
the Persians of what had happened,&nbsp;
Herodotus imagines their reaction.

03:57:11.120 --> 03:57:17.359
When the first message came to Susa,&nbsp;
telling that Xerxes had taken Athens,

03:57:17.359 --> 03:57:23.599
it gave such delight to the Persians who were&nbsp;
left at home that they strewed all the roads

03:57:23.600 --> 03:57:29.520
with myrtle boughs and burnt incense and&nbsp;
gave themselves up to sacrificial feasts

03:57:29.520 --> 03:57:35.840
and jollity. But the second message,&nbsp;
coming on the heels of the first,

03:57:35.840 --> 03:57:47.760
so confounded them that they all rent their&nbsp;
tunics and cried and lamented without ceasing.

03:57:47.760 --> 03:57:53.279
Once the dust of the battle had settled,&nbsp;
Xerxes must have realized the enormity

03:57:53.279 --> 03:58:01.840
of his mistake. His fleet was a crucial&nbsp;
element in his invasion. With it destroyed,

03:58:01.840 --> 03:58:07.040
his army now had no way of getting&nbsp;
supplies from the Persian mainland,

03:58:07.040 --> 03:58:15.040
and they feared being stranded in&nbsp;
Europe, as Herodotus describes.

03:58:15.040 --> 03:58:20.160
When Xerxes was aware of the&nbsp;
calamity that had befallen him,

03:58:20.160 --> 03:58:26.160
he feared lest the Greeks might sail&nbsp;
to the Hellespont to break his bridges,

03:58:26.160 --> 03:58:36.479
and he might be cut off in Europe and in&nbsp;
peril of his life. And so, he planned to flee.

03:58:36.479 --> 03:58:44.479
Xerxes soon departed, and took more than&nbsp;
half of his army with him. His most capable

03:58:44.479 --> 03:58:51.439
troops he left in the care of the veteran&nbsp;
general Mardonius and took the rest north,

03:58:51.439 --> 03:58:55.599
crossing back over his bridges of boats.

03:58:57.120 --> 03:59:03.120
The reasons for this departure we can&nbsp;
never know. Herodotus paints a picture

03:59:03.120 --> 03:59:09.040
of a cowardly king fleeing in panic, but&nbsp;
it may not have looked like this from the

03:59:09.040 --> 03:59:16.319
Persian side. They had achieved virtually all&nbsp;
of their war aims, and the king had to return

03:59:16.319 --> 03:59:23.840
home to participate in the ceremonial calendar of&nbsp;
Persian royalty. He may have assumed that the war

03:59:23.840 --> 03:59:34.239
was simply over. But regardless, the king's&nbsp;
departure certainly emboldened the Greeks.

03:59:34.239 --> 03:59:42.719
In 479 BC, the Greek allies were able to amass&nbsp;
an enormous force, perhaps the largest Greek

03:59:42.720 --> 03:59:48.640
army ever gathered, and marched out to meet&nbsp;
the Persians, who were still camped in the

03:59:48.640 --> 03:59:56.720
ruins of Athens. When he heard that this army&nbsp;
was approaching, the Persian general Mardonius

03:59:56.720 --> 04:00:05.040
ordered that everything left standing in the&nbsp;
city be torn down to the very foundations.

04:00:05.040 --> 04:00:15.040
Then he retreated to a wide plain at a place&nbsp;
called Plataea. There, the combined forces of

04:00:15.040 --> 04:00:22.800
Athens and Sparta converged on the Persians and&nbsp;
the 20 to 30,000 Greek allies who fought alongside

04:00:22.800 --> 04:00:31.600
them. Now surrounded, exhausted, and cut off from&nbsp;
their supplies, and with their king departed for

04:00:31.600 --> 04:00:41.359
home, the Persians were finally overcome. So long&nbsp;
as Mardonius was alive, the Persians stood their

04:00:41.359 --> 04:00:48.559
ground and defended themselves, overthrowing&nbsp;
many Spartans. But when Mardonius was slain,

04:00:48.560 --> 04:00:59.199
and his guards, who were the strongest part of the&nbsp;
army, then the rest, too, yielded and gained ground.

04:00:59.199 --> 04:01:04.000
The Persian army retreated from&nbsp;
the battle to their fortified camp,

04:01:04.000 --> 04:01:08.880
which the Greeks surrounded.&nbsp;
They breached the walls and

04:01:08.880 --> 04:01:20.000
began a general slaughter that left few&nbsp;
alive. The general Mardonius was killed.

04:01:20.000 --> 04:01:26.960
From this moment on, the Persian force that&nbsp;
Xerxes had brought to Greece was no more,

04:01:26.960 --> 04:01:34.080
and all Persian attempts to conquer&nbsp;
the Greek mainland came to an end.

04:01:39.600 --> 04:01:43.920
But Xerxes, for his part, put a typical Persian

04:01:43.920 --> 04:01:51.680
spin on the situation. On one of his&nbsp;
inscriptions he had carved at Persepolis,

04:01:51.680 --> 04:02:00.480
he includes one oblique reference that many&nbsp;
think refers to this disastrous campaign.

04:02:01.840 --> 04:02:08.560
When I became king, there was one among&nbsp;
the countries which was in disorder.

04:02:08.560 --> 04:02:29.760
By the favor of Ahura Mazda, I overwhelmed&nbsp;
that country and put it in its proper place.

04:02:34.160 --> 04:02:43.359
Despite Xerxes' attempts to spin it, the defeat&nbsp;
in Greece was not a minor setback for the empire.

04:02:43.359 --> 04:02:49.519
Persia had marched across the Hellespont with a&nbsp;
huge force of men brought from every corner of

04:02:49.520 --> 04:02:59.359
its domain, and these had been all but eradicated.&nbsp;
In every part of the empire, wives and mothers and

04:02:59.359 --> 04:03:08.799
children would now mourn the men who never came&nbsp;
home. In Egypt, women let their hair fall loose

04:03:08.800 --> 04:03:17.040
and scattered sand on their heads as incense&nbsp;
drifted through the streets. In Babylon, wives

04:03:17.040 --> 04:03:27.279
tore their robes and sat in silence with ash on&nbsp;
their faces. In Media, riders wore black wool and

04:03:27.279 --> 04:03:35.759
led their horses unbridled through the streets, and&nbsp;
everywhere the empire's failure would have been

04:03:35.760 --> 04:03:44.239
understood. Even in the Persian royal court, a&nbsp;
significant period of mourning must have followed.

04:03:44.880 --> 04:03:53.760
Xerxes' own sister was the wife of the general&nbsp;
Mardonius, who he had abandoned to fight at Plataea,

04:03:53.760 --> 04:04:02.880
and a multitude of courtiers now lay at the&nbsp;
bottom of the Bay of Salamis. The campaign

04:04:02.880 --> 04:04:10.720
was a strategic disaster, too. For the next fifty&nbsp;
years, the Persian Empire would have to contend

04:04:10.720 --> 04:04:18.239
with the fleets of the emboldened Greek states&nbsp;
buzzing like hornets around its western fringes,

04:04:18.239 --> 04:04:27.920
and whenever a rebellion flared up anywhere in&nbsp;
Persia, the Greeks made sure to support it. But

04:04:27.920 --> 04:04:34.880
the blow was far from a fatal one, and in fact,&nbsp;
the Persian Empire continued to flourish for

04:04:34.880 --> 04:04:52.880
another 150 years, and during this time, it&nbsp;
continued to export its influence overseas.

04:04:52.880 --> 04:05:00.800
Over the next decades, while the Greeks rebuilt&nbsp;
their devastated cities, they regaled each other

04:05:00.800 --> 04:05:09.360
with tales of the Persian Wars, now as momentous&nbsp;
in their minds as the Trojan War once had been.

04:05:10.239 --> 04:05:16.399
The playwright Aeschylus, himself a veteran&nbsp;
of many of the battles, delighted Athenian

04:05:16.399 --> 04:05:22.559
audiences by putting words into the&nbsp;
mouth of Xerxes himself in his play

04:05:22.560 --> 04:05:30.960
The Persians, which he debuted only&nbsp;
eight years after the Battle of Salamis.

04:05:30.960 --> 04:05:39.040
Alas, wretched I am, who have met this cruel&nbsp;
doom, which did not give the faintest sign

04:05:39.040 --> 04:05:46.560
of its coming. In what savage mood has&nbsp;
fortune trampled upon the Persian race?

04:05:46.560 --> 04:05:54.960
What misery is yet in store for me?&nbsp;
Unhappy wretch. The land bewails her

04:05:54.960 --> 04:06:07.840
native youth, slaughtered for Xerxes, who has&nbsp;
crowded the underworld with Persian slain.

04:06:07.840 --> 04:06:13.920
But as much as they enjoyed stories of their&nbsp;
underdog victory, throughout the decades that

04:06:13.920 --> 04:06:21.760
followed, Greeks, and especially Athenians,&nbsp;
began to develop a taste for Persian things.

04:06:24.960 --> 04:06:32.800
One of the biggest influences on Athens was in&nbsp;
the realm of fashion. By the middle of the fifth

04:06:32.800 --> 04:06:39.760
century BC, we can see from painted vases&nbsp;
that clothes with sleeves began to appear

04:06:39.760 --> 04:06:48.720
on Athenian streets, patterned in Persian styles.&nbsp;
Some of these garments were made in Athens, but

04:06:48.720 --> 04:06:56.960
others were actually imported from Persia itself.&nbsp;
Archaeologists have found traces of Indian cotton

04:06:56.960 --> 04:07:04.160
and Chinese silk in Athenian graves beginning&nbsp;
around this time, showing that Persian goods were

04:07:04.160 --> 04:07:12.960
flowing into the city in record amounts. Athenians&nbsp;
also began wearing Persian-style slippers on their

04:07:12.960 --> 04:07:22.319
feet. In his work, A History of the Pelonponnesian&nbsp;
War, Thucydides criticizes the Athenian love of

04:07:22.319 --> 04:07:30.239
these Eastern fashions. The Athenians were the&nbsp;
first to lay aside their weapons and to adopt an

04:07:30.239 --> 04:07:36.399
easier and more luxurious mode of life. Indeed,&nbsp;
their rich old men had the luxury of wearing

04:07:36.399 --> 04:07:42.559
undergarments of linen and fastening a knot of&nbsp;
their hair with a tie of golden grasshoppers.

04:07:44.080 --> 04:07:51.120
For a long time, Greeks had particularly mocked&nbsp;
the Persian custom of carrying parasols to

04:07:51.120 --> 04:07:57.199
protect themselves from the sun, but in&nbsp;
the decades following the Persian Wars,

04:07:57.199 --> 04:08:03.840
wealthy Greeks in Athens themselves began&nbsp;
carrying parasols, and for the especially

04:08:03.840 --> 04:08:11.600
wealthy Athenians, they imitated Persian kings in&nbsp;
having their slaves carry the parasols for them.

04:08:13.199 --> 04:08:19.040
It has even been suggested that when the&nbsp;
Greeks rebuilt the Parthenon at the heart

04:08:19.040 --> 04:08:25.279
of the Athenian Acropolis on top of the&nbsp;
rubble left by the Persians, the Athenians

04:08:25.279 --> 04:08:33.920
imitated the styles of the palaces of Persia,&nbsp;
in particular the Persepolis friezes. Just like

04:08:33.920 --> 04:08:40.479
the palace of Persepolis, the Parthenon Marbles
show all the peoples of the Athenian lands,

04:08:40.479 --> 04:08:47.199
bringing goods and tribute to the great&nbsp;
city. It's possible that the craftsmen

04:08:47.199 --> 04:08:58.639
they brought in to do the work had also honed&nbsp;
their craft while working on Persian palaces.

04:09:04.720 --> 04:09:12.239
The great King Xerxes never let go of&nbsp;
his obsession. Over the next decade,

04:09:12.239 --> 04:09:17.599
he gathered another army and fleet in&nbsp;
order to crush what was now an open

04:09:17.600 --> 04:09:23.360
rebellion among Greek city-states all&nbsp;
along the western coast of his empire.

04:09:23.920 --> 04:09:32.880
But these forces were destroyed in the battle&nbsp;
of Eurymedon in 469 BC, a daring strike by the

04:09:32.880 --> 04:09:42.560
Greeks that actually took place in&nbsp;
Persian lands, as Thucydides recounts.

04:09:42.560 --> 04:09:47.680
The Athenians won both battles on the same&nbsp;
day, and captured and destroyed the whole

04:09:47.680 --> 04:09:57.040
Phoenician fleet, consisting of 200 vessels. This&nbsp;
battle was a symptom of just how emboldened the

04:09:57.040 --> 04:10:05.120
Greeks had now become. Perhaps it was this final&nbsp;
defeat that would have turned Xerxes away from

04:10:05.120 --> 04:10:15.359
Greece forever, but we will never know. That's&nbsp;
because four years later, in the autumn of 465 BC,

04:10:15.359 --> 04:10:21.199
a commander of the king's bodyguard&nbsp;
named Artabanus conspired along with

04:10:21.199 --> 04:10:31.120
a palace eunuch to seize the throne,&nbsp;
as the Greek writer Ctesias recounts.

04:10:31.120 --> 04:10:35.680
Artabanus, the commander of the&nbsp;
god, plotted against Xerxes.

04:10:35.680 --> 04:10:43.600
He went in by night to the king's&nbsp;
chamber and slew him while he slept.

04:10:43.600 --> 04:10:50.239
The son and heir of Xerxes, named Darius, was&nbsp;
also killed in the violence that suddenly

04:10:50.239 --> 04:10:58.239
engulfed the palace. When the conspiracy&nbsp;
was discovered, another of Xerxes' sons

04:10:58.239 --> 04:11:06.880
drew his sword and came to revenge his father. He&nbsp;
managed to kill the plotting eunuch and the general

04:11:06.880 --> 04:11:17.439
Artabanus, and foil their plan. This man's&nbsp;
name in Old Persian was Artakh-shathra, or

04:11:17.439 --> 04:11:29.439
‘he who holds power through truth’. But in Greek&nbsp;
he would come to be known as Artaxerxes.

04:11:41.760 --> 04:11:48.239
King Artaxerxes seems to have had a&nbsp;
quite different temperament to his rash

04:11:48.239 --> 04:11:55.679
and vengeful father, Xerxes. We can see&nbsp;
this demonstrated in the story of the

04:11:55.680 --> 04:12:01.760
incredible career of one Athenian Greek&nbsp;
who had been instrumental in the defeat

04:12:01.760 --> 04:12:18.479
of Xerxes only thirty years earlier. That was the&nbsp;
Athenian statesman and admiral, Themistocles.

04:12:18.479 --> 04:12:25.279
Themistocles was the man who had first convinced&nbsp;
the Athenians to build a fleet, and he had

04:12:25.279 --> 04:12:33.040
commanded it during the pivotal battle of&nbsp;
Salamis. He was perhaps the one man most

04:12:33.040 --> 04:12:40.399
responsible for repelling the Persian invasion,&nbsp;
but in the years since, Themistocles had fallen

04:12:40.399 --> 04:12:49.439
out of favor in Athens. Eventually, its citizens&nbsp;
voted to ostracize him from the city, a kind of

04:12:49.439 --> 04:13:00.479
exile. Humiliated and outcast, Themistocles then&nbsp;
left Greece. But instead of fading into obscurity,

04:13:00.479 --> 04:13:07.359
he took the decision to travel to Persia, where&nbsp;
he presented himself at the court of the son of

04:13:07.359 --> 04:13:17.120
his great enemy, King Artaxerxes. This was&nbsp;
an especially daring move, because in Persia,

04:13:17.120 --> 04:13:25.599
Themistocles actually had a bounty on his head&nbsp;
set at 200 talents, or more than five metric tons

04:13:25.600 --> 04:13:34.319
of silver. But when Themistocles presented&nbsp;
himself before the new Persian King of Kings,

04:13:34.319 --> 04:13:40.960
Artaxerxes seemed more amused&nbsp;
than anything, as Plutarch recounts.

04:13:42.239 --> 04:13:48.000
When he had come into the king's presence, the&nbsp;
king welcomed him and spake him kindly, and said

04:13:48.000 --> 04:13:53.520
he already owed the Greek 200 talents;&nbsp;
for since he had delivered himself up,

04:13:53.520 --> 04:14:01.520
it was only just that he should receive&nbsp;
the reward proclaimed for his capture.

04:14:01.520 --> 04:14:07.120
The king next asked Themistocles to&nbsp;
explain why he had come before him,

04:14:07.120 --> 04:14:14.479
but the Greek apologized that he had&nbsp;
not yet learned the Persian language.

04:14:14.479 --> 04:14:20.080
Themistocles answered that the speech of man&nbsp;
was like embroidered tapestries, since when it

04:14:20.080 --> 04:14:26.559
was rolled up, it concealed and distorted&nbsp;
its patterns. For this reason, he had need

04:14:26.560 --> 04:14:33.439
of time. Themistocles asked for a year, and&nbsp;
in that time he learned the Persian language

04:14:33.439 --> 04:14:41.519
sufficiently to have interviews with the&nbsp;
king by himself, without interpreters.

04:14:41.520 --> 04:14:47.520
Themistocles soon became a trusted adviser&nbsp;
to the Persian king, and over the next six

04:14:47.520 --> 04:14:53.840
or seven years, taught him how to deal
with his Greek enemies. And perhaps

04:14:53.840 --> 04:14:59.199
partly due to the advice of the man who&nbsp;
had once destroyed his father's fleet,

04:14:59.199 --> 04:15:07.599
Artaxerxes struck upon a new&nbsp;
way of handling the Greek problem.

04:15:12.640 --> 04:15:17.840
By this time, the Athenians were becoming&nbsp;
so bold that they were actually supporting

04:15:17.840 --> 04:15:27.520
a rebellion in Egypt, clearly aiming to break the&nbsp;
Persian Empire apart piece by piece. In response,

04:15:27.520 --> 04:15:33.600
Artaxerxes began a policy so simple&nbsp;
and effective that it's remarkable no

04:15:33.600 --> 04:15:40.399
Persian king had thought of it before.&nbsp;
He began pouring funds towards Athens'

04:15:40.399 --> 04:15:49.599
enemies in Greece, and the greatest rival&nbsp;
of Athens was, of course, Sparta. The Greek

04:15:49.600 --> 04:15:56.160
writer Thucydides wrote the following&nbsp;
description of what happened next.

04:15:57.840 --> 04:16:04.319
For a short time, the Greek league held together&nbsp;
‘til the Spartans and Athenians quarreled, and

04:16:04.319 --> 04:16:10.239
made war upon each other with their allies,&nbsp;
a duel into which all the Greeks sooner or

04:16:10.239 --> 04:16:16.159
later were drawn, though some might at first&nbsp;
remain neutral. So that the whole period from

04:16:16.159 --> 04:16:24.399
the Persian War to this, with some peaceful&nbsp;
intervals, was spent by each power in war.

04:16:27.359 --> 04:16:34.799
This conflict would become known as the Peloponnesian&nbsp;
War, and it would rage for nearly three decades

04:16:34.800 --> 04:16:44.239
after 431 BC. During all this time, the Persians&nbsp;
made sure to put all of their resources at

04:16:44.239 --> 04:16:51.840
Sparta's disposal, and in exchange, the Greeks&nbsp;
were willing to give the Persians concessions

04:16:51.840 --> 04:17:00.080
that up to that point had seemed unthinkable.&nbsp;
They would soon relinquish any claim to the Greek

04:17:00.080 --> 04:17:10.319
cities in Asia Minor, as the following treaty&nbsp;
proposed between Persia and Sparta states.

04:17:10.319 --> 04:17:16.559
"Whatever country or cities the king has&nbsp;
or the king's ancestors had shall be the

04:17:16.560 --> 04:17:23.920
kings, and whatever came into the Athenians from&nbsp;
these cities, either money or any other thing,

04:17:23.920 --> 04:17:30.640
the king and the Spartans shall jointly hinder&nbsp;
the Athenians from receiving. The war with the

04:17:30.640 --> 04:17:38.800
Athenians shall be carried on jointly by the&nbsp;
king and by the Spartans and their allies.”

04:17:40.960 --> 04:17:46.080
Sparta had always been a land&nbsp;
power and had hardly any navy,

04:17:46.080 --> 04:17:52.640
something that put them at a disadvantage to&nbsp;
the Athenians in war, but the Persians funded

04:17:52.640 --> 04:17:57.199
the construction of a large fleet&nbsp;
for Sparta to match the Athenians

04:17:57.199 --> 04:18:05.599
at sea and to ensure that the war&nbsp;
dragged on for as long as possible.

04:18:05.600 --> 04:18:11.279
Some decades later, during the Corinthian&nbsp;
war that followed, the Persians would in

04:18:11.279 --> 04:18:17.759
turn fund the Athenians to build a new fleet&nbsp;
of their own to destroy a Spartan fleet that

04:18:17.760 --> 04:18:26.399
the Persians had also funded. While this policy&nbsp;
may have seemed circular and a little ridiculous,

04:18:26.399 --> 04:18:32.319
it successfully kept the major cities of&nbsp;
Greece occupied, fighting one another.

04:18:33.120 --> 04:18:42.640
Never again would they marshal the kind of united&nbsp;
force that had defeated the Persians at Plataea.

04:18:42.640 --> 04:18:46.720
One Spartan king would later remark bitterly that

04:18:46.720 --> 04:18:53.040
the Greeks had been defeated by 10,000&nbsp;
Persian archers, meaning not an army,

04:18:53.040 --> 04:19:00.560
but the symbol of an archer that the empire&nbsp;
stamped on each one of its gold coins.

04:19:02.560 --> 04:19:05.279
With this shrewd foreign policy,

04:19:05.279 --> 04:19:23.120
the Persian Empire's western border&nbsp;
finally achieved a level of stability.

04:19:23.120 --> 04:19:29.680
Artaxerxes ruled for forty-one years, longer&nbsp;
than either of the more famous kings

04:19:29.680 --> 04:19:38.399
Darius or Xerxes, and his rule was arguably&nbsp;
more successful. His shrewd foreign policy

04:19:38.399 --> 04:19:48.080
coupled with domestic stability, and the empire&nbsp;
flourished. But after his death in 424 BC,

04:19:48.080 --> 04:19:57.359
the trouble began. His son, Xerxes II, would&nbsp;
rule for only forty-five days before two of his

04:19:57.359 --> 04:20:04.880
brothers plotted to depose him. One of these&nbsp;
brothers, named Sogdianus, took the throne, but

04:20:04.880 --> 04:20:13.120
ruled for only six months before himself being&nbsp;
deposed. The empire returned to some degree

04:20:13.120 --> 04:20:21.519
of stability during the twenty-year reign of King&nbsp;
Darius II, but when he died in 404 BC, it would

04:20:21.520 --> 04:20:30.560
once more return to a bloody and destructive&nbsp;
state of civil war. This conflict came about

04:20:30.560 --> 04:20:40.960
due to a rivalry between two of Darius' sons; his&nbsp;
eldest son, Arses, and the youngest son, Cyrus.

04:20:42.479 --> 04:20:49.599
While Arses had always been favored by his father&nbsp;
the king as a thoughtful and pragmatic young man,

04:20:49.600 --> 04:20:58.399
Cyrus was the most beloved of their mother,&nbsp;
as the Greek writer Xenophon records.

04:20:58.399 --> 04:21:04.719
Darius had two sons. The elder was&nbsp;
named Arses and the younger Cyrus. Now,

04:21:04.720 --> 04:21:10.640
as Darius lay sick and felt that the end of&nbsp;
life drew near, he wished both his sons to be

04:21:10.640 --> 04:21:19.600
with him. But Cyrus' mother had more love&nbsp;
for Cyrus than for Arses upon his throne.

04:21:19.600 --> 04:21:25.840
When Darius died, his chosen heir,&nbsp;
Arses, became king and took on the

04:21:25.840 --> 04:21:33.279
throne name Artaxerxes II. But his&nbsp;
brother Cyrus would not be satisfied.

04:21:34.319 --> 04:21:42.960
Artaxerxes soon uncovered a plot by Cyrus&nbsp;
to kill him and take the throne for himself.

04:21:42.960 --> 04:21:52.239
Artaxerxes had his brother arrested and dragged&nbsp;
before the court to answer for himself. Everyone

04:21:52.239 --> 04:21:59.920
expected Cyrus to be executed for his crime,&nbsp;
but at the last moment, their mother intervened.

04:22:00.640 --> 04:22:09.680
She threw herself before the king and pleaded for&nbsp;
her favorite son's life. Artaxerxes laid hands

04:22:09.680 --> 04:22:15.600
upon Cyrus, desiring to put him to death,
but his mother made intercession for him,

04:22:15.600 --> 04:22:21.600
and instead he sent him back again in&nbsp;
safety to his province. Cyrus then,

04:22:21.600 --> 04:22:27.600
having so escaped through peril and dishonor,&nbsp;
fell to considering not only how he might avoid

04:22:27.600 --> 04:22:36.960
ever again being in his brother's power, but how,&nbsp;
if possible, he might become king in his stead.

04:22:36.960 --> 04:22:42.880
Back in his home province, Cyrus&nbsp;
began gathering an army in secret.

04:22:43.760 --> 04:22:49.840
This force would include 20,000 warriors&nbsp;
of his own, but he knew this wouldn't be

04:22:49.840 --> 04:23:01.040
enough. To supplement his forces, he hired 12,000&nbsp;
mercenaries. Of these, 10,000 were Greek hoplites

04:23:01.040 --> 04:23:08.800
come to sell their spears in Persia. With the&nbsp;
addition of these Greeks, the would-be usurper

04:23:08.800 --> 04:23:16.239
Cyrus now commanded the largest army of hoplites&nbsp;
anywhere in the world, twice the size of the

04:23:16.239 --> 04:23:26.960
Spartan army at the time. Among these 10,000&nbsp;
was the Greek writer and adventurer, Xenophon.

04:23:29.680 --> 04:23:39.760
Once the war began, Xenophon and his 10,000 men&nbsp;
marched across Persia under the command of Cyrus.

04:23:39.760 --> 04:23:46.560
On his journey, Xenophon was impressed by the&nbsp;
sights of the empire; among them, several pontoon

04:23:46.560 --> 04:23:55.200
bridges of the kind that the Persians excelled&nbsp;
in, and a number of Persian garden paradises.

04:23:56.720 --> 04:24:03.760
Thus, Cyrus set out from Sardis and marched&nbsp;
on and on through Lydia to the river Maeander.

04:24:03.760 --> 04:24:10.960
That river is 200 feet broad, but was spanned by&nbsp;
a bridge consisting of seven boats. Crossing it,

04:24:10.960 --> 04:24:17.600
he marched to Celaenae, a popular city, large&nbsp;
and prosperous. Here Cyrus owned a palace

04:24:17.600 --> 04:24:23.359
and a large park full of wild beasts, which&nbsp;
he used to hunt on horseback whenever he

04:24:23.359 --> 04:24:32.239
wished to give himself or his horses exercise.&nbsp;
Through the midst of the park flows the river.

04:24:32.239 --> 04:24:39.599
The usurper Cyrus finally met his brother&nbsp;
in battle at a place called Cunaxa.

04:24:39.600 --> 04:24:45.840
There, in the midst of the melee, he&nbsp;
saw the king Artaxerxes. Cyrus

04:24:45.840 --> 04:24:53.600
charged into the thick of the&nbsp;
fighting, as Xenophon describes.

04:24:53.600 --> 04:24:59.840
With the cry of “I see the man,” Cyrus rushed&nbsp;
upon him and struck him in the breast, and

04:24:59.840 --> 04:25:05.680
wounded him through his breastplate. While Cyrus&nbsp;
was delivering his stroke, however, someone hit

04:25:05.680 --> 04:25:11.439
him with a hard blow under the eye with a javelin;&nbsp;
and then followed a struggle between the king and

04:25:11.439 --> 04:25:19.279
Cyrus and the attendants who supported each&nbsp;
of them. While reeling from this wound, Cyrus

04:25:19.279 --> 04:25:27.439
was stabbed in the leg, and fell to the ground&nbsp;
where his head struck a stone, and he was killed.

04:25:28.399 --> 04:25:34.879
Xenophon's Greeks had carried themselves well&nbsp;
in the battle, but now with the usurper dead,

04:25:34.880 --> 04:25:42.560
his cause died with him. His army scattered&nbsp;
in all directions, and the Greeks had to flee

04:25:42.560 --> 04:25:49.520
back westwards as fast as they could,&nbsp;
with the Persians chasing close behind.

04:25:50.960 --> 04:25:59.120
The war of the brothers was over, but Artaxerxes’&nbsp;
reign, although a long one at forty-six years,

04:25:59.120 --> 04:26:06.800
was to be a troubled one. Egypt successfully&nbsp;
rebelled against him at the start of his rule,

04:26:06.800 --> 04:26:13.600
and his attempts to retake it would fail. In&nbsp;
fact, Egypt would leave the empire entirely

04:26:13.600 --> 04:26:22.560
for a full sixty years. This imperial failure&nbsp;
emboldened others, and soon further rebellions

04:26:22.560 --> 04:26:32.000
spread all around the empire. One of these,&nbsp;
known as the Great Satrap’s Revolt, saw western

04:26:32.000 --> 04:26:40.800
satrapies in Asia Minor such as Lydia, Armenia,&nbsp;
and Phrygia rise up against Artaxerxes' rule.

04:26:41.840 --> 04:26:50.560
Added to this, the Greeks of Sparta were now&nbsp;
aiding the rebels. The writer Diodorus Siculus

04:26:50.560 --> 04:27:00.399
writes about the situation the king faced as&nbsp;
the whole empire seemed to rise up in revolt.

04:27:00.399 --> 04:27:06.000
The inhabitants of the Asiatic coast revolted from&nbsp;
Persia, and some of the satraps and generals rising

04:27:06.000 --> 04:27:11.760
in insurrection made war on Artaxerxes.&nbsp;
At the same time, Tachos, the Egyptian king,

04:27:11.760 --> 04:27:17.279
decided to fight the Persians, and prepared&nbsp;
ships and gathered infantry forces. At one

04:27:17.279 --> 04:27:22.399
and the same time, he had to fight the Egyptian&nbsp;
king, the Greek cities of Asia, the Spartans,

04:27:22.399 --> 04:27:30.159
and the allies of these who had agreed upon making&nbsp;
common cause with them. To quell these rebellions,

04:27:30.159 --> 04:27:38.000
the king increasingly relied on the services of&nbsp;
mercenaries, many of them Greeks. Using these

04:27:38.000 --> 04:27:47.120
forces, he was able to put down the revolt by 362&nbsp;
BC, but each conflict was ruinously expensive,

04:27:47.120 --> 04:27:57.519
and the empire must have felt increasingly fragile&nbsp;
as the decades of the mid 4th century wore on.

04:27:57.520 --> 04:28:02.240
His son, Artaxerxes III,&nbsp;
carried on in this vein.

04:28:02.800 --> 04:28:11.279
He led one unsuccessful campaign to recapture&nbsp;
Egypt, but managed it on his second try. But

04:28:11.279 --> 04:28:20.880
Egypt by that point had had a taste of freedom, and&nbsp;
would never again sit happily within the empire.

04:28:20.880 --> 04:28:28.319
Due to their constant rebellions, Artaxerxes III&nbsp;
set about a reign of terror in Egypt, during which

04:28:28.319 --> 04:28:36.960
many were killed and temples were destroyed. He&nbsp;
raised taxes there to punishingly cruel amounts,

04:28:36.960 --> 04:28:44.720
hoping to impoverish the Egyptians and reduce&nbsp;
their ability to rebel. One Egyptian text

04:28:44.720 --> 04:28:53.760
known as the Demotic Chronicle seems to&nbsp;
record this time of hardship and cruelty.

04:28:53.760 --> 04:29:00.399
Our lakes and our islands are full of tears.&nbsp;
The houses of the people of Egypt don't have

04:29:00.399 --> 04:29:07.040
people to live in them. The Persians will massacre&nbsp;
them. They will take their houses and live there.

04:29:07.040 --> 04:29:16.159
They are massacring the people of Egypt while the&nbsp;
sun looks on. The Persian Empire had always ruled

04:29:16.159 --> 04:29:25.760
with a degree of compromise and consent from its&nbsp;
subjects, but now that era was coming to an end.

04:29:25.760 --> 04:29:34.000
But the end of the Persian Empire&nbsp;
would not come through rebellion.

04:29:34.000 --> 04:29:41.040
In the final years of Artaxerxes' reign, he&nbsp;
became concerned about the growing threat of one

04:29:41.040 --> 04:29:48.000
northerly Greek kingdom, one that was slowly&nbsp;
gathering power to itself and achieving what

04:29:48.000 --> 04:29:54.880
neither Athens nor Sparta had ever been able&nbsp;
to do; the near unification of Greece under

04:29:54.880 --> 04:30:20.239
a single king. That power was Macedon, and&nbsp;
the man who ruled it was named Philip.

04:30:20.239 --> 04:30:29.760
Macedon had once been a Persian subject. They had&nbsp;
helped King Xerxes during his invasion of Greece,

04:30:29.760 --> 04:30:35.600
but after the Persian withdrawal from Europe,&nbsp;
following their defeat at the battle of Plataea,

04:30:35.600 --> 04:30:44.080
Macedon was left to its own devices. It had&nbsp;
flourished as a Persian subject, and adopted

04:30:44.080 --> 04:30:49.519
elements of the Persian courtly&nbsp;
culture into its royal palaces.

04:30:50.880 --> 04:30:56.479
Although they spoke a dialect of Greek&nbsp;
and shared many aspects of Greek culture,

04:30:56.479 --> 04:31:04.080
the Macedonians were always considered outsiders&nbsp;
by the Athenians and other southern Greeks. They

04:31:04.080 --> 04:31:11.439
looked down on Macedonians as brash and rough, and&nbsp;
were shocked at their seemingly barbarian customs.

04:31:12.080 --> 04:31:18.880
They married multiple wives, drank their wine&nbsp;
without watering it down, and rode and hunted

04:31:18.880 --> 04:31:27.680
on horseback. In fact, the Macedonian cavalry was&nbsp;
among the most skilled in the region. The king of

04:31:27.680 --> 04:31:37.439
Macedon was a man named Philip II. He had become&nbsp;
king at the age of twenty-three at a time when the kingdom

04:31:37.439 --> 04:31:46.000
was struggling, faced with numerous powerful Greek&nbsp;
rivals. But over the next decades, he along with

04:31:46.000 --> 04:31:55.600
his generals and advisers continued a series&nbsp;
of rapid reforms that led to enormous success.

04:31:55.600 --> 04:32:04.240
A key part of this success was Philip's&nbsp;
reforming of the Macedonian army.

04:32:06.080 --> 04:32:12.000
For centuries, Greek soldiers had fought in&nbsp;
phalanxes, a formation where they locked their

04:32:12.000 --> 04:32:19.279
shields together and formed a bristling wall of&nbsp;
spears. The Greeks had used this formation to

04:32:19.279 --> 04:32:28.399
devastating effect on battlefields like Marathon&nbsp;and
Thermopylae. These spears were two to three meters in

04:32:28.399 --> 04:32:34.000
length, and since they were longer than the spears&nbsp;
used by the Persians, they had allowed Greek

04:32:34.000 --> 04:32:47.760
soldiers a crucial tactical advantage; allowing&nbsp;
multiple lines of men to engage the enemy at once.

04:32:47.760 --> 04:32:55.199
Philip's new idea was quite simple; to&nbsp;
make these spears even longer. In fact,

04:32:55.199 --> 04:33:02.319
they would be about as long as it was possible&nbsp;for
a man to carry, about five to seven meters in length,

04:33:02.319 --> 04:33:12.798
as tall as a lamp post. The Roman writer Polybius&nbsp;
describes the formation of these phalanxes.

04:33:12.799 --> 04:33:18.480
When the phalanx has its characteristic&nbsp;
virtue and strength, nothing can sustain

04:33:18.480 --> 04:33:24.959
its frontal attack or withstand the charge,&nbsp;
for since when it is closed up for action,

04:33:24.959 --> 04:33:32.080
the length of the pikes is sixteen cubits. Thus, each&nbsp;
man of the first rank must have the points of

04:33:32.080 --> 04:33:41.039
five pikes extending beyond him, each at&nbsp;
a distance of two cubits from the next.

04:33:41.039 --> 04:33:46.240
These spears would form a bristling&nbsp;
porcupine that was able to effortlessly

04:33:46.240 --> 04:33:52.320
hold enemy troops at bay, and while&nbsp;
the enemy was thus held in place,

04:33:52.320 --> 04:34:00.400
the Macedonian heavy cavalry would sweep&nbsp;
into their sides like a hammer on an anvil.

04:34:02.480 --> 04:34:09.599
This combination of pike and horse was so&nbsp;
effective that in little more than ten years,

04:34:09.600 --> 04:34:15.039
Philip of Macedon was able to conquer&nbsp;
a large area of mainland Greece, and

04:34:15.039 --> 04:34:21.039
even defeated the ancient cities&nbsp;
of Athens and Thebes. After that,

04:34:21.039 --> 04:34:25.680
he founded an alliance known&nbsp;
as the League of Corinth,

04:34:25.680 --> 04:34:36.000
a confederacy of Greek cities that recognized&nbsp;
Macedon and Philip as the ruler of all Greece.

04:34:36.000 --> 04:34:45.279
But Philip was not content. He believed that&nbsp;
across the sea, the empire of Persia was now a

04:34:45.279 --> 04:34:54.400
weakened edifice. It had expended its strength on&nbsp;
internal rebellions and civil wars, but had also

04:34:54.400 --> 04:35:02.000
grown complacent when it came to outside threats.&nbsp;
Their soldiers hadn't fought a battle against

04:35:02.000 --> 04:35:10.400
a foreign enemy in decades. Their tactics were&nbsp;
outdated, and their commanders were inexperienced.

04:35:11.119 --> 04:35:18.719
Meanwhile, the Macedonians had honed their&nbsp;
skills over years of combat within Greece.

04:35:18.719 --> 04:35:33.920
Now, with virtually all Greece united&nbsp;
around him, Philip set his sights on Asia.

04:35:33.920 --> 04:35:40.240
Whether King Artaxerxes III would have been&nbsp;
able to meet the disaster that was about to land

04:35:40.240 --> 04:35:47.039
on his shores, we will never know, since he&nbsp;
would meet his end in another episode of

04:35:47.039 --> 04:35:56.400
Persian court intrigue. In the year 338 BC,&nbsp;
a court eunuch called Bagoas plotted with the

04:35:56.400 --> 04:36:05.279
king's physician to poison him. After that, Bagoas&nbsp;
installed the king's youngest son on the throne,

04:36:05.279 --> 04:36:12.718
presumably intending to use him as a puppet. But&nbsp;
when the young boy wasn't as pliable as he hoped,

04:36:12.719 --> 04:36:22.799
he had him poisoned, too. Then Bagoas installed&nbsp;
a distant relative named Artashiyaata to rule.

04:36:23.359 --> 04:36:30.959
This man would take the throne name of Darius&nbsp;
III, and one of his first acts was quite wisely

04:36:30.959 --> 04:36:40.240
to have the poisoning eunuch Bagoas killed by&nbsp;
drinking his own poison. Darius was about forty-four

04:36:40.240 --> 04:36:47.519
years old when he came to the throne. As a young&nbsp;
man, he had distinguished himself as a warrior,

04:36:47.520 --> 04:36:53.920
once killing an enemy on the battlefield in&nbsp;
single combat, and had been awarded by being made

04:36:53.920 --> 04:37:02.000
the satrap of Armenia. But his warrior days were&nbsp;
now well behind him, and he had spent the last

04:37:02.000 --> 04:37:09.520
years as the head of the empire's postal service,&nbsp;
a distinguished but relatively peaceful position.

04:37:10.320 --> 04:37:16.799
He had come to the throne in peculiar and murky&nbsp;
circumstances, and people's faith in his rule

04:37:16.799 --> 04:37:27.600
must have been fragile. What Darius III needed was&nbsp;
time, time to shore up loyalty among his satraps,

04:37:27.600 --> 04:37:36.000
time to cement his hold on power in the empire,&nbsp;
time to ensure the quality of his fighting forces.

04:37:36.561 --> 04:37:45.199
But time was the one thing that Darius didn't&nbsp;
have. That's because on the other side of the sea,

04:37:45.199 --> 04:38:03.679
at the same time as the new king Darius was&nbsp;
being crowned, another assassination took place.

04:38:08.561 --> 04:38:15.119
In Macedon, in the capital of Aegae,&nbsp;
the Macedonian king Philip II was

04:38:15.119 --> 04:38:23.279
celebrating the wedding of one of his daughters.&nbsp;
Diodorus Siculus paints a picture of the scene.

04:38:24.480 --> 04:38:28.718
He wanted as many Greeks as possible&nbsp;
to take part in the festivities in

04:38:28.719 --> 04:38:34.000
honor of the gods, and so planned brilliant&nbsp;
musical contests and lavish banquets for

04:38:34.000 --> 04:38:40.719
his friends and guests. But as the praises&nbsp;
and congratulations of all rang in his ears,

04:38:40.719 --> 04:38:49.039
suddenly without warning, the plot against&nbsp;
the king was revealed as death struck.

04:38:49.039 --> 04:38:56.320
From the crowd, a man bearing&nbsp;
a dagger stepped forwards.

04:38:56.320 --> 04:38:59.920
When Philip directed his attending&nbsp;
friends to proceed him into the theater,

04:38:59.920 --> 04:39:04.879
while the guards kept their distance, he saw&nbsp;
that the king was left alone, rushed at him,

04:39:04.879 --> 04:39:13.199
pierced him through his ribs, and&nbsp;
stretched him out dead. According

04:39:13.199 --> 04:39:19.439
to ancient sources, this man killed Philip&nbsp;
because the king had failed to punish one of

04:39:19.439 --> 04:39:28.240
his vassals who had abused him. It was a story of&nbsp;
petty court rivalries and wounded honor, but the

04:39:28.240 --> 04:39:35.920
king's young son and heir believed differently.&nbsp;
He believed that his father had been killed by a

04:39:35.920 --> 04:39:43.840
trained assassin paid for by their great rivals&nbsp;
across the sea, the Persian Empire and the new

04:39:43.840 --> 04:39:54.160
King of Kings, Darius III. Now Philip's Macedonian&nbsp;
Empire and its revolutionary and battle-hardened

04:39:54.160 --> 04:40:01.519
army would pass on to his son, whose heart was&nbsp;
filled with rage and thoughts of vengeance,

04:40:02.320 --> 04:40:09.920
a young man of about twenty, whose name meant&nbsp;
‘defender of men’, from the Greek ‘alexein’,

04:40:09.920 --> 04:40:41.279
to defend, and ‘andros’, men. His name was&nbsp;
Alexandros, but we know him as Alexander.

04:40:52.480 --> 04:40:58.718
Just as with previous conquerors like&nbsp;
Cyrus the Great, the life of Alexander

04:40:58.719 --> 04:41:04.400
has been pieced together from incomplete&nbsp;
and fragmentary sources, all of them

04:41:04.400 --> 04:41:10.560
written down centuries after he was born,&nbsp;
and often far away in the Roman Empire,

04:41:11.119 --> 04:41:18.000
although some do draw on earlier&nbsp;
texts that have been lost.

04:41:18.000 --> 04:41:23.840
What we do know is that during the first&nbsp;
two years of his reign as King of Macedon,

04:41:23.840 --> 04:41:32.639
the young Alexander distinguished himself&nbsp;
for his ruthlessness and brutality.

04:41:32.639 --> 04:41:37.920
After the death of Philip, the cities of&nbsp;
southern Greece saw their opportunity for

04:41:37.920 --> 04:41:44.160
freedom from Macedonian control.&nbsp;
The city of Thebes broke out in

04:41:44.160 --> 04:41:53.119
open rebellion, and Alexander&nbsp;
marched south to crush them.

04:41:57.039 --> 04:42:03.840
Alexander had spent much of his youth accompanying&nbsp;
his father on campaign, and he was well-versed in

04:42:03.840 --> 04:42:11.520
the Macedonians’ innovative style of warfare. He&nbsp;
captured the city of Thebes and utterly destroyed

04:42:11.520 --> 04:42:20.240
it, massacring its population, and selling 30,000&nbsp;
of its people into slavery, as Diodorus of Sicily

04:42:20.240 --> 04:42:28.320
recounts. As the slaughter mounted and every&nbsp;
corner of the city was piled high with corpses,

04:42:28.320 --> 04:42:34.240
no one could have failed to pity the plight&nbsp;
of the unfortunates. So it was that many

04:42:34.240 --> 04:42:40.638
terrible things befell the city. Greeks were&nbsp;
mercilessly slain by Greeks. Relatives were

04:42:40.639 --> 04:42:46.481
butchered by their own relatives, and&nbsp;
even a common dialect induced no pity.

04:42:48.160 --> 04:42:54.719
The selling of Greeks into slavery was still&nbsp;
considered a great taboo, and it was a clear sign

04:42:54.719 --> 04:43:02.080
that Alexander intended to continue ruling&nbsp;
over Greece with an iron fist. In Thebes,

04:43:02.080 --> 04:43:07.359
Alexander left only the temples to&nbsp;
the gods standing, and reportedly a

04:43:07.359 --> 04:43:15.039
house that had once belonged to&nbsp;
the poet Pindar, whom he admired.

04:43:15.039 --> 04:43:20.719
With the rest of Greece now terrified&nbsp;
into line, Alexander set out on what

04:43:20.719 --> 04:43:28.320
had been his father's great ambition, a
full-scale invasion of the Persian Empire,

04:43:28.320 --> 04:43:37.279
now infused with all the impetuousness of&nbsp;
youth, as Diodoras of Sicily describes.

04:43:38.799 --> 04:43:43.680
The king returned with his army to Macedonia,&nbsp;
assembled his military commanders and his

04:43:43.680 --> 04:43:49.439
noblest friends, and posed for discussion the&nbsp;
plan for crossing over to Asia. His generals

04:43:49.439 --> 04:43:53.919
advised him to produce an heir first, and&nbsp;
then to turn his hand to so ambitious an

04:43:53.920 --> 04:44:05.039
enterprise. But Alexander was eager for&nbsp;
action, and opposed to any postponement.

04:44:05.039 --> 04:44:11.199
That Alexander was a young man who had never&nbsp;
lost a battle was reason enough for him to be

04:44:11.199 --> 04:44:18.480
confident, but all his life he had also been told&nbsp;
that he was descended from the mythical demigod

04:44:18.480 --> 04:44:27.199
Heracles through his father's line. He had also&nbsp;
grown up reading the stories of Homer's Iliad,

04:44:27.199 --> 04:44:33.359
a story of a great war in the East, and&nbsp;
he was inspired by the story of the great

04:44:33.359 --> 04:44:45.439
hero Achilles. All of this combined to make&nbsp;
him a man of singular and remorseless focus.

04:44:45.439 --> 04:44:51.519
In spring of 334 BC, Alexander&nbsp;
crossed the Hellespont with

04:44:51.520 --> 04:44:57.840
30 to 40,000 of Macedon's best warriors.

04:44:57.840 --> 04:45:03.920
When the local Persian satraps heard about the&nbsp;
arrival of this army, they gathered their own

04:45:03.920 --> 04:45:12.799
forces, along with a few thousand Greek mercenaries,&nbsp;
and went out to meet him. One Greek general from

04:45:12.799 --> 04:45:20.160
Rhodes, a man named Memnon, who, like Themistocles,&nbsp;
had come to Persia to seek his fortune,

04:45:20.160 --> 04:45:28.560
acted as an adviser to the western satraps. He&nbsp;
advised the Persians not to fight Alexander with

04:45:28.561 --> 04:45:35.920
their inexperienced forces, and instead to adopt&nbsp;
a scorched earth policy, luring his men into the

04:45:35.920 --> 04:45:46.160
interior and denying them any food or supplies,&nbsp;
as the Roman period writer Arrian recounts.

04:45:46.160 --> 04:45:51.199
Memnon, the Rhodian, advised them not to risk a&nbsp;
conflict with the Macedonians, since they were

04:45:51.199 --> 04:45:56.320
far superior to themselves in infantry, and&nbsp;
Alexander was there in person, whereas Darius

04:45:56.320 --> 04:46:01.840
was not with them. He advised them to advance&nbsp;
and destroy the fields by trampling them down

04:46:01.840 --> 04:46:07.359
under their horses’ hooves, to burn the crops&nbsp;
in the country, and not even to spare the very

04:46:07.359 --> 04:46:15.439
cities. For then, Alexander will not be able&nbsp;
to stay in the land from lack of provisions.

04:46:18.719 --> 04:46:24.320
The Persians, understandably reluctant&nbsp;
to burn their own people's property,

04:46:24.320 --> 04:46:31.279
refused. They met Alexander in&nbsp;
battle at the Granicus River,

04:46:31.279 --> 04:46:39.359
and there his experienced Macedonian spearmen&nbsp;
and hardened cavalry smashed the Persian force.

04:46:40.160 --> 04:46:46.719
Alexander allowed the Persian army to leave the&nbsp;
battlefield, but the Greek mercenaries who had

04:46:46.719 --> 04:46:53.039
fought on the Persian side he treated&nbsp;
with exceptional severity as traitors,

04:46:53.039 --> 04:47:00.480
as Arrian recounts. He soon completely&nbsp;
surrounded them and cut them up so that

04:47:00.480 --> 04:47:08.718
none of them escaped, except such as might have&nbsp;
concealed themselves among the dead bodies.

04:47:08.719 --> 04:47:12.719
From there he conquered all&nbsp;
the way through Asia Minor,

04:47:12.719 --> 04:47:22.080
capturing Greek cities like Ephesus, Miletus,&nbsp;
and Herodotus' hometown of Halicarnassus.

04:47:22.080 --> 04:47:26.240
The Persians likely assumed&nbsp;
that he would stop there,

04:47:26.240 --> 04:47:33.519
interested only in liberating the Greek-speaking&nbsp;
regions of the empire, but to their dismay,

04:47:33.520 --> 04:47:43.680
Alexander kept going. In autumn of 333 BC, he&nbsp;
marched through the Cilician gates and down

04:47:43.680 --> 04:47:54.400
into the region of Syria. Distraught, the Persian&nbsp;
king Darius III now marched to meet Alexander.

04:47:54.400 --> 04:48:00.240
He was able to surprise the Macedonian,&nbsp;
sweeping down on the rear of his ranks at

04:48:00.240 --> 04:48:10.080
a wide plain near a place called Issus,&nbsp;
now on the Syrian border with Turkey.

04:48:10.080 --> 04:48:18.719
Alexander swung around to prevent being&nbsp;
cut off, and the armies came together.

04:48:20.480 --> 04:48:27.519
At first, the Persians had great success. Darius&nbsp;
had brought with him a large number of Greek

04:48:27.520 --> 04:48:37.199
mercenaries, perhaps as many as 12,000 men, and&nbsp;
these fared well against the Macedonians. But at

04:48:37.199 --> 04:48:46.400
a crucial moment in the battle, Alexander made a&nbsp;
daring and impetuous gamble. He rode at the head

04:48:46.400 --> 04:48:54.718
of his cavalry and led them in a desperate charge&nbsp;
directly at Darius himself, ensconced in his royal

04:48:54.719 --> 04:49:02.799
bodyguard. It was a dangerous and unorthodox&nbsp;
move. Darius, seeing that he was the target

04:49:02.799 --> 04:49:11.039
of this charge, withdrew to a safer position,&nbsp;
but this withdrawal began a domino effect among

04:49:11.039 --> 04:49:20.639
the Persian lines. The historian Arrian recounts&nbsp;
what happened next. The Persians did not give way

04:49:20.639 --> 04:49:27.840
until they perceived that Darius had fled. Then&nbsp;
at last there ensued a decided flight, and on all

04:49:27.840 --> 04:49:33.520
sides. The horses of the Persians suffered&nbsp;
much injury in the retreat, and the horsemen

04:49:33.520 --> 04:49:39.520
themselves, being so many in number and retreating&nbsp;
in panicked terror without any regard to order along

04:49:39.520 --> 04:49:49.680
narrow roads, were trampled on and injured no&nbsp;
less by each other than by the pursuing enemy.

04:49:49.680 --> 04:49:58.719
The battle was a disaster. Darius barely escaped&nbsp;
with his life, and the Persian army was scattered

04:49:58.719 --> 04:50:08.639
in all directions. As a final devastating blow,&nbsp;
Alexander swept into Darius' camp and captured

04:50:08.639 --> 04:50:17.199
the women of his court; his mother, his wives,&nbsp;
and concubines. Humiliated and eager to plead

04:50:17.199 --> 04:50:25.279
for the safe return of his family, Darius sent an&nbsp;
envoy to Alexander, but the Macedonian refused to

04:50:25.279 --> 04:50:32.000
free the court women, and sent back the&nbsp;
following reply to the Persian king.

04:50:33.359 --> 04:50:38.798
Your ancestors invaded Macedonia and the rest&nbsp;
of Greece, and did us harm although we are not

04:50:38.799 --> 04:50:45.840
done you any previous injury. I have been&nbsp;
appointed commander and chief of the Greeks,

04:50:45.840 --> 04:50:54.561
and it is with the aim of punishing the&nbsp;
Persians that I have crossed into Asia.

04:50:54.561 --> 04:50:59.279
To many Greeks, this may have&nbsp;
appeared somewhat hypocritical,

04:50:59.279 --> 04:51:06.638
since Alexander himself had invaded much of Greece&nbsp;
alongside his father and had burned Thebes,

04:51:06.639 --> 04:51:17.119
one of its most ancient cities, to the ground.&nbsp;
Still, Alexander's list of accusations went on.

04:51:17.119 --> 04:51:22.000
My father died at the hands of&nbsp;
conspirators instigated by you.

04:51:22.799 --> 04:51:28.879
You sent unfriendly letters to the Greeks about&nbsp;
me to push them to war against me, and sent money

04:51:28.879 --> 04:51:36.240
to the Spartans and some other Greeks. But now I&nbsp;
have defeated in battle first your generals and

04:51:36.240 --> 04:51:44.638
satraps, and now you in person in your army, and&nbsp;
by the grace of the gods I control the country.

04:51:44.639 --> 04:51:52.320
Approach me therefore as the lord of all Asia. If&nbsp;
you wish to lay claim to the title of king, then

04:51:52.320 --> 04:52:07.920
stand your ground and fight for it. Do not take to&nbsp;
flight, as I shall pursue you wherever you may be.

04:52:07.920 --> 04:52:14.400
From there, Alexander marched through&nbsp;
Palestine, conquering cities as he went.

04:52:14.400 --> 04:52:20.480
He besieged the Phoenician island city&nbsp;
of Tyre, which held out for seven months,

04:52:20.480 --> 04:52:26.798
after which he ordered its population to&nbsp;
be massacred and 2,000 of its defenders

04:52:26.799 --> 04:52:34.320
to be crucified along the shoreline for daring to&nbsp;
hold out against him. This was an exceptionally

04:52:34.320 --> 04:52:42.879
brutal act by Greek standards, and few Persian&nbsp;
kings had ever used such a gruesome spectacle.

04:52:42.879 --> 04:52:50.080
In the town of Gaza, Alexander also slaughtered&nbsp;
every one of the 10,000 men in the city, and

04:52:50.080 --> 04:52:57.760
sold the women and children into slavery. When&nbsp;
the Persian commander refused to kneel to him,

04:52:57.760 --> 04:53:03.840
Alexander ordered that he be dragged behind&nbsp;
a horse until he died, a punishment likely

04:53:03.840 --> 04:53:11.680
inspired by Homer's Iliad, in which Achilles&nbsp;
drags the Trojan hero Hector behind his chariot.

04:53:14.240 --> 04:53:20.560
From there he marched into Egypt. There,&nbsp;
sources claim that he was welcomed with

04:53:20.561 --> 04:53:26.240
open arms since the relationship between&nbsp;
Egypt and Persia had soured so much in the

04:53:26.240 --> 04:53:33.760
preceding decades, but really, the Egyptians&nbsp;
had little choice. They had been largely

04:53:33.760 --> 04:53:40.400
disarmed after their recent rebellions, and&nbsp;
Alexander had made clear in Tyre and Gaza that

04:53:40.400 --> 04:53:48.160
he was willing to take revenge against&nbsp;
civilian populations who resisted him.

04:53:48.160 --> 04:53:53.279
In 332 BC, Alexander was crowned pharaoh in

04:53:53.279 --> 04:54:02.638
Memphis nearly two hundred years after&nbsp;
Cyrus the Great's son, Cambyses.

04:54:02.639 --> 04:54:10.561
After the wounding loss at Issus, Darius III&nbsp;
retreated to Babylon, and there began to gather

04:54:10.561 --> 04:54:20.879
an even more massive army. Seemingly as a ploy&nbsp;
to buy time, Darius sent Alexander an envoy,

04:54:20.879 --> 04:54:27.840
offering to surrender the western half of the&nbsp;
empire, everything beyond the river Euphrates

04:54:27.840 --> 04:54:36.480
to Alexander. But the Macedonian refused,&nbsp;
repeating once again that he was now king

04:54:36.480 --> 04:54:47.519
of all Asia, and that soon all of Darius' empire&nbsp;
would be his. The final decisive clash would occur

04:54:47.520 --> 04:54:59.840
in 331 BC, when Alexander set out again for&nbsp;
Mesopotamia to confront Darius III for good.

04:54:59.840 --> 04:55:05.920
On the 20th of September, ten days before&nbsp;
the battle, the Babylonian Astronomical

04:55:05.920 --> 04:55:16.879
Diaries record that an apocalyptic sign&nbsp;
appeared in the heavens just after sunset.

04:55:16.879 --> 04:55:24.000
On the 13th day of the month of Ululu, in the&nbsp;
fifth year of Darius, there was an eclipse

04:55:24.000 --> 04:55:32.719
of the moon, which was entirely darkened as&nbsp;
Jupiter set. Saturn was four fingers distant.

04:55:32.719 --> 04:55:39.920
As the eclipse became total, a westerly wind&nbsp;
was blowing. As the moon became visible again,

04:55:39.920 --> 04:55:51.119
an easterly wind arose. During the&nbsp;
eclipse, there were deaths and plagues.

04:55:51.119 --> 04:55:56.879
For the Macedonians, this celestial&nbsp;
event was an omen of victory,

04:55:56.879 --> 04:56:04.240
a sign that a great empire would soon&nbsp;
also be eclipsed. But for the Persians,

04:56:04.240 --> 04:56:13.840
the event was an omen of doom. The two armies met&nbsp;
at a small village named Gaugamela on the banks of

04:56:13.840 --> 04:56:25.039
the river Bumodus, near to modern-day Erbil in&nbsp;
northern Iraq, on the 1st of October 331 BC.

04:56:25.039 --> 04:56:27.119
During the battle that followed,

04:56:27.119 --> 04:56:35.599
despite being outnumbered, Alexander once&nbsp;
again prevailed, and Darius fled East.

04:56:38.639 --> 04:56:45.680
Now completely unopposed, Alexander marched to&nbsp;
Babylon, and the great city surrendered without

04:56:45.680 --> 04:56:56.879
a fight. He entered through the great Ishtar&nbsp;
Gate and down the processional way in triumph.

04:56:59.199 --> 04:57:07.039
The Roman period writer Curtius&nbsp;
Rufus describes this moment.

04:57:07.039 --> 04:57:12.400
Alexander put himself at the head of his&nbsp;
column, which he formed into a square, and

04:57:12.400 --> 04:57:18.638
ordered his men to advance into the city as if&nbsp;
they were going into battle. A large number of

04:57:18.639 --> 04:57:24.240
the Babylonians had taken up a position on the&nbsp;
walls, eager to have a view of their new king,

04:57:24.240 --> 04:57:30.799
but most went out to meet him. They had carpeted&nbsp;
the whole road with flowers and garlands, and set

04:57:30.799 --> 04:57:36.959
up at intervals on both sides silver altars&nbsp;
heaped not just with frankincense but with

04:57:36.959 --> 04:57:44.400
all manner of perfumes; herds of cattle and&nbsp;
horses, and lions, too, and leopards carried along

04:57:44.400 --> 04:57:53.599
in cages. Next came the Magi chanting a song&nbsp;
in their native fashion, and also musicians.

04:57:58.480 --> 04:58:05.519
Alexander and his men were astonished at the&nbsp;
sight of Babylon, by far the largest, wealthiest,

04:58:05.520 --> 04:58:11.920
and most well-developed city they had ever seen.

04:58:11.920 --> 04:58:17.359
It was the city itself, with its beauty and&nbsp;
antiquity, that commanded the attention not

04:58:17.359 --> 04:58:24.798
only of the king but of all the Macedonians.&nbsp;
Its wall is ten meters wide, and it is said that two

04:58:24.799 --> 04:58:31.199
chariots meeting on it can safely pass each&nbsp;
other. The two parts of the city are connected

04:58:31.199 --> 04:58:39.039
by a stone bridge over the river, and this is&nbsp;
also reckoned among the wonders of the East.

04:58:40.719 --> 04:58:45.600
The Macedonians, who had grown up in the&nbsp;
hardy mountains of northern Greece, were

04:58:45.600 --> 04:58:51.119
greatly affected by the sights of the&nbsp;
sophisticated and wealthy Persian Empire,

04:58:51.119 --> 04:59:00.799
and found Persian influences already taking&nbsp;
hold of them, as Diodorus of Sicily recounts,.

04:59:00.799 --> 04:59:06.639
Alexander began to imitate the Persian luxury&nbsp;
and the extravagant display of the kings of Asia.

04:59:06.639 --> 04:59:11.439
He put on the Persian diadem and dressed&nbsp;
himself in the white robe and the Persian

04:59:11.439 --> 04:59:17.439
sash and everything else except the trousers and&nbsp;
the long-sleeved upper garment. He distributed

04:59:17.439 --> 04:59:27.199
to his companions cloaks with purple borders,&nbsp;
and dressed the horses in Persian harness.

04:59:27.199 --> 04:59:35.199
Others feared that Alexander was less overcoming&nbsp;
Persia and more being overcome by it, as the

04:59:35.199 --> 04:59:43.279
Roman historian Curtius Rufus remarks. In the&nbsp;
whole camp, the feeling and the talk of all

04:59:43.279 --> 04:59:49.439
was that more had been lost by victory than had&nbsp;
been gained by war; that they themselves were

04:59:49.439 --> 04:59:59.119
conquered men when they had surrendered&nbsp;
themselves to alien and foreign habits.

05:00:04.879 --> 05:00:09.760
While Alexander reveled in his&nbsp;
victory and tried on new clothes,

05:00:09.760 --> 05:00:15.680
the Persian Emperor Darius fled ever&nbsp;
further eastwards up into the Iranian

05:00:15.680 --> 05:00:23.119
plateau. There, he hoped to gather another&nbsp;
army to stop the relentless advance of the

05:00:23.119 --> 05:00:38.639
Macedonians. And around him, the&nbsp;
Persian Empire began to collapse.

05:00:38.639 --> 05:00:50.080
After a month's stay in Babylon, around&nbsp;
November 331 BC, Alexander set out in pursuit.

05:00:50.080 --> 05:00:57.439
The fine Persian roads, dotted with wells,&nbsp;
waystations, and supply depots, had once been the

05:00:57.439 --> 05:01:05.839
empire's great strength, but now they became&nbsp;
a liability. Alexander and his men advanced

05:01:05.840 --> 05:01:12.160
rapidly along these highways, and were soon&nbsp;
at the foothills of the Zagros Mountains,

05:01:12.160 --> 05:01:18.639
the only obstacle now standing between&nbsp;
them and the capital of Persepolis.

05:01:21.359 --> 05:01:25.920
There, in a remarkable echo&nbsp;
of the Battle of Thermopylae,

05:01:25.920 --> 05:01:31.840
a Persian army under the command&nbsp;
of Ariobarzanes, the satrap of Parsa,

05:01:31.840 --> 05:01:40.719
staged a heroic defense in the mouth of&nbsp;
a narrow pass called the Persian Gates.

05:01:40.719 --> 05:01:47.359
The Persians held this pass for a full month,&nbsp;
during which time Alexander's soldiers were

05:01:47.359 --> 05:01:56.798
brought to a standstill and suffered heavy&nbsp;
losses. But just as Xerxes had 150 years earlier,

05:01:56.799 --> 05:02:02.400
the Macedonians eventually found a narrow&nbsp;
path through the mountains, and were able

05:02:02.400 --> 05:02:09.839
to surround the Persian defenders. The&nbsp;
path to the Persian capital was now open.

05:02:12.959 --> 05:02:21.920
In late January of 330 BC, four years after he had&nbsp;
landed in Asia, Alexander and his men arrived in

05:02:21.920 --> 05:02:31.680
Persepolis. The Greek writer Diodorus of Sicily&nbsp;
recounts the fine city that Alexander found.

05:02:33.119 --> 05:02:38.080
It was the richest city under the sun, and&nbsp;
the private houses had been furnished with

05:02:38.080 --> 05:02:43.119
every sort of wealth over the years. Many&nbsp;
of the houses belong to the common people,

05:02:43.119 --> 05:02:46.959
and were abundantly supplied with&nbsp;
furniture and wearing apparel of

05:02:46.959 --> 05:02:53.680
every kind. The citadel is a noteworthy&nbsp;
one, and is surrounded by a triple wall.

05:02:53.680 --> 05:02:59.520
Scattered about the royal terrace were residences&nbsp;
of the kings and quarters for the great generals,

05:02:59.520 --> 05:03:08.799
all luxuriously furnished, and buildings&nbsp;
suitably made for guarding the royal treasure.

05:03:08.799 --> 05:03:14.000
Perhaps in retribution for holding&nbsp;
out so long at the Persian Gates,

05:03:14.000 --> 05:03:21.840
Alexander ordered his soldiers to treat the people&nbsp;
of Persepolis much like those of Tyre and Gaza.

05:03:21.840 --> 05:03:33.199
They slaughtered all the men and enslaved all&nbsp;
the women. The palace they looted with impunity.

05:03:33.199 --> 05:03:39.359
Archaeology shows that they tore through&nbsp;
the halls of Persepolis in haste, ripping

05:03:39.359 --> 05:03:45.759
gold ornaments from the walls, and leaving&nbsp;
much behind scattered on the flagstones.

05:03:46.561 --> 05:03:52.719
Much of the fine stone tableware and everything&nbsp;
else too heavy to take with them, they simply

05:03:52.719 --> 05:04:00.879
smashed on the floor. After picking the palace&nbsp;
clean of every gold object they could carry,

05:04:00.879 --> 05:04:07.760
either deliberately or as a drunken accident,&nbsp;
according to some sources, Alexander then burned

05:04:07.760 --> 05:04:15.439
down the royal palace of the great king and&nbsp;
much of the city around it. The flames would

05:04:15.439 --> 05:04:23.759
have been visible for miles, and a great column of&nbsp;
black smoke would have climbed into the sky. The

05:04:23.760 --> 05:04:34.561
thick cedar rafters of the 100 columned halls&nbsp;
would have smoldered and finally fallen in.

05:04:34.561 --> 05:04:40.959
The gold looted from the treasuries&nbsp;
of Persepolis supposedly weighed 120,000

05:04:40.959 --> 05:04:52.240
talents, or nearly 4,000 tons. The Macedonians&nbsp;
needed thousands of camels to carry it away.

05:04:52.240 --> 05:04:57.599
This gold had been the treasury of the&nbsp;
empire that kept its well-oiled machine

05:04:57.600 --> 05:05:17.039
running, and in looting it, Alexander had&nbsp;
ripped the heart out of the Achaemenid system.

05:05:17.039 --> 05:05:22.639
Next, Alexander marched to Pasargadae,&nbsp;
where he briefly stopped at the

05:05:22.639 --> 05:05:27.680
tomb of Cyrus the Great, as Strabo describes.

05:05:29.920 --> 05:05:38.240
Alexander then went to Pasargadae, and this, too, was&nbsp;
an ancient royal residence. Here he saw also in a

05:05:38.240 --> 05:05:46.560
park the tomb of Cyrus. It was a small tower and&nbsp;
was concealed within the dense growth of trees.

05:05:46.561 --> 05:05:53.439
He passed through the entrance and saw a golden&nbsp;
couch, a table with cups, a golden coffin,

05:05:53.439 --> 05:05:59.279
and numerous garments and ornaments set&nbsp;
with precious stones, and that he saw all

05:05:59.279 --> 05:06:05.039
these things on his first visit, but that&nbsp;
on a later visit, the place had been robbed

05:06:05.039 --> 05:06:12.160
and everything had been carried off, and that the&nbsp;
robbers had removed the corpse to another place.

05:06:13.600 --> 05:06:20.320
If this is true, then it's clear that Persian&nbsp;
royal authority had by that point completely

05:06:20.320 --> 05:06:29.039
collapsed. From there, Alexander continued to&nbsp;
pursue Darius high up into the Iranian plateau,

05:06:29.039 --> 05:06:35.039
chasing him a distance of more than a thousand&nbsp;
kilometers across the winding roads of the Eastern

05:06:35.039 --> 05:06:45.039
Empire, but he would not catch him. Darius&nbsp;
III was eventually murdered by his own satrap,

05:06:45.039 --> 05:06:55.119
a man named Bessus, high in the hills near Ecbatana.&nbsp;
Bessus would name himself the new Achaemenid king,

05:06:55.119 --> 05:07:01.920
even taking the royal name Artaxerxes V, and&nbsp;
intending to raise an army in the eastern province

05:07:01.920 --> 05:07:09.600
of Bactria. But by this time, he controlled&nbsp;
only the easternmost quadrant of the empire,

05:07:09.600 --> 05:07:19.439
and his time would be short. Eventually Bessus was&nbsp;
captured, and Alexander, perhaps enraged that he had

05:07:19.439 --> 05:07:25.279
robbed him of the joy of killing Darius himself,&nbsp;
ordered the treacherous general to be flogged,

05:07:25.279 --> 05:07:34.320
mutilated, and finally killed in an ostentatious&nbsp;
display of cruelty. With the death of Bessus,

05:07:34.320 --> 05:07:42.240
Persia was now completely in the hands&nbsp;
of Alexander, but his men were exhausted,

05:07:42.240 --> 05:07:50.080
and it's clear that Alexander was beginning to&nbsp;
lose touch with reality. In his escapade across

05:07:50.080 --> 05:07:56.480
the collapsing empire, he had met with little&nbsp;
resistance, and he had begun to believe that he

05:07:56.480 --> 05:08:06.718
could conquer the entire world, as one anecdote&nbsp;
related in Plutarch's Moralia illustrates.

05:08:06.719 --> 05:08:11.760
It is reported that King Alexander the&nbsp;
Great, hearing Anaxarchus, the philosopher,

05:08:11.760 --> 05:08:18.240
discoursing that there were infinite worlds,&nbsp;
fell a weeping. “Have I not good cause to weep?”

05:08:18.240 --> 05:08:27.519
quoth he, “that being as there are an infinite&nbsp;
number of worlds, I'm not yet the lord of one?”

05:08:27.520 --> 05:08:31.680
Finally, Alexander reached the&nbsp;
easternmost border of the empire

05:08:31.680 --> 05:08:35.520
that he had destroyed, and even then, he wanted

05:08:35.520 --> 05:08:42.719
to keep on conquering. With the Himalayan&nbsp;
mountains rising blue in the far distance,

05:08:42.719 --> 05:08:52.080
he led an expedition into the Punjab in Northern&nbsp;
India, and here the adventure came to an end.

05:08:54.080 --> 05:08:59.039
Alexander's men were by that point used to&nbsp;
facing the scattered remnants of Persian

05:08:59.039 --> 05:09:04.320
resistance, but the moment they left&nbsp;
the old empire, they faced the strong

05:09:04.320 --> 05:09:14.000
independent kingdoms of India, and Alexander's&nbsp;
forces struggled, as Plutarch recounts.

05:09:14.000 --> 05:09:19.920
The combat in India was of a more mixed&nbsp;
kind, but maintained with such obstinacy

05:09:19.920 --> 05:09:25.439
that it was not decided ‘til the eighth&nbsp;
hour of the day. As for the Macedonians,

05:09:25.439 --> 05:09:30.718
this struggle blunted their courage and&nbsp;
stayed their further advance into India,

05:09:30.719 --> 05:09:36.000
for they were told that the kings of India&nbsp;
were awaiting them with 80,000 horsemen,

05:09:36.000 --> 05:09:45.920
200,000 footmen, 8,000 chariots,&nbsp;
and 6,000 fighting elephants.

05:09:45.920 --> 05:09:51.760
While Alexander may have styled himself&nbsp;
as the lord of all Asia, in reality,

05:09:51.760 --> 05:09:59.119
he had only defeated a single power, the&nbsp;
Achaemenid Empire, and inherited its ruins.

05:10:01.279 --> 05:10:09.439
Alexander eventually listened to reason and agreed&nbsp;
to turn back. On the return journey to Babylon,

05:10:09.439 --> 05:10:17.519
for unknown reasons, Alexander declined to use the&nbsp;
well-worn Persian road that led inland, and instead

05:10:17.520 --> 05:10:25.440
ordered his men to march through a waste known&nbsp;
as the Gedrosian Desert, now in modern Pakistan.

05:10:26.320 --> 05:10:33.279
Some sources claim he did this in order to punish&nbsp;
his men for refusing to continue on into India,

05:10:33.279 --> 05:10:40.240
whereas others say he wanted to complete another&nbsp;
glorious exploit like his ancestor Heracles to

05:10:40.240 --> 05:10:51.279
add to his growing legend. Either way, the route&nbsp;
was a disaster, as the writer Arrian describes.

05:10:51.279 --> 05:10:57.519
The blazing heat and the lack of water caused&nbsp;
innumerable casualties; of thirst or from the

05:10:57.520 --> 05:11:03.680
effects of the deep, burning, sun-baked sand.&nbsp;
Sometimes they met with lofty hills of sand,

05:11:03.680 --> 05:11:10.000
loose, deep sand into which they sank as if&nbsp;
it were mud or untrodden snow. The mules and

05:11:10.000 --> 05:11:15.359
horses suffered even greater distress from the&nbsp;
uneven and treacherous surface of the track.

05:11:17.279 --> 05:11:22.320
It was perhaps at this moment that&nbsp;
Alexander might have realized the debt he

05:11:22.320 --> 05:11:30.400
owed to the Persian road-builders who&nbsp;
had made his eastward journey so easy.

05:11:30.400 --> 05:11:36.000
The fact that they never knew when they would&nbsp;
find water made regular, normal marches impossible.

05:11:36.000 --> 05:11:41.520
Casualties among the animals were very numerous.&nbsp;
Often they were killed deliberately by the men,

05:11:41.520 --> 05:11:48.879
who butchered the mules and horses whenever&nbsp;
supplies gave out, and then ate their flesh.

05:11:48.879 --> 05:11:54.480
It was only through a stroke of luck that&nbsp;
the army was able to find the sea coast, and

05:11:54.480 --> 05:12:03.199
followed it west out of the desert and towards&nbsp;home.
By some reports, three-quarters of Alexander's men

05:12:03.199 --> 05:12:11.359
died on this stretch of the journey. In the&nbsp;
Gedrosian Desert, Alexander may have realized

05:12:11.359 --> 05:12:32.000
that it wasn't so easy conquering when someone&nbsp;
hadn't already done most of the work for you.

05:12:32.000 --> 05:12:38.639
But what had Alexander conquered? It was an&nbsp;
empire that he had no hope of successfully

05:12:38.639 --> 05:12:45.520
administrating, an empire made up of people who&nbsp;
didn't speak his language, held together by an

05:12:45.520 --> 05:12:52.480
administrative regime he didn't understand, and&nbsp;
by the promise of Persian safety, stability, and

05:12:52.480 --> 05:13:01.039
gold. Alexander didn't have any heirs since he had&nbsp;
left home as a young man and spent his whole adult

05:13:01.039 --> 05:13:11.519
life chasing glory across Asia. When he returned&nbsp;
to Babylon in April of 323 BC, weakened and

05:13:11.520 --> 05:13:20.959
exhausted from his journey across the Gedrosian
Desert, Alexander didn't have long left to live.

05:13:20.959 --> 05:13:27.840
Our story began in the city of Babylon, with its&nbsp;
rebellion against the Assyrian Empire, and it's

05:13:27.840 --> 05:13:36.480
in this city that our story will also end. In&nbsp;
June, just two months after returning to Babylon,

05:13:36.480 --> 05:13:44.638
Alexander sickened and died, refusing to&nbsp;
name a successor. The territory that had

05:13:44.639 --> 05:13:50.400
once been the Persian Empire, the largest&nbsp;
and wealthiest the world had ever known,

05:13:50.400 --> 05:13:57.599
was carved up among his generals. These&nbsp;
generals and their descendants would spend

05:13:57.600 --> 05:14:07.119
the next two hundred years fighting amongst
one another, as Diodorus of Sicily recalls.

05:14:07.119 --> 05:14:11.359
When he was quitting life in Babylon,&nbsp;
and that his last breath was asked by

05:14:11.359 --> 05:14:16.560
his friends to whom he was leaving the&nbsp;
kingdom, he said, "To the best man,

05:14:16.561 --> 05:14:21.440
for I foresee that a great combat of&nbsp;
my friends will be my funeral games."

05:14:22.160 --> 05:14:25.840
This actually happened, for&nbsp;
after the death of Alexander,

05:14:25.840 --> 05:14:38.639
the foremost of his friends quarreled about&nbsp;
the primacy and joined in many great combats.

05:14:38.639 --> 05:14:45.279
With these wars, the descendants of the Macedonian&nbsp;
conquerors would try to put back together what

05:14:45.279 --> 05:14:53.519
they had broken to reunify an empire that had&nbsp;
ruled in stability for more than two centuries,

05:14:53.520 --> 05:15:02.480
but none of them would succeed. Before long, the&nbsp;
Achaemenid Persian Empire was all but forgotten,

05:15:02.480 --> 05:15:07.919
except as the villains in the stories that the&nbsp;
Greeks still told themselves in their streets

05:15:07.920 --> 05:15:16.000
and theaters. The language of Old Persian would&nbsp;
gradually pass out of use, along with the use of

05:15:16.000 --> 05:15:22.480
cuneiform, and as the centuries went by, people&nbsp;
forgot how to read the inscriptions still carved

05:15:22.480 --> 05:15:31.519
into the palaces and pillars, into the stones and&nbsp;
cliff faces of the Iranian mountains. The empires

05:15:31.520 --> 05:15:38.719
that followed, the Cassenians and the Parthians,
drew their lineages back to a mythical Iranian

05:15:38.719 --> 05:15:45.920
heritage, but the legacy of the Achaemenids&nbsp;
was remembered only in the tiniest fragments.

05:15:48.879 --> 05:15:56.400
While some Achaemenid cities like Susa and Ecbatana&nbsp;
continued to be important population centers in

05:15:56.400 --> 05:16:04.798
later periods, others saw a more rapid&nbsp;
decline. The garden city of Pasargadae,

05:16:04.799 --> 05:16:12.959
always more of a royal complex than a true city,&nbsp;
was rapidly abandoned. Its blooming parkland would

05:16:12.959 --> 05:16:19.920
have overgrown with scrub and weeds, its water&nbsp;
channels filled with silt and finally stopped

05:16:19.920 --> 05:16:26.719
working entirely. Its imported trees and&nbsp;
shrubs would have died, and before long,

05:16:26.719 --> 05:16:38.799
the once paradise of the Persian kings would&nbsp;
have blown away with the loose layer of top soil.

05:16:38.799 --> 05:16:45.920
The blackened ruin of the palaces at Persepolis&nbsp;
would stand for some time over the city, and

05:16:45.920 --> 05:16:52.799
over the following centuries it would decline&nbsp;
steadily. Eventually it was little more than a

05:16:52.799 --> 05:17:01.039
village, and then the people left entirely.&nbsp;
Sand and earth would soon blow over the

05:17:01.039 --> 05:17:10.480
slowly crumbling stones of the palace that still&nbsp;
bore the following inscription. King of Kings,

05:17:10.480 --> 05:17:30.798
king of countries containing many kinds of&nbsp;
men, king in this great earth far and wide.

05:17:30.799 --> 05:17:37.840
In 1906, the American scholar of&nbsp;
Iranian languages, A.V. Williams Jackson,

05:17:37.840 --> 05:17:45.359
traveled through Persia and visited&nbsp;
the site of Pasargadae. There, he wrote

05:17:45.359 --> 05:17:51.359
the following description of its&nbsp;
wasted and melancholy appearance.

05:17:53.039 --> 05:18:03.279
Pasargadae and Persepolis are sad themes, for&nbsp;
both are silent cities of a dead past. Cyrus

05:18:03.279 --> 05:18:11.359
and Darius still remain in effigy of stone, and&nbsp;
the vestiges of royal halls, untenanted for

05:18:11.359 --> 05:18:20.000
more than 2,000 years, bear witness to the&nbsp;
departed splendor of a period of grandeur.

05:18:22.160 --> 05:18:33.680
To Jackson, the ruins appeared as reminders of the&nbsp;
fearsome power of time. Here ruin reigns supreme,

05:18:33.680 --> 05:18:41.200
and even the tombs that housed the bodies of&nbsp;
the dead kings have been crumbling for ages.

05:18:41.920 --> 05:18:46.400
Time's relentless touch has worn&nbsp;
away the clear-cut features of

05:18:46.400 --> 05:18:53.039
these monuments and destroyed the beauty&nbsp;
of their lineaments, yet they still endure

05:18:53.039 --> 05:19:03.600
to mark daily by their shadows the advance&nbsp;
of centuries across the dial of eternity.

05:19:03.600 --> 05:19:08.401
Williams Jackson also visited&nbsp;
the tomb of Cyrus the Great.

05:19:09.119 --> 05:19:17.920
He even stepped inside its inner chamber, but&nbsp;
what he found disappointed him. The condition

05:19:17.920 --> 05:19:26.400
of the royal chamber is not what it once was.&nbsp;
Innumerable graffiti cover the walls; but most

05:19:26.400 --> 05:19:33.439
inharmonious of all, for it hung all over the&nbsp;
place where the body must have lain, was a cord

05:19:33.439 --> 05:19:41.519
with an incongruous collection of worthless trash&nbsp;
in the way of votive offerings; a piece of rag,

05:19:41.520 --> 05:19:52.879
a bit of brass, a fragment of a lamp, a bell, a&nbsp;
copper ring, and whatnot made up the motley string.

05:19:56.000 --> 05:20:00.719
He turned to leave, but as he did, for a moment,

05:20:00.719 --> 05:20:06.160
the ancient power of the site&nbsp;
reasserted itself, and for a moment,

05:20:06.160 --> 05:20:19.199
he felt connected to the monumental nature&nbsp;
of the history that had happened here.

05:20:19.199 --> 05:20:26.959
As I slowly descended the deep steps and mounted&nbsp;
my horse, the sun sank low behind the western

05:20:26.959 --> 05:20:38.480
hills. I turned for a last look at the historic&nbsp;
shrine. A vision seemed to rise before my view,

05:20:38.480 --> 05:20:47.279
and I saw in fancy the scene of the last rites of&nbsp;
the great king. I still could hear the tramplings

05:20:47.279 --> 05:20:53.439
of the horses that led the funeral train. The&nbsp;
measured tread of the soldiers in clanking

05:20:53.439 --> 05:21:01.039
armor rang dully on my ear, and the chanting&nbsp;
voice of the Magian priest intoning perchance

05:21:01.039 --> 05:21:12.639
the Zoroastrian psalm ‘Kam nemoi zaam’, ‘to what land am
I going?’ beat rhythmically through my brain. Then the

05:21:12.639 --> 05:21:37.119
shroud of darkness fell like a pall upon the plain,&nbsp;
and the moon rose slowly over the distant hills.

05:21:41.920 --> 05:21:49.119
The Athenian playwright Aeschylus fought the&nbsp;
Persians for much of his life. He had been

05:21:49.119 --> 05:21:56.080
a hoplite at the battle of Marathon when he&nbsp;
was around thirty-five years old, and fought again

05:21:56.080 --> 05:22:02.480
ten years later at the sea battle of Salamis,&nbsp;
and the final decisive confrontation of

05:22:02.480 --> 05:22:10.320
Platea. He would be remembered to history as&nbsp;
the father of Greek tragedy and the writer

05:22:10.320 --> 05:22:17.439
of more than seventy plays, of which only&nbsp;
seven have survived. But when he died,

05:22:17.439 --> 05:22:22.400
he wanted to be remembered not for his&nbsp;
writing, but for the part he had played

05:22:22.400 --> 05:22:33.679
on the battlefield. On his gravestone, he&nbsp;
asked that the following inscription be left.

05:22:53.359 --> 05:23:00.240
Beneath this stone lies Aeschylus, son of&nbsp;
Euphorion the Athenian, who perished in the

05:23:00.240 --> 05:23:07.840
wheat-bearing land of Gela. Of his noble&nbsp;
prowess the grove of Marathon can speak,

05:23:07.840 --> 05:23:16.080
and the long-haired Persian knows it well.

05:23:16.080 --> 05:23:22.000
But despite his pride in the part he had&nbsp;
taken in these battles, Aeschylus also knew

05:23:22.000 --> 05:23:30.400
the horrors of war. While his plays glorified&nbsp;
Greek victories, they also gave voice to his

05:23:30.400 --> 05:23:37.279
Persian enemies and asked his audience to&nbsp;
extend the hand of humanity to the Persian

05:23:37.279 --> 05:23:45.920
men who had died on the beaches and in the fields&nbsp;
of Greece for the vanity of kings. In his play

05:23:45.920 --> 05:23:52.561
The Persians, he offers a kind of lament&nbsp;
for all those who had died in these wars.

05:23:53.279 --> 05:24:00.400
This lament now stands as a kind of epitaph
for the entire Persian Empire, as its palaces

05:24:00.400 --> 05:24:14.560
stood in ruins, its peoples scattered, and&nbsp;
the sun finally set on the Achaemenid world.

05:24:14.561 --> 05:24:25.119
True guardians are we of many a temple rich in&nbsp;
gold and holy, whom our lord and king, for age and

05:24:25.119 --> 05:24:36.240
honor has extolled to watch his land forlorn.&nbsp;
For all the strength of Asia born, like hounds

05:24:36.240 --> 05:24:50.080
at a young master's horn, baying, away has flown,&nbsp;
and now for long no royal post comes, no rider

05:24:50.080 --> 05:25:01.359
from the host; back to great Persia's throne&nbsp;
from Agbatan, from Susa tall, from ancient Kissia’s

05:25:01.359 --> 05:25:13.279
guarded wall, we saw the horse and chariot go, the&nbsp;
gliding ships, the footmen slow; so has the flower

05:25:13.279 --> 05:25:22.959
of Persia's youth departed, and in fierce&nbsp;
longing full many a wife and mother staying,

05:25:22.959 --> 05:25:31.520
waiting as day still follows day,&nbsp;
and dread the lengthening delay.

05:25:31.520 --> 05:25:45.760
Therefore does my spirit mourn, robed in darkness,&nbsp;
racked with fear. Lest a cry the people hear; “Woe, woe;

05:25:45.760 --> 05:25:59.039
woe for Persia's host forlorn,” ringing through&nbsp;
the wide, empty streets of Susa's lonely land.

